{"title_page": "Pyrocephalus", "text_new": "{{short description|Genus of birds in the tyrant flycatcher family}}\n{{Automatic Taxobox\n| image = Vermilion flycatcher (Pyrocephalus rubinus) male 2.JPG\n| image_caption = [[Scarlet flycatcher]] (''Pyrocephalus rubinus'')\n| taxon = Pyrocephalus\n| authority = [[John Gould|Gould]], 1839\n}}\n\n'''''Pyrocephalus''''' is a [[genus]] of bird in the tyrant flycatcher family [[Tyrannidae]].\n\nThe genus was introduced by the English ornithologist and bird artist [[John Gould]] in 1839 in [[Charles Darwin]]'s ''[[Zoology of the Voyage of H.M.S. Beagle]]''.<ref>{{ cite book | last=Gould | first=John | author-link=John Gould | editor-last=Darwin | editor-first=Charles | editor-link=Charles Darwin | year=1841 | title=The Zoology of the Voyage of H.M.S. Beagle, Part III. Birds | location=London | publisher=Smith, Elder and Company | page=44 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/40300059 }}</ref>{{efn|Some taxonomists date the publication to 1838.<ref>{{ cite book | editor-last1=Dickinson | editor-first1=E.C. | editor1-link=Edward C. Dickinson  | editor-last2=Christidis | editor-first2=L. | editor2-link=Leslie Christidis | year=2014 | title=The Howard & Moore Complete Checklist of the Birds of the World | volume=Volume 2: Passerines | edition=4th | place=Eastbourne, UK | publisher=Aves Press | isbn=978-0-9568611-2-2 | page=58 }}</ref> Although the title page to ''Aves. Part III'' is dated 1841, the volume was issued in five parts. Page 44 containing the text was issued in 1839 but plates VI and VII were issued in 1838 and have captions that include the generic name ''Pyrocephalus''.<ref>{{ cite journal | last1=Steinheimer | first1=F. | last2=Dickinson | first2=E.C. | last3=Walters | first3=M.P. | year=2006 | title=''The Zoology of the Voyage of H.M.S. Beagle, Part III. Birds.'' New avian names, their authorship and the dates | journal=Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club | volume=126 | issue=2 | pages=171\u2013193 [184]| doi= | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/40884106 }}</ref><ref>{{ cite book | last1=Dickinson | first1=E.C. | author1-link=Edward C. Dickinson | last2=Overstreet | first2=L.K. | last3=Dowsett | first3=R.J. | last4=Bruce | first4=M.D. | year=2011 | title=Priority! The Dating of Scientific Names in Ornithology: a Directory to the literature and its reviewers | location=Northampton, UK | publisher=Aves Press | isbn=978-0-9568611-1-5 | page=98 | url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/267763194 }}</ref> }} The [[type species]] was designated as the [[scarlet flycatcher]] (''Pyrocephalus rubinus'') by the English zoologist [[George Robert Gray]] in 1840.<ref>{{ cite book | last=Gray | first=George Robert | author-link=George Robert Gray | year=1840 | title=A List of the Genera of Birds : with an Indication of the Typical Species of Each Genus | place=London | publisher=R. and J.E. Taylor | page=30 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14500926 }}</ref><ref>{{ cite book | editor-last=Traylor | editor-first=Melvin A. Jr | author-link=Melvin Alvah Traylor Jr. | year=1979 | title=Check-list of Birds of the World | volume=Volume 8 | publisher=Museum of Comparative Zoology  | place=Cambridge, Massachusetts  | pages=149\u2013150 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/50637 }}</ref> The name ''Pyrocephalus'' combines the [[Ancient Greek]] ''purrhos'' meaning \"flame-coloured\" or \"red\" and ''-kephalos'' meaning \"-headed\".<ref>{{cite book | last=Jobling | first=James A. | year=2010| title=The Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names | publisher=Christopher Helm | location=London | isbn=978-1-4081-2501-4 | page=326 }}</ref>\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nThe [[tyrant flycatcher]] family, the Tyrannidae, is a group of [[passerine]] birds present only in the [[New World]], and its members are generally drab in coloration.<ref name=\"HBW9\">del Hoyo, J. Elliott, A. & Christie, D. (editors). (2004) ''Handbook of the Birds of the World. Volume 9: Cotingas to Pipits and Wagtails''. Lynx Edicions. {{ISBN|84-87334-69-5}}</ref> Within it, the subfamily Fluvicolinae comprises the genuses ''[[Pyrocephalus]]'', ''[[Contopus]]'', ''[[Empidonax]]'', and ''[[Sayornis]]''. They likely shared a common ancestor in the ''[[Contopus]]'' or ''[[Xenotriccus]]'' genus before diversifying. The ''Pyrocephalus'' are most closely related to the ''Sayornis'' in terms of [[Morphology (biology)|morphology]], but genetic analysis shows that they may be more closely related to the ''[[Fluvicola]]''.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Ellison|first=Kevin|last2=Wolf|first2=Blair|last3=Jones|first3=Stephanie|date=March 2020|editor-last=Poole|editor-first=A. F.|title=Vermilion Flycatcher (Pyrocephalus rubinus), version 1.0|url=https://birdsoftheworld.org/bow/species/verfly/cur/introduction|url-status=live|language=en|publisher=[[Cornell Lab of Ornithology]]|doi=10.2173/bow.verfly.01|url-access=subscription|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15|website=birdsoftheworld.org}}</ref> The vermilion flycatcher likely evolved around 1.15&#x2013;million years ago (mya), with the species on the [[Gal\u00e1pagos Islands]] having split off around 0.82&#x2013;mya. The South American species/subspecies diverged about 0.56&#x2013;mya.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Carmi|first=Ore|last2=Witt|first2=Christopher C.|last3=Jaramillo|first3=Alvaro|last4=Dumbacher|first4=John P.|date=2016-09-01|title=Phylogeography of the Vermilion Flycatcher species complex: Multiple speciation events, shifts in migratory behavior, and an apparent extinction of a Gal\u00e1pagos-endemic bird species|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|language=en|volume=102|pages=152\u2013173|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2016.05.029|issn=1055-7903|pmid=27233443|doi-access=free}}</ref> \n\n==Species==\nThe genus contains contains four species:<ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | year=2019 | title=Tyrant flycatchers | work=World Bird List Version 9.2 | url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/flycatchers/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | accessdate=29 June 2019 }}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Image !! Scientific name !! Common Name !! Distribution \n|-\n|[[File:Pyrocephalus rubinus Titirib\u00ed pechirrojo Vermilion Flycatcher (male) (17321352426).jpg|120px]] || ''Pyrocephalus rubinus'' ||[[Scarlet flycatcher]]||southeastern Bolivia and Brazil, Paraguay to Argentina and Uruguay.\n|-\n|[[File:Pyrocephalus rubinus 1.jpg|120px]] || ''Pyrocephalus obscurus''  ||[[Vermilion flycatcher]] ||almost all of Mexico; it extends north into the southwestern United States, and south to scattered portions of Central America, parts of northwestern and central South America\n|-\n|[[File:Flycatcher1.jpg|120px]] || ''Pyrocephalus nanus''  ||[[Darwin's flycatcher]]||the Gal\u00e1pagos Islands.\n|-\n| ||\u271d''Pyrocephalus dubius''  ||[[San Crist\u00f3bal flycatcher]]||San Crist\u00f3bal Island in the Gal\u00e1pagos Islands. \n|-\n|}\n\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q15881075}}\n\n[[Category:Pyrocephalus]]\n[[Category:Bird genera]]\n\n{{Tyrannidae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Genus of birds in the tyrant flycatcher family}}\n{{Automatic Taxobox\n| image = Vermilion flycatcher (Pyrocephalus rubinus) male 2.JPG\n| image_caption = [[Scarlet flycatcher]] (''Pyrocephalus rubinus'')\n| taxon = Pyrocephalus\n| authority = [[John Gould|Gould]], 1839\n}}\n\n'''''Pyrocephalus''''' is a [[genus]] of bird in the tyrant flycatcher family [[Tyrannidae]].\n\nThe genus was introduced by the English ornithologist and bird artist [[John Gould]] in 1839 in [[Charles Darwin]]'s ''[[Zoology of the Voyage of H.M.S. Beagle]]''.<ref>{{ cite book | last=Gould | first=John | author-link=John Gould | editor-last=Darwin | editor-first=Charles | editor-link=Charles Darwin | year=1841 | title=The Zoology of the Voyage of H.M.S. Beagle, Part III. Birds | location=London | publisher=Smith, Elder and Company | page=44 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/40300059 }}</ref>{{efn|Some taxonomists date the publication to 1838.<ref>{{ cite book | editor-last1=Dickinson | editor-first1=E.C. | editor1-link=Edward C. Dickinson  | editor-last2=Christidis | editor-first2=L. | editor2-link=Leslie Christidis | year=2014 | title=The Howard & Moore Complete Checklist of the Birds of the World | volume=Volume 2: Passerines | edition=4th | place=Eastbourne, UK | publisher=Aves Press | isbn=978-0-9568611-2-2 | page=58 }}</ref> Although the title page to ''Aves. Part III'' is dated 1841, the volume was issued in five parts. Page 44 containing the text was issued in 1839 but plates VI and VII were issued in 1838 and have captions that include the generic name ''Pyrocephalus''.<ref>{{ cite journal | last1=Steinheimer | first1=F. | last2=Dickinson | first2=E.C. | last3=Walters | first3=M.P. | year=2006 | title=''The Zoology of the Voyage of H.M.S. Beagle, Part III. Birds.'' New avian names, their authorship and the dates | journal=Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club | volume=126 | issue=2 | pages=171\u2013193 [184]| doi= | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/40884106 }}</ref><ref>{{ cite book | last1=Dickinson | first1=E.C. | author1-link=Edward C. Dickinson | last2=Overstreet | first2=L.K. | last3=Dowsett | first3=R.J. | last4=Bruce | first4=M.D. | year=2011 | title=Priority! The Dating of Scientific Names in Ornithology: a Directory to the literature and its reviewers | location=Northampton, UK | publisher=Aves Press | isbn=978-0-9568611-1-5 | page=98 | url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/267763194 }}</ref> }} The [[type species]] was designated as the [[scarlet flycatcher]] (''Pyrocephalus rubinus'') by the English zoologist [[George Robert Gray]] in 1840.<ref>{{ cite book | last=Gray | first=George Robert | author-link=George Robert Gray | year=1840 | title=A List of the Genera of Birds : with an Indication of the Typical Species of Each Genus | place=London | publisher=R. and J.E. Taylor | page=30 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14500926 }}</ref><ref>{{ cite book | editor-last=Traylor | editor-first=Melvin A. Jr | author-link=Melvin Alvah Traylor Jr. | year=1979 | title=Check-list of Birds of the World | volume=Volume 8 | publisher=Museum of Comparative Zoology  | place=Cambridge, Massachusetts  | pages=149\u2013150 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/50637 }}</ref> The name ''Pyrocephalus'' combines the [[Ancient Greek]] ''purrhos'' meaning \"flame-coloured\" or \"red\" and ''-kephalos'' meaning \"-headed\".<ref>{{cite book | last=Jobling | first=James A. | year=2010| title=The Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names | publisher=Christopher Helm | location=London | isbn=978-1-4081-2501-4 | page=326 }}</ref>\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nThe [[tyrant flycatcher]] family, the Tyrannidae, is a group of [[passerine]] birds present only in the [[New World]], and its members are generally drab in coloration.<ref name=\"HBW9\">del Hoyo, J. Elliott, A. & Christie, D. (editors). (2004) ''Handbook of the Birds of the World. Volume 9: Cotingas to Pipits and Wagtails''. Lynx Edicions. {{ISBN|84-87334-69-5}}</ref> Within it, the subfamily Fluvicolinae comprises the genuses ''[[Pyrocephalus]]'', ''[[Contopus]]'', ''[[Empidonax]]'', and ''[[Sayornis]]''. They likely shared a common ancestor in the ''[[Contopus]]'' or ''[[Xenotriccus]]'' genus before diversifying. The ''Pyrocephalus'' are most closely related to the the ''Sayornis'' in terms of [[Morphology (biology)|morphology]], but genetic analysis shows that they may be more closely related to the ''[[Fluvicola]]''.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Ellison|first=Kevin|last2=Wolf|first2=Blair|last3=Jones|first3=Stephanie|date=March 2020|editor-last=Poole|editor-first=A. F.|title=Vermilion Flycatcher (Pyrocephalus rubinus), version 1.0|url=https://birdsoftheworld.org/bow/species/verfly/cur/introduction|url-status=live|language=en|publisher=[[Cornell Lab of Ornithology]]|doi=10.2173/bow.verfly.01|url-access=subscription|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15|website=birdsoftheworld.org}}</ref> The vermilion flycatcher likely evolved around 1.15&#x2013;million years ago (mya), with the species on the [[Gal\u00e1pagos Islands]] having split off around 0.82&#x2013;mya. The South American species/subspecies diverged about 0.56&#x2013;mya.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Carmi|first=Ore|last2=Witt|first2=Christopher C.|last3=Jaramillo|first3=Alvaro|last4=Dumbacher|first4=John P.|date=2016-09-01|title=Phylogeography of the Vermilion Flycatcher species complex: Multiple speciation events, shifts in migratory behavior, and an apparent extinction of a Gal\u00e1pagos-endemic bird species|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|language=en|volume=102|pages=152\u2013173|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2016.05.029|issn=1055-7903|pmid=27233443|doi-access=free}}</ref> \n\n==Species==\nThe genus contains contains four species:<ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | year=2019 | title=Tyrant flycatchers | work=World Bird List Version 9.2 | url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/flycatchers/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | accessdate=29 June 2019 }}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Image !! Scientific name !! Common Name !! Distribution \n|-\n|[[File:Pyrocephalus rubinus Titirib\u00ed pechirrojo Vermilion Flycatcher (male) (17321352426).jpg|120px]] || ''Pyrocephalus rubinus'' ||[[Scarlet flycatcher]]||southeastern Bolivia and Brazil, Paraguay to Argentina and Uruguay.\n|-\n|[[File:Pyrocephalus rubinus 1.jpg|120px]] || ''Pyrocephalus obscurus''  ||[[Vermilion flycatcher]] ||almost all of Mexico; it extends north into the southwestern United States, and south to scattered portions of Central America, parts of northwestern and central South America\n|-\n|[[File:Flycatcher1.jpg|120px]] || ''Pyrocephalus nanus''  ||[[Darwin's flycatcher]]||the Gal\u00e1pagos Islands.\n|-\n| ||\u271d''Pyrocephalus dubius''  ||[[San Crist\u00f3bal flycatcher]]||San Crist\u00f3bal Island in the Gal\u00e1pagos Islands. \n|-\n|}\n\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q15881075}}\n\n[[Category:Pyrocephalus]]\n[[Category:Bird genera]]\n\n{{Tyrannidae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pyrocephalus"}
{"title_page": "Don Scott (Virginia politician)", "text_new": "{{short description|Virginia house of representatives member}}\n{{ Infobox officeholder\n| birthname =\n| name = Don Scott\n| image =\n| caption =\n| state_delegate = Virginia\n| district = [[Virginia's 80th House of Delegates district|80th]]\n| term_start = January 8, 2020\n| term_end = \n| preceded = [[Matthew James (politician)|Matthew James]]\n| succeeded = \n| birth_date =\n| birth_place =\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse = Mellanda Colson-Scott\n| children = 1\n| residence = [[Portsmouth, Virginia]]\n| alma_mater = \n| website = http://www.donscott.us/\n| committees =\n}}\n\n'''Don Scott''' is an American politician. A [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], he is a member of the [[Virginia House of Delegates]], representing the [[Virginia's 80th House of Delegates district|80th district]].\n\n==Biography==\nScott was born and raised in [[Houston, Texas]] as one of six children, and graduated from [[Texas A&M University]] with a degree in [[agriculture]]. Following his undergraduate education, Scott served as a Naval Officer.  Following his honorable discharge, he obtained a law degree from [[Louisiana State University]].<ref>https://www.wavy.com/news/politics/candidates/candidate-profile-don-scott-jr-80th-district/</ref><ref>https://wtkr.com/2019/10/23/get-to-know-don-scott-candidate-for-virginias-80th-district/</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Scott was arrested on federal drug charges, and served seven years in prison. Later, he acknowledged his mistakes, and said that the experience motivated him, and showed him injustices of the legal system.<ref>https://www.pilotonline.com/news/article_8172be74-ecf7-11e8-80ba-dff53ee8262d.html</ref> Following his release from prison, Scott took an entry-level position at KRA Corporation, where he eventually became senior vice president and relocated to [[Portsmouth, Virginia]]. \n\nIn 2015, Scott was admitted to the bar and and opened his own firm, where he practices criminal defense, family law, and civil cases <ref>http://www.donscottfirm.com</ref>.\n\n==Political Career==\n===2019===\nScott filed to run to represent the 80th district in the [[2019 Virginia House of Delegates election]] after the resignation of [[Matthew James (politician)|Matthew James]], who was appointed by Governor [[Ralph Northam]] to an executive position. Scott was unopposed in the primaries, and in the general election defeated [[Republican party (United States)|Republican]] James W. Evans and [[Independent politician |Independent]] Ryan Benton  with 66.01% of the vote.<ref>https://results.elections.virginia.gov/vaelections/2019%20November%20General/Site/GeneralAssembly.html</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Scott endorsed former Vice President Joe Biden in the 2020 Democratic Primary.\n<ref>https://blog.4president.org/2020/2020/03/virginia-house-majority-leader-charniele-herring-and-30-top-virginia-leaders-endorse-joe-biden.html</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Virginia House of Delegates}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scott, Don}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Virginia House of Delegates]]\n[[Category:Virginia Democrats]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Virginia house of representatives member}}\n{{ Infobox officeholder\n| birthname =\n| name = Don Scott\n| image =\n| caption =\n| state_delegate = Virginia\n| district = [[Virginia's 80th House of Delegates district|80th]]\n| term_start = January 8, 2020\n| term_end = \n| preceded = [[Matthew James (politician)|Matthew James]]\n| succeeded = \n| birth_date =\n| birth_place =\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse = Mellanda Colson-Scott\n| children = 1\n| residence = [[Portsmouth, Virginia]]\n| alma_mater = \n| website = http://www.donscott.us/\n| committees =\n}}\n\n'''Don Scott''' is an American politician. A [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], he is a member of the [[Virginia House of Delegates]], representing the [[Virginia's 80th House of Delegates district|80th district]].\n\n==Biography==\nScott was born and raised in [[Houston, Texas]] as one of six children, and graduated from [[Texas A&M University]] with a degree in [[agriculture]]. Following his undergraduate education, Scott served as a Naval Officer.  Following his honorable discharge, he obtained a law degree from [[Louisiana State University]].<ref>https://www.wavy.com/news/politics/candidates/candidate-profile-don-scott-jr-80th-district/</ref><ref>https://wtkr.com/2019/10/23/get-to-know-don-scott-candidate-for-virginias-80th-district/</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Scott was arrested on federal drug charges, and served seven years in prison. Later, he acknowledged his mistakes, and said that the experience motivated him, and showed him injustices of the legal system.<ref>https://www.pilotonline.com/news/article_8172be74-ecf7-11e8-80ba-dff53ee8262d.html</ref> Following his release from prison, Scott took an entry-level position at KRA Corporation, where he eventually became senior vice president and relocated to [[Portsmouth, Virginia]]. \n\nIn 2015, Scott was admitted to the bar and and opened his own firm, where he practices criminal defense, family law, and civil cases <ref>http://www.donscottfirm.com</ref>.\n\n==Political Career==\n===2019===\nScott filed to run to represent the 80th district in the [[2019 Virginia House of Delegates election]] after the resignation of [[Matthew James (politician)|Matthew James]], who was appointed by Governor [[Ralph Northam]] to an executive position. Scott was unopposed in the primaries, and in the general election defeated [[Republican party (United States)|Republican]] James W. Evans and Independent Ryan Benton  with 66.01% of the vote.<ref>https://results.elections.virginia.gov/vaelections/2019%20November%20General/Site/GeneralAssembly.html</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Scott endorsed former Vice President Joe Biden in the 2020 Democratic Primary.\n<ref>https://blog.4president.org/2020/2020/03/virginia-house-majority-leader-charniele-herring-and-30-top-virginia-leaders-endorse-joe-biden.html</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Virginia House of Delegates}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scott, Don}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Virginia House of Delegates]]\n[[Category:Virginia Democrats]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Bulls88", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added independent opponent in 2019 election", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Don_Scott_(Virginia_politician)"}
{"title_page": "Szombierki", "text_new": "\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Szombierki\n| native_name             = <!-- If different from name -->\n| native_name_lang        = <!-- ISO 639-2 code e.g. \"pl\" for Polish -->\n| settlement_type         = [[Bytom]] [[Dzielnica|District]]\n| image_skyline           = File:Bytom z lotu ptaka - Szombierki.jpg\n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = Birds eye view of Szombierki, Bytom.\n| image_shield            = \n| shield_alt              = \n| image_map               = File:Bytom - Szombierki.svg\n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = Location of Szombierki within Bytom.\n| coordinates             = \n| coor_pinpoint           = \n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|Poland}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Voivodeships of Poland|Voivodeship]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Silesian Voivodeship|Silesian]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[Powiat|County]]/City\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Bytom]]\n| established_title       = \n| established_date        = \n| parts_type              = Notable landmarks\n| parts_style             = para\n| p1                      = [[Szombierki Heat Power Station]], [[Szombierki Coal Mine]], [[Old Town Hall, Szombierki|Szombierki town hall]], Fazaniec Park.\n| government_footnotes    = \n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            = \n| leader_name             = \n| unit_pref               = Metric<!-- or US or UK -->\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 4,93\n| area_note               = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = 23665\n| population_as_of        = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_note         = \n| timezone                = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset              = +1\n| timezone_DST            = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST          = +2\n| postal_code_type        = Postal code\n| postal_code             = 41-907\n| area_code               = \n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n{{coord|50|20|N|18|53|E|display=title}}\n'''Szombierki''' ({{lang-de| Schomberg}}) is a district of [[Bytom]], [[Poland]].\n\n[[Szombierki Heat Power Station]] and [[Szombierki Coal Mine]] (KWK Szombierki), both recognized as important historical and industrial monuments, are located here.\n\nIn 2004 the [[winding tower]] \"Krystyna\" of the former coal mine KWK Szombierki and its surroundings was listed as a Zabytek National Heritage Site.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.wkz.katowice.pl/documents/rejestr_zabytkow/gmina_bytom.doc| title = Rejestr zabytk\u00f3w w Bytomiu}}</ref> In 2009 the tower and the Power Station were voted as two of the \"Seven Architectural Wonders of the [[Silesian Voivodeship]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slaskie.pl/strona_n.php?jezyk=pl&grupa=10&art=3515&id_menu |title=Znamy 7 cud\u00f3w architektury wojew\u00f3dztwa \u015bl\u0105skiego |publisher=Slaskie.pl |date=2009-10-09 |accessdate=2014-03-07}}</ref> In 2013 the Power Station was also recognized as a national heritage site.<ref name=dz>{{cite web|url=http://www.dziennikzachodni.pl/artykul/757599,bytom-elektrocieplownia-szombierki-w-rejestrze-zabytkow-wojewodztwa-slaskiego,id,t.html |title=Bytom: Elektrociep\u0142ownia Szombierki w rejestrze zabytk\u00f3w wojew\u00f3dztwa \u015bl\u0105skiego |publisher=Dziennikzachodni.pl |date=2013-02-08 |accessdate=2014-03-07}}</ref>\n\nThe village of Szombierki was first mentioned in documents in 1369.<ref>Edward Wieczorek, ''Bytom i okolice'', OSiR, Bytom, 1997, p. 80.</ref> In 1768, the first coal mine was established in Szombierki. However, it was closed around 1820.\n\nSzombierki is home to football club [[Szombierki Bytom]], established in 1919, Polish champions from [[Ekstraklasa 1979-80|1980]].\n\nThe historic churches of Saint Margaret and of the [[Church of the Most Sacred Heart of Jesus in Szombierki|Sacred Heart of Jesus]] are located in the district.\n\n==Etymology and other names==\n===Etymology===\nThe origin of the district's name is disputed, some suggest it derived from the name of Fridericus de Schonenburch, a knight who was a witness of the vassalage of [[Casimir II of \u0141\u0119czyca|Casimir II]] to the king of [[Kingdom of Bohemia|Bohemia]], while others point towards \"''Sch\u00f6nberg''\" (Meaning Beautiful Mountain in [[German Language|German]]), a medieval settlement located in the approximate area of Szombierki.\n===Name of the district in various languages===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Language\n! Name/s\n|-\n| [[Polish Language|Polish]]\n| '''Szombierki'''\n|-\n| [[Silesian language|Silesian]]\n| '''Sz\u014dmbierki''' (\u015alabik\u014frzowy szrajb\u014dnek), '''Sz\u016fmbierki''' (Steuer alphabet)\n|-\n| [[German Language|German]]\n| '''Schomberg'''\n|-\n|}\n===Former names===\nShortly after the [[Provisional Government of the Republic of Poland|Polish communist authorities]] [[Recovered territories|took over]] Szombierki, its name was officialy changed to \"Chruszcz\u00f3w\". The origin of the name is unknown and it was changed back in 1985<ref>https://bytom.naszemiasto.pl/chruszczow-pojdzie-w-zapomnienie/ar/c1-6113775</ref>.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=145>\nFile:Bytom Szombierki - Kopalnia Szombierki.jpg|Winding towers Krystyna (right) and Ewa\nFile:Bytom - widok ko\u015bcio\u0142a p.w. \u015aw. Ma\u0142gorzaty - panoramio (5).jpg|Saint Margaret Church\nFile:Bytom Szombierki Skarpa hala.jpg|City Sports Hall (''Miejska Hala Sportowa'')\nFile:Bytom Szombierki town hall.jpg|Former Szombierki town hall\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Neighbourhoods in Silesian Voivodeship]]\n[[Category:Bytom]]\n[[Category:Szombierki]]\n\n\n{{Silesian-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Szombierki\n| native_name             = <!-- If different from name -->\n| native_name_lang        = <!-- ISO 639-2 code e.g. \"pl\" for Polish -->\n| settlement_type         = [[Bytom]] [[Dzielnica|District]]\n| image_skyline           = File:Bytom z lotu ptaka - Szombierki.jpg\n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = Birds eye view of Szombierki, Bytom.\n| image_shield            = \n| shield_alt              = \n| image_map               = File:Bytom - Szombierki.svg\n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = Location of Szombierki within Bytom.\n| coordinates             = \n| coor_pinpoint           = \n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|Poland}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Voivodeships of Poland|Voivodeship]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Silesian Voivodeship|Silesian]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[Powiat|County]]/City\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Bytom]]\n| established_title       = \n| established_date        = \n| parts_type              = Notable landmarks\n| parts_style             = para\n| p1                      = [[Szombierki Heat Power Station]], [[Szombierki Coal Mine]], [[Old Town Hall, Szombierki|Szombierki town hall]], Fazaniec Park.\n| government_footnotes    = \n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            = \n| leader_name             = \n| unit_pref               = Metric<!-- or US or UK -->\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 4,93\n| area_note               = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = 23665\n| population_as_of        = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_note         = \n| timezone                = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| utc_offset              = +1\n| timezone_DST            = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST          = +2\n| postal_code_type        = Postal code\n| postal_code             = 41-907\n| area_code               = \n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n{{coord|50|20|N|18|53|E|display=title}}\n'''Szombierki''' ({{lang-de| Schomberg}}) is a district of [[Bytom]], [[Poland]].\n\n[[Szombierki Heat Power Station]] and [[Szombierki Coal Mine]] (KWK Szombierki), both recognized as important historical and industrial monuments, are located here.\n\nIn 2004 the [[winding tower]] \"Krystyna\" of the former coal mine KWK Szombierki and its surroundings was listed as a Zabytek National Heritage Site.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.wkz.katowice.pl/documents/rejestr_zabytkow/gmina_bytom.doc| title = Rejestr zabytk\u00f3w w Bytomiu}}</ref> In 2009 the tower and the Power Station were voted as two of the \"Seven Architectural Wonders of the [[Silesian Voivodeship]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slaskie.pl/strona_n.php?jezyk=pl&grupa=10&art=3515&id_menu |title=Znamy 7 cud\u00f3w architektury wojew\u00f3dztwa \u015bl\u0105skiego |publisher=Slaskie.pl |date=2009-10-09 |accessdate=2014-03-07}}</ref> In 2013 the Power Station was also recognized as a national heritage site.<ref name=dz>{{cite web|url=http://www.dziennikzachodni.pl/artykul/757599,bytom-elektrocieplownia-szombierki-w-rejestrze-zabytkow-wojewodztwa-slaskiego,id,t.html |title=Bytom: Elektrociep\u0142ownia Szombierki w rejestrze zabytk\u00f3w wojew\u00f3dztwa \u015bl\u0105skiego |publisher=Dziennikzachodni.pl |date=2013-02-08 |accessdate=2014-03-07}}</ref>\n\nThe village of Szombierki was first mentioned in documents in 1369.<ref>Edward Wieczorek, ''Bytom i okolice'', OSiR, Bytom, 1997, p. 80.</ref> In 1768, the first coal mine was established in Szombierki. However, it was closed around 1820.\n\nSzombierki is home to football club [[Szombierki Bytom]], established in 1919, Polish champions from [[Ekstraklasa 1979-80|1980]].\n\nThe historic churches of Saint Margaret and of the [[Church of the Most Sacred Heart of Jesus in Szombierki|Sacred Heart of Jesus]] are located in the district.\n\n==Etymology and other names==\n===Etymology===\nThe origin of the district's name is disputed, some suggest it derived from the name of Fridericus de Schonenburch, a knight who was a witness of the vassalage of [[Casimir II of \u0141\u0119czyca|Casimir II]] to the king of [[Kingdom of Bohemia|Bohemia]], while others point towards \"''Sch\u00f6nberg''\" (Meaning Beautiful Mountain in [[German Language|German]]), a medieval settlement located in the approximate area of Szombierki.\n===Name of the district in various languages===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Language\n! Name/s\n|-\n| [[Polish Language|Polish]]\n| '''Szombierki'''\n|-\n| [[Silesian language|Silesian]]\n| '''Sz\u014dmbierki''' (\u015alabik\u014frzowy szrajb\u014dnek), '''Sz\u016fmbierki''' (Steuer alphabet)\n|-\n| [[German Language|German]]\n| '''Schomberg'''\n|-\n|}\n===Former names===\nShortly after the [[Polish People's Republic|Polish communist authorities]] [[Recovered territories|took over]] Szombierki, its name was officialy changed to \"Chruszcz\u00f3w\". The origin of the name is unknown and it was changed back in 1985<ref>https://bytom.naszemiasto.pl/chruszczow-pojdzie-w-zapomnienie/ar/c1-6113775</ref>.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=145>\nFile:Bytom Szombierki - Kopalnia Szombierki.jpg|Winding towers Krystyna (right) and Ewa\nFile:Bytom - widok ko\u015bcio\u0142a p.w. \u015aw. Ma\u0142gorzaty - panoramio (5).jpg|Saint Margaret Church\nFile:Bytom Szombierki Skarpa hala.jpg|City Sports Hall (''Miejska Hala Sportowa'')\nFile:Bytom Szombierki town hall.jpg|Former Szombierki town hall\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Neighbourhoods in Silesian Voivodeship]]\n[[Category:Bytom]]\n[[Category:Szombierki]]\n\n\n{{Silesian-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "He\u0142mPolski", "label": "safe"