{"title_page": "Brian Mushimba", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Brian C. Mushimba\n|office3       = [[Ministry of Higher Education (Zambia)|Minister of Higher Education]]\n|term_start3   = 19 July 2019\n|term_end3     = \n|president3    = [[Edgar Lungu]]\n|predecessor3  = [[Professor Nkandu Luo]]\n|office        = [[Ministry of Transport and Communications (Zambia)|Minister of Transport and Communications]]\n|term_start    = 29 September 2016\n|term_end      = 19 July 2019\n|president     = [[Edgar Lungu]]\n|image         =\n|caption       = \n|predecessor   = [[Kapembwa Simbao]]\n|footnotes     =\n|office2       = [[National Assembly (Zambia)|Member of Parliament]]\n|order2        =\n|constituency2 = [[Kankoyo (constituency)|Kankoyo]] \n|president2    = [[Edgar Lungu]] <small>2015-</small>\n|successor2    = \n|term_start2   = 11 August 2016\n|term_end2     = \n|party         = [[Patriotic Front (Zambia)|Patriotic Front]] {{small|(2001\u2013present)}}\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1974|11|7}} \n|birth_place   = [[Mufulira]], Zambia\n|nationality   = Zambian \n|spouse        = Brenda Mushimba\n|children      = 2 \n|alma_mater    = [[University of Arizona]] (BS) <br> [[Salem University]] (Masters)<br> [[University of Zambia ]](PhD)\n|religion      = Roman Catholicism\n|profession    = Engineer\n|website       = {{URL|brianmushimba.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Brian C. Mushimba''' (born 7 November 1974) is a seasoned American trained engineer currently serving in the cabinet of the Zambian government. Before entering public service in 2016 as a way of giving back to his country of birth, he studied, graduated and practiced engineering in the [[United States]], [[Europe]] and around [[Africa]] with increasing responsibilities to become a Regional Director/CEO In the electricity sector.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lusakatimes.com/2016/09/29/president-lungu-appoints-9-ministers-bring-cabinet-size-25-ministers/|title=Zambia : President Lungu appoints 9 more ministers to bring his cabinet size to 25 Ministers|date=2016-09-29|accessdate=2018-04-05}}</ref> \nPrior to being appointed into cabinet, Mushimba was asked to stand and won the elections to become a member of Parliament and represent his home district. Mushimba's priorities as a member of Parliament have been around improving access to education, Healthcare and employment opportunities for his district. At a national level, and drawing on his vast energy background, he has focused on Energy issues in supporting government's agenda for increased energy security with market friendly energy policies.\nThrough his foundation, he launched a \"Mushimba Academic Scholarship\" in 2017/2018 to take back to school all vulnerable kids in the constituency that had dropped out of school due to lack of financial sponsorship, many of them due to being orphaned. In its first year, the scholarship has sponsored 130 students at a cost of K236, 000 ($24,000). Further, recognizing the challenge of putting three meals on the table per day by the constituents, Mushimba started a farmer input support program that in its first year supported local farmers with farming inputs from fertilizers to seeds totaling k130,000 ($13,000); all these programs were funded from personal funds from Mushimba himself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.gov.zm/node/5391|title=Brian  Mushimba  {{!}} National Assembly of Zambia|website=www.parliament.gov.zm|accessdate=2018-04-05}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nMushimba was born in [[Mufulira, Zambia]] on 7 November 1974. Being one of the best student at primary and junior secondary schools in [[mufulira]], he was admitted and completed his secondary education, 'O' levels and 'A' levels, at the prestigious [[Mpelembe Secondary School]], a boarding school that boasted as the best high school in Zambia in 1993 and 1996 respectively. Continuing his academic brilliance and upon successful completion of his 'A' levels (Form Six), he proceeded on the academic scholarship by the Zambian Government to the [[University of Arizona]] in the [[United States]] where he earned an undergraduate degree in engineering. He subsequently received graduate degrees in business administration while in USA before returning to his home country. In [[Zambia]], he completed his [[PhD]] in [[Environmental Engineering]] from the [[University of Zambia]]. His doctoral dissertation was on \" Viability of carbon-neutral energy sources in pyroprocesses; waste to energy conversion.\"\n\n==Career==\nUpon graduating from the [[University of Arizona]], Mushimba joined [[Siemens]] Power Generation in [[Atlanta, Georgia, USA]] as an electrical controls engineer. He subsequently worked for [[Lafarge (company)|Lafarge]] in Atlanta before being transferred to Zambia. Between 2012 and 2013, he would work for [[Pratt & Whitney]] Power Systems in [[East Hartford, Connecticut]] as their Product Line Manager for the [[Aeroderivative]] [[Gas Turbine]] Business line. He then joined [[Eskom]], the state electricity utility of [[South Africa]], as their Technical Director and worked there up to 2016 before [[Statkraft]], the state electricity utility of [[Norway]], operating as [[SN Power]], hired him as their Regional Executive for the African market. He would only stay in this role for a few months as he transitioned into public office by standing and winning a parliamentary seat for his childhood community of [[Kankoyo (constituency)|Kankoyo]] in the 2016 general elections. He subsequently was appointed into [[cabinet (government)|cabinet]].\n\n==Personal life==\nMushimba is of the Christian faith. He is married to Brenda Mushimba and they have two young sons.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Lungu Cabinet Navbox 2016}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mushimba, Brian}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly (Zambia)]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Transport ministers of Zambia]]\n[[Category:Zambian engineers]]\n[[Category:People from Mufulira]]\n[[Category:University of Zambia alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Brian C. Mushimba\n|office3       = [[Ministry of Higher Education (Zambia)|Minister of Higher Education]]\n|term_start3   = 19 July 2019\n|term_end3     = \n|president3    = [[Edgar Lungu]]\n|predecessor3  = [[Professor Nkandu Luo]]\n|office        = [[Ministry of Transport and Communications (Zambia)|Minister of Transport and Communications]]\n|term_start    = 29 September 2016\n|term_end      = 19 July 2019\n|president     = [[Edgar Lungu]]\n|image         =\n|caption       = \n|predecessor   = [[Kapembwa Simbao]]\n|footnotes     =\n|office2       = [[National Assembly (Zambia)|Member of Parliament]]\n|order2        =\n|constituency2 = [[Kankoyo (constituency)|Kankoyo]] \n|president2    = [[Edgar Lungu]] <small>2015-</small>\n|successor2    = \n|term_start2   = 11 August 2016\n|term_end2     = \n|party         = [[Patriotic Front (Zambia)|Patriotic Front]] {{small|(2001\u2013present)}}\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1974|11|7}} \n|birth_place   = [[Mufulira]], Zambia\n|nationality   = Zambian \n|spouse        = Brenda Mushimba\n|children      = 2 \n|alma_mater    = [[University of Arizona]] (BS) <br> [[Salem University]] (Masters)<br> [[University of Zambia ]](PhD)\n|religion      = Roman Catholicism\n|profession    = Engineer\n|website       = {{URL|brianmushimba.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Brian C. Mushimba''' (born 7 November 1974) is a seasoned American trained engineer currently serving in the cabinet of the Zambian government. Before entering public service in 2016 as a way of giving back to his country of birth, he studied, graduated and practiced engineering in the [[United States]], [[Europe]] and around [[Africa]] with increasing responsibilities to become a Regional Director/CEO In the electricity sector.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lusakatimes.com/2016/09/29/president-lungu-appoints-9-ministers-bring-cabinet-size-25-ministers/|title=Zambia : President Lungu appoints 9 more ministers to bring his cabinet size to 25 Ministers|date=2016-09-29|accessdate=2018-04-05}}</ref> \nPrior to being appointed into cabinet, Mushimba was asked to stand and won the elections to become a member of Parliament and represent his home district. Mushimba's priorities as a member of Parliament have been around improving access to education, Healthcare and employment opportunities for his district. At a national level, and drawing on his vast energy background, he has focused on Energy issues in supporting government's agenda for increased energy security with market friendly energy policies.\nThrough his foundation, he launched a \"Mushimba Academic Scholarship\" in 2017/2018 to take back to school all vulnerable kids in the constituency that had dropped out of school due to lack of financial sponsorship, many of them due to being orphaned. In its first year, the scholarship has sponsored 130 students at a cost of K236, 000 ($24,000). Further, recognizing the challenge of putting three meals on the table per day by the constituents, Mushimba started a farmer input support program that in its first year supported local farmers with farming inputs from fertilizers to seeds totaling k130,000 ($13,000); all these programs were funded from personal funds from Mushimba himself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.gov.zm/node/5391|title=Brian  Mushimba  {{!}} National Assembly of Zambia|website=www.parliament.gov.zm|accessdate=2018-04-05}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nMushimba was born in [[Mufulira, Zambia]] on 7 November 1974. Being one of the best student at primary and junior secondary schools in [[mufulira]], he was admitted and completed his secondary education, 'O' levels and 'A' levels, at the prestigious [[Mpelembe Secondary School]], a boarding school that boasted as the best high school in Zambia in 1993 and 1996 respectively. Continuing his academic brilliance and upon successful completion of his 'A' levels (Form Six), he proceeded on the academic scholarship by the Zambian Government to the [[University of Arizona]] in the [[United States]] where he earned an undergraduate degree in engineering. He subsequently received graduate degrees in business administration while in USA before returning to his home country. In [[Zambia]], he completed his [[PhD]] in [[Environmental Engineering]] from the [[University of Zambia]]. His doctoral dissertation was on \" Viability of carbon-neutral energy sources in pyroprocesses; waste to energy conversion.\"\n\n==Career==\nUpon graduating from the [[University of Arizona]], Mushimba joined [[Siemens]] Power Generation in [[Atlanta, Georgia, USA]] as an electrical controls engineer. He subsequently worked for [[Lafarge]] in Atlanta before being transferred to Zambia. Between 2012 and 2013, he would work for [[Pratt & Whitney]] Power Systems in [[East Hartford, Connecticut]] as their Product Line Manager for the [[Aeroderivative]] [[Gas Turbine]] Business line. He then joined [[Eskom]], the state electricity utility of [[South Africa]], as their Technical Director and worked there up to 2016 before [[Statkraft]], the state electricity utility of [[Norway]], operating as [[SN Power]], hired him as their Regional Executive for the African market. He would only stay in this role for a few months as he transitioned into public office by standing and winning a parliamentary seat for his childhood community of [[Kankoyo (constituency)|Kankoyo]] in the 2016 general elections. He subsequently was appointed into [[cabinet (government)|cabinet]].\n\n==Personal life==\nMushimba is of the Christian faith. He is married to Brenda Mushimba and they have two young sons.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Lungu Cabinet Navbox 2016}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mushimba, Brian}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly (Zambia)]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Transport ministers of Zambia]]\n[[Category:Zambian engineers]]\n[[Category:People from Mufulira]]\n[[Category:University of Zambia alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLafarge(link changed toLafarge (company)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brian_Mushimba"}
{"title_page": "Milan Bandi\u0107", "text_new": "{{Infobox Mayor\n| name         = Milan Bandi\u0107\n| image        = Dan OSRH Milan Bandic 28052011 2.jpg| width        = 220px\n| caption      = Bandi\u0107 on 28 May 2011\n| order        = 50th and 52nd\n| office       = Mayor of Zagreb\n| term_start1  = 15 May 2005\n| predecessor1 = [[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]]\n| successor1   = \n| term_start2  = 5 May 2000\n| term_end2    = 21 January 2002\n| predecessor2 = [[Marina Matulovi\u0107-Dropuli\u0107]]\n| successor2   = [[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]]\n| office3           = Leader of the [[Bandi\u0107 Milan 365 - Labour and Solidarity Party|Bandi\u0107 Milan 365 -<br />Labour and Solidarity Party]] \n| term_start3    = 28 March 2015 \n| term_end3     =\n| predecessor3 = ''Position established'' \n| successor3     = \n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1955|11|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Grude]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|FPR Yugoslavia]] {{small|(now [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]])}}\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| nationality  = Croatian\n| party        = {{plainlist|\n*[[League of Communists of Croatia]] {{small|(1980s)}}\n*[[Social Democratic Party of Croatia]] {{small|(1990\u20132009)}}\n*[[Independent (politician)|Independent]] {{small|(2009\u20132015)}}\n*[[Bandi\u0107 Milan 365 - Labour and Solidarity Party]] {{small|(2015\u2013present)}}\n}}\n| other_party = \n| relations   =\n| spouse      = {{marriage|Vesna Bandi\u0107|1981|1996}}<br />{{marriage|Vesna Bandi\u0107|2003}}<ref name=spouse_children />\n| children    = 1<ref name=spouse_children />\n| residence   = [[Stara Pe\u0161\u010denica]]\n| alma_mater  = [[University of Zagreb]]\n| occupation  = [[Politician]]\n| profession  = \n| signature   =\n| website     = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n{{About|the Croatian politician|the Croatian filmmaker who legally changed his name to Milan Bandi\u0107|Dario Juri\u010dan}}\n\n'''Milan Bandi\u0107''' ({{IPA-hr|m\u01d0lan b\u00e2\u02d0ndit\u0361\u0255:|hr}} {{small|({{Audio-nohelp|Milanbandicname.ogg|listen}})}}; born 22 November 1955) is a Croatian politician currently serving his sixth term as [[List of mayors of Zagreb|mayor]] of the Croatian capital, [[Zagreb]], since 2005. Between 2000 and 2009, he was a prominent member of the [[Social Democratic Party of Croatia|Social Democratic Party]] (SDP). In 2007, he unsuccessfully ran for party president. However, he remained one of the main rivals of the former party president [[Zoran Milanovi\u0107]]. On 5 November 2009, he announced his intention to run for a president, in violation of the party's bylaws which led to his expulsion from the party.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/video--bandic-krenuo-u-utrku-milan-ce-igrati-lopte-u-svakom-selu/458485.aspx |title=Video - Bandi\u0107 krenuo u utrku: \"Milan \u0107e igrati lopte u svakom selu\" |author= |date=5 November 2009 |work= |publisher=[[Index.hr]] |accessdate=16 November 2011|language=hr}}</ref> On 10 January 2010, he lost the [[Croatian presidential election, 2009\u20132010|Croatian presidential election]] to the official SDP candidate [[Ivo Josipovi\u0107]] in the runoff elections.\n\nAlthough described in 2002 as the SDP's most popular politician for the \"famous 24 hours he devotes to the service of citizens of Zagreb\",<ref name=nin_omiljeni>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.nin.co.rs/2002-01/31/21760.html\n| title = Metropola bez gradona\u010delnika\n| date = 2002-01-31\n| last = Stanivukovi\u0107\n| first = Zoran\n| accessdate = 2008-09-19\n| work = [[\u041d\u0418\u041d]]\n| language = Serbian\n}}</ref> he has also gained notoriety for a number of actions and statements he has made as mayor.<ref name=javno_biografija/>\nBandi\u0107 is viewed as a hands-on mayor because of his ambition and the number of projects related to Zagreb that he has undertaken. He is widely credited{{fact|date=January 2020}} for the renovation of [[Ljubljanska Avenue]] (now [[Zagreba\u010dka Avenue]]), for his work on the [[Arena Zagreb]] and the [[Homeland Bridge]] (which opened during his third term).\n\nBandi\u0107 was arrested in the evening hours of 19 October 2014, along with 18 other officials, under the suspicion of malfeasance related to [[Zagreb Holding]]. In his absence, his deputy [[Sandra \u0160valjek]] took the duties of mayor from 19 October 2014 until 26 March 2015.<ref>http://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/Novosti/Hrvatska/tabid/66/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/279857/Bandi-opunomoio-Kusin-za-voenje-Zagreba.aspx</ref> Bandi\u0107 canceled the authorization that he granted to her because some disagreements between them.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/jutarnji-doznaje-uhicen-milan-bandic-/1229175/ |title=Uhi\u0107eni Milan Bandi\u0107! |last1=De\u0161kovi\u0107 |first1=Marin |date=2014-10-19 |website=Jutarnji list |publisher=Jutarnji list |accessdate=2014-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rtl.hr/vijesti/novosti/1367502/uhicen-milan-bandic-u-tijeku-pretraga-njegovog-stana/ |title=Uhi\u0107en Milan Bandi\u0107, u tijeku pretraga njegovog stana! |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2014-10-19 |website=RTL Televizija |publisher=RTL Televizija |accessdate=2014-10-19}}</ref> Consequently, \u0160valjek has resigned all of her duties in city. Bandi\u0107's second deputy Vesna Kusin took the duties of mayor on 26 March 2015. On 10 April 2015, Zagreb County Court ruled that Milan Bandi\u0107 has to be released from prison while pending trial. Consequently, he returned to the position of Mayor.<ref>http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/bandic-ostaje-na-slobodi-i-vraca-se-na-mjesto-gradonacelnika/812562.aspx</ref>\n\n==Private life==\nMilan Bandi\u0107 was born to Jozo and Blagica Bandi\u0107 ([[n\u00e9e]] Tomi\u0107) in the small [[Hamlet (place)|hamlet]] of Bandi\u0107a Brig, a part of Cerov Dolac in the municipality of [[Grude]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] (then [[PR Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[FPR Yugoslavia]]).<ref name=Bandic>Bandi\u0107, Milan. [http://www.milanbandiczagreb.com/Default.aspx?tabid=149 Biografija] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080424082908/http://www.milanbandiczagreb.com/Default.aspx?tabid=149 |date=2008-04-24}}. Bandi\u0107's official web site. Retrieved 2011-10-30 {{in lang|hr}}</ref> He was the middle child in the family, with an older brother Drago and a younger sister Tonka.<ref name=Barilar>{{cite news |title=Bandi\u0107: Od doseljenika s koferom do neprikosnovenog vladara Zagreba |author=Barilar, Suzana |url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/bandic--od-doseljenika-s-koferom-do-neprikosnovenog-vladara-zagreba/333515/ |newspaper=[[Jutarnji list]] |date=4 November 2009 |accessdate=20 November 2011|language=hr}}</ref> His family's main source of income was a [[tobacco plantation]]. As a child, Bandi\u0107 was altar servant in local church.<ref name=Bandic/> He attended [[Antun Branko \u0160imi\u0107]] High School in Grude and he was excellent student.<ref name=Barilar/> In 1974, he moved to Zagreb to study at the Department of Political Science at the [[University of Zagreb]]<ref name=Bandic/>, program of National defense and social self-protection (today non-existent). To pay off his [[student loan]]s he unloaded sugar and coal<ref name=Bandic/> and he was also a [[masonry|mason]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/bandicev-put-na-celo-zagreba-poceo-je-istovarom-secera-i-zbukanjem-fasada/778501.aspx | title=Bandi\u0107ev put na \u010delo Zagreba po\u010deo je istovarom \u0161e\u0107era i \u017ebukanjem fasada | date=19 October 2014 | work=[[Index.hr]] | language=Croatian | accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduation, Bandi\u0107 was conscripted to the [[Yugoslav People's Army]], and after that he was employed in [[Ledo (company)|Ledo]], producer of ice creams.<ref name=Bandic/>\n\nDuring his student days he met his wife Vesna.<ref name=Bandic/> He was married to her until their divorce in 1996, although they still live together in their [[Stara Pe\u0161\u010denica]] apartment. They have a daughter, Ana-Marija.<ref name=spouse_children>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak.aspx?id=248861\n | title = Bandi\u0107 se 1996. razveo zbog otkupa stana?\n | date = 2005-02-10\n | accessdate = 2008-08-01\n | work = Vijesti.net\n | language = Croatian}}</ref> Bandi\u0107 has stated that his divorce was the result of a seven-year separation.<ref name=spouse_children /> Bandi\u0107 owns two [[golden retriever]]s, Bil and Rudi, which he often walks during his work hours.<ref name=24sata_bil_operacija>{{cite web\n| url = http://damp.nsk.hr/arhiva/vol1/880/14301/www.24sata.hr/articles/view/48239/index.html\n| title = Bandi\u0107ev Bil ide na kemoterapiju?\n| date = 2007-03-22\n| last = Vukadin\n| first = Romana\n| accessdate = 2008-08-03\n| work = [[24 sata (Croatia)|24 sata]]\n| language = Croatian\n}}</ref><ref name=bil_rudi>{{cite journal |date=2008-08-04 |title=Bandi\u0107u u dom sti\u017ee retriver Rudi |trans-title=Retriever Rudi arrives in Bandi\u0107 home |journal=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |issue=664 |language=Croatian |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/47766/8/ |accessdate=2008-08-06 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68oppVAzh?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/47766/bandicu-u-dom-stize-retriver-rudi |archivedate=1 July 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBandi\u0107 is an avid distance runner, describing himself as \"addicted to running\".<ref>{{cite news | title=Ne bojim se, imam jo\u0161 mnogo kilometara za pretr\u010dati| work=[[Jutarnji list]] | date=July 28, 2009 | language=Croatian | quote=Mogu re\u0107i da sam ovisan o tr\u010danju i da je to moja droga.}}</ref> He is reported to run 10 kilometers every weekday morning,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.javno.com/en-croatia/photo--zagreb-mayor-turns-pilgrimage-into-marathon_182355 | title=PHOTO: Zagreb Mayor Turns Pilgrimage Into Marathon | work=javno.com | first=Ivan | last=Kova\u010d | date=September 15, 2008 | accessdate=2009-08-23 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090520043315/http://www.javno.com/en-croatia/photo--zagreb-mayor-turns-pilgrimage-into-marathon_182355 | archivedate=May 20, 2009}}</ref> and in March 2008 completed the 61&nbsp;km [[Zagreb]]\u2013[[\u010cazma]] [[ultramarathon]].\n\n==Political career==\n{{POV section|date=April 2020}}\n==={{anchor|Before becoming a mayor}}Before becoming mayor===\nAfter serving the army and short work in [[Ledo (company)|Ledo company]] Bandi\u0107 was employed in Municipal Committee of [[League of Communists of Croatia]] in [[Pe\u0161\u010denica \u2013 \u017ditnjak|Pe\u0161\u0107enica]] where he worked as professional political worker.<ref name=Bandic/><ref name=Barilar/>\n\nAfter collapse of [[Socialist Federative Republic of Yugoslavia|SFR Yugoslavia]] and [[League of Communists of Croatia]] Bandi\u0107 did not want to leave the party because he worked for years in Pe\u0161\u010denica and thus it was matter of pride.<ref name=Bandic/> He expressed his hopes that he and his colleagues will return to political stage as Croatian social democrats.<ref name=Bandic/>\n\nDuring the [[Croatian War of Independence]] Bandi\u0107 helped with logistics.<ref name=Bandic/>\n\nBandi\u0107 was one of the few [[Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Herzegovinian Croats]] to remain with the party after the [[1990 Croatian parliamentary election|first democratic elections in 1990]] in which the Communist Party, led by [[Ivica Ra\u010dan]], reformed and re-branded itself as the [[Social Democratic Party of Croatia]] (SDP). He demonstrated organizational ability and populist political instincts. These abilities allowed the SDP to gain in Zagreb blue-collar neighborhoods and attract votes which the [[Croatian Democratic Union]] (HDZ) and its then-president [[Franjo Tu\u0111man]] had considered theirs by default. As such, he proved to be a valuable asset for the Social Democratic Party. In 1993 he became party secretary.<ref name=Barilar/>\n\nConflict between HDZ and SDP manifested in the [[1995 Croatian parliamentary election|1995 parliamentary]] and City of [[Zagreb]] elections, leading to the [[Zagreb Crisis]]: an electoral alliance (in which the SDP was a major partner) won a majority in the Zagreb elections and chose [[Goran Grani\u0107]] as the new mayor, but Franjo Tu\u0111man used a legal loophole to stop Grani\u0107 from taking office. Several subsequent elections were held, with the SDP winning each time and Tu\u0111man promptly removing every candidate. For a time Zagreb was a city without a mayor, which led to public unrest and protests in [[Ban Jela\u010di\u0107 Square]]. With the final 1997 election of the HDZ candidate [[Marina Matulovi\u0107-Dropuli\u0107]] as the mayor of Zagreb, the crisis faded. Bandi\u0107 played a role in the crisis by becoming a city councilman in 1995 and the leader of the Zagreb SDP in 1997.<ref name=javno_biografija>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.javno.com/hr/hrvatska/clanak.php?id=49365\n |title       = Biografija: Milan Bandi\u0107\n |date        = 2007-06-02\n |accessdate  = 2008-08-01\n |work        = Javno.hr\n |language    = Croatian\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/68EJ2pyfI?url=http://dalje.com/hr-hrvatska/biografija--milan-bandic/49365\n |archivedate = 2012-06-06\n}}</ref>\n\nDuring the first campaign his [[Herzegovina|Herzegovinian]] background became an issue, as the [[Croatian Peasant Party]] (HSS) suggested that only a native citizen of Zagreb could become the city's mayor. HSS also launched a propaganda campaign against [[Herzegovinians]] in an effort to undermine Bandi\u0107's campaign. The party hoped that the majority of Zagreb voters would turn away from Bandi\u0107. Those expectations were not fulfilled and Bandi\u0107 later used his Herzegovinian background as an advantage, broadening his support among the ordinary citizens of Zagreb.\n\nThe HDZ under Bandi\u0107 eventually lost power in the Croatian capital in 2000.<ref name=Barilar/>\n\n==={{anchor|First and second term (2000\u20132002)}}First and second terms (2000\u20132002)===\n{{see also|2000 Zagreb local elections|2001 Zagreb local elections}}\n\nBandi\u0107 was elected [[mayor]] of Zagreb in 2000<ref name=izbori>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.zgizbori.hr/2000Lokalni/izbori_2000_.html\n | title = Izbori odr\u017eani 7. svibnja 2000.\n | work = Gradski zavod za automatsku obradu podataka\n | accessdate = 2008-07-27\n | language = Croatian\n | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100129103926/http://www.zgizbori.hr/2000Lokalni/izbori_2000_.html\n | archive-date = 2010-01-29\n | url-status = dead\n}}</ref> and re-elected in the city election in 2001.<ref name=izbori_2001>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.zgizbori.hr/2001Lokalni/rezultati.html\n| title = Izbori odr\u017eani 20. svibnja 2001.\n| work = City Bureau for Automatic Data Processing\n| accessdate = 2008-08-04\n| language = Croatian\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080316190322/http://www.zgizbori.hr/2001Lokalni/rezultati.html\n| archive-date = 2008-03-16\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref> His rise in influence among SDP politicians and on the Zagreb political scene created a backlash by the [[Croatian People's Party]] (HNS), the other left-of-center party led by [[Vesna Pusi\u0107]], who did not trust his nationalist populism and his occasional run-ins with the courts. The HNS campaigned against the SDP in the 2000 elections. However, the HNS entered into a coalition with the SDP in 2001. It governed Zagreb with the SDP until 2005 when it withdrew, again because of Bandi\u0107.\n\nIn 2002, Bandi\u0107 fled from the scene of a motor vehicle accident while under the influence of alcohol. He tried to bribe the officer who stopped him and threatened the officer with his alleged connections in the [[Ministry of the Interior (Croatia)|Ministry of the Interior]]. The incident was heavily covered by the media that asked for his resignation. The SDP was at first reluctant to sanction Bandi\u0107. Under public pressure, the SDP leadership compelled Bandi\u0107 to resign.<ref name=resignation>{{cite web| url = http://www.hsp1861.hr/vijesti2/020121jl.htm| title = Bandi\u0107eva ostavka - pobjeda javnosti| accessdate = 2008-07-27| last = Lovri\u0107| first = Jelena| date = 2002-01-21| work = [[Novi list]]| language = Croatian}}</ref><ref name=scandals_drunk_driving>{{cite web| url = http://www.hsp1861.hr/vijesti7/060118vm.htm| title = Esdepeovci zgro\u017eeni pona\u0161anjem Bandi\u0107a| accessdate = 2007-09-29| last = Mazzocco| first = Vojislav| date = 2006-01-18| work = [[Ve\u010dernji list]]| language = Croatian}}</ref><ref name=index_policemen>{{cite web| url = http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak.aspx?id=391401| title = Kako se rije\u0161iti policajca koji radi svoj posao| accessdate = 2008-09-21| last = Mazzocco| first = Vojislav| date = 2008-06-17| work = Vijesti.net| language = Croatian}}</ref> After his resignation there was uncertainty concerning his successor; while the Zagreb SDP had the right to nominate the mayor, it was so dominated by Bandi\u0107 that it was questionable who could replace him.<ref name=resignation /> Eventually [[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]] took over as mayor, while Bandi\u0107 retained a place in the Zagreb chain of command as deputy mayor. He was eager to become a mayor again, and blocked Pavi\u0107's development plans (advancing his own) while working toward an early election.<ref name=scandals_cursing_pavic /><ref name=\"savez_desni\u010dari\">{{cite journal\n |url         = http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/10596/\n |title       = Bandi\u0107 s desni\u010darima ru\u0161i Vlastu Pavi\u0107\n |date        = 2003-05-27\n |accessdate  = 2008-08-02\n |last        = Babi\u0107\n |first       = Jelena\n |issue       = 393\n |journal     = [[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]]\n |language    = Croatian\n |trans-title = Bandi\u0107 and right-wingers brings down Vlasta Pavi\u0107\n |archivedate = 30 June 2012\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/68oWiX4IA?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/10596/bandic-s-desnicarima-rusi-vlastu-pavic\n}}</ref><ref name=\"pavi\u0107_deal\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/10895/ |title=Vlasta Pavi\u0107 u zamjenu za primirje ustupa mjesto Bandi\u0107u |last=Jelini\u0107 |first=Berislav |language=Croatian |trans-title=Vlasta Pavi\u0107 steps down for Bandi\u0107 in exchange for a truce |work=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |date=24 February 2004 |accessdate=30 June 2012 |archivedate=30 June 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68oY6G8Cg?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/10895/vlasta-pavic-u-zamjenu-za-primirje-ustupa-mjesto-bandicu |url-status=dead}}</ref> In response [[Ivica Ra\u010dan]] (head of the SDP) tried to restrain Bandi\u0107's activities.<ref name=\"ra\u010dan_upozorenje\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/10240/ |title=Ra\u010dan poti\u010de Vlastu Pavi\u0107 da vlada bez Bandi\u0107a |date=15 May 2002 |last=Ple\u0161e |first=Mladen |accessdate=30 June 2012 |work=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |language=Croatian |trans-title=Ra\u010dan urges Vlasta Pavi\u0107 to govern without Bandi\u0107 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68oWJlgkS?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/10240/racan-potice-vlastu-pavic-da-vlada-bez-bandica |archivedate=30 June 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\nThe rules then in force would not allow Bandi\u0107 to have a second term as mayor during the current term of the assembly.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/10985/racan-ustuknuo-pred-bandicevim-divljastvom |publisher=[[Nacional (weekly)]] |title=Ra\u010dan ustuknuo pred Bandi\u0107evim divlja\u0161tvom |trans-title=Ra\u010dan taken aback by Bandi\u0107's savage remark |language=Croatian |author=Berislav Jelini\u0107 |date=4 May 2004 |accessdate=1 July 2012 |archivedate=1 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68pZwx7NY?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/10985/racan-ustuknuo-pred-bandicevim-divljastvom}}</ref> Vlasta Pavi\u0107 attempted to strike a deal ending the ongoing feud, but Bandi\u0107 eventually succeeded in undermining her. Although no early elections were held, he was re-elected mayor in [[2005 Zagreb mayoral elections|the May 15, 2005 elections]].<ref name=izbori_2005>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.zgizbori.hr/2005Lokalni/zgizbori_zg_a/rezultati/r06_021_0021_000.html\n| title = Rezultati glasovanja za izbor \u010dlanova Gradske skup\u0161tine Grada Zagreba (\"Voting results for the election of Municipal Councillors to the City of Zagreb\")\n| date = 2005-05-16\n| accessdate = 2008-08-01\n| language = Croatian\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110721102953/http://www.zgizbori.hr/2005Lokalni/zgizbori_zg_a/rezultati/r06_021_0021_000.html\n| archive-date = 2011-07-21\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref><ref name=\"pavi\u0107_deal\" />\n\nIn April 2004 then-mayor [[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]] criticized Bandi\u0107 for having spent 15 million [[kuna (currency)|kunas]] (about [[USD|US$]]3.26 million) of city money to buy a lot on [[Vjekoslav Heinzel Avenue|Heinzelova Avenue]] which was formerly owned by the [[meat packing industry|meat packing plant]] Zagrep\u010danka. The controversy was dubbed \"the Zagrep\u010danka case\" by the newspapers.<ref name=scandals_cursing_pavic /><ref name=scandals_drunk_driving /> The city government could not use the lot, because its ownership was divided among 43 individuals. When (responding to a question from a city counselor) Mayor Pavi\u0107 distanced herself from Bandi\u0107, Bandi\u0107 was accused of cursing her mother in a vulgar way during the talks.<ref name=scandals_cursing_pavic>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.index.hr/clanak.aspx?id=199287\n| title = Milan Bandi\u0107 opsovao majku zagreba\u010dkoj gradona\u010delnici\n| accessdate = 2007-09-29\n| date = 2004-04-28\n| work = Vijesti.net\n| language = Croatian\n}}</ref><ref name=scandals_drunk_driving /> He also published a newspaper advertisement on behalf of the city government, entitled ''Istina je!'' (\"It's true!\"). The advertisement was supported by all SDP members of the city council except [[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]], the mayor at that time. [[Ivica Ra\u010dan]] later condemned the advertisement as a political mistake, telling the Zagreb SDP that they would face consequences for their action.<ref name=zagrepcanka_indictment/>\n\nA court case ensued, with charges being brought against Bandi\u0107 and others involved.<ref name=zagrepcanka_indictment>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.hrt.hr/arhiv/2004/05/10/HRT0037.html\n |title       = Kaznena prijava protiv Bandi\u0107a, Buluma i nekih \u010dlanova poglavarstva zbog oglasa ''Istina je!''\n |date        = 2004-05-10\n |publisher   = [[Croatian Radio Television]]\n |language    = Croatian\n |accessdate  = 2008-04-30\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20160303170804/http://www.hrt.hr/arhiv/2004/05/10/HRT0037.html\n |archivedate = 2016-03-03\n}}</ref> Three years later, Bandi\u0107 was acquitted and the City of Zagreb was awarded ownership of the Zagrep\u010danka lot in a [[judgment (law)|court judgment]]. Bandi\u0107 promised a new [[business district]] in the Zagrep\u010danka location.<ref name=city_centar_zagrepcanka>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=49358\n |title       = Zagreb To Get A City Centre\n |date        = 2007-06-02\n |accessdate  = 2008-09-28\n |work        = Javno.hr\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070612235956/http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=49358\n |archivedate = 2007-06-12\n}}</ref>\n\nNot all legal troubles have been solved, however, as the city still has to deal with unsolved cases and complaints entered against the lot.<ref name=plomba>{{cite web\n |url        = http://www.javno.com/hr/zagreb/clanak.php?id=186305\n |archive-url = https://archive.is/20130126200636/http://www.javno.com/hr/zagreb/clanak.php?id=186305\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 2013-01-26\n |title      = Bandi\u0107 isplatio ovrhu za Zagrep\u010danku - 3 mil kuna\n |date       = 2008-09-26\n |accessdate = 2008-09-28\n |work       = Javno.hr\n |language   = Croatian\n}}</ref> In 2008 the sale of the Zagrep\u010danka lot to [[Institut IGH]] was announced, but the deal fell through in 2009; this has potential to incur a cost of \u20ac4.5&nbsp;million to the Zagreb [[holding company]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.poslovni.hr/133686.aspx | title = Ivo \u010covi\u0107 ipak potpisao \u0161tetan ugovor s Radi\u0107em? | language = Croatian | work = [[Poslovni dnevnik]] | date = December 4, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Third term (2005\u20132009)===\n{{see also|2005 Zagreb local elections}}\n\nFollowing the illness and death of Ra\u010dan Bandi\u0107 announced his candidacy for SDP leadership,<ref name=nacional_kandidatura>{{cite journal\n |url         = http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/34638/\n |title       = Obra\u010dun Bandi\u0107a i Milanovi\u0107a odlu\u010duje o \u0161efu SDP-a\n |trans-title = Conflict of Bandi\u0107 and Milanovi\u0107 to decide leader of the SDP\n |date        = 2007-05-21\n |last        = Bajru\u0161i\n |first       = Robert\n |accessdate  = 2008-08-04\n |issue       = 601\n |journal     = [[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]]\n |language    = Croatian\n |archivedate = 30 June 2012\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/68ohfBem2?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/34638/obracun-bandica-i-milanovica-odlucuje-o-sefu-sdp-a\n |url-status  = dead\n}}</ref> planning to resign as mayor afterwards. He competed against [[\u017deljka Antunovi\u0107]], [[Zoran Milanovi\u0107]] and [[Tonino Picula]]. [[Zoran Milanovi\u0107]] was elected on 2 June 2007 as the new SDP leader, while Bandi\u0107 remained mayor of Zagreb.<ref name=milanovic>{{cite journal\n |url         = http://www.nacional.hr/en/articles/view/35122/\n |title       = Milanovi\u0107 widens his base\n |accessdate  = 2007-09-30\n |last        = Bajru\u0161i\n |first       = Robert\n |date        = 2007-06-06\n |archivedate = 25 July 2012\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/69QLPJQhh?url=http://www.nacional.hr/en/clanak/35122/milanovic-widens-his-base\n |issue       = 603\n |journal     = [[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]]\n}}</ref> He did not give up the fight, however, organizing opposition within the party and campaigning to defeat Milanovi\u0107 in the next party election.<ref name=\"revolt_milanovi\u0107\">{{cite journal\n |url         = http://www.nacional.hr/en/articles/view/40824/\n |title       = Revolt against Milanovi\u0107\n |accessdate  = 2008-07-28\n |archivedate = 25 July 2012\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/69QLV04ei?url=http://www.nacional.hr/en/clanak/40824/revolt-against-milanovic\n |last        = Bajru\u0161i\n |first       = Robert\n |date        = 2007-12-12\n |issue       = 630\n |journal     = [[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]]\n}}</ref><ref name=\"milanovi\u0107_obra\u010dun\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/Hrvatska/tabid/66/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/11033/Default.aspx\n| title = Milanovi\u0107 krenuo u obra\u010dun s Bandi\u0107em\n| accessdate = 2008-07-28\n| last = Karlovi\u0107-Saboti\u0107\n| first = Marina\n| date = 2008-06-12\n| work = [[Slobodna Dalmacija]]\n| language = Croatian\n}}</ref>\n\nA controversy arose on 31 July 2005, when Bandi\u0107 was on a bus with 30 other people and saw workers waving on the street. He then allegedly cited the [[Arbeit macht frei|Auschwitz motto]]: \"Work liberates, the Nazis weren't totally dumb.\" Hrvoje Kre\u0161i\u0107, a ''[[Novi list]]'' journalist, allegedly heard Bandi\u0107 and published his statement. The following day Bandi\u0107 threatened to sue Kre\u0161i\u0107 and ''Novi list''; he claimed he said \"Marxists,\" not \"Nazis\". Bandi\u0107's statement was corroborated by several of his nearby colleagues; other journalists at the rear of the bus did not hear anything said by Bandi\u0107, due to noise inside the vehicle. Bandi\u0107 said that if awarded [[damages]], he would donate the money to the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]]. The director of the center, [[Efraim Zuroff]], refused.<ref name=zuroff_auschwitz />\n\nIn January 2006, Bandi\u0107 publicly threatened a journalist working for ''[[Ve\u010dernji list]]''. The journalist asked Bandi\u0107 about an offer from a [[Czech Republic|Czech]] company; Bandi\u0107 replied aggressively, cursing and threatening the journalist. Afterwards, he claimed he had simply spoken to the journalist in a loud voice.<ref name=threatened_journalist />\n\nAs of October 2007 Bandi\u0107 was under investigation by the [[USKOK]] (Office for the Suppression of Corruption and Organized Crime) about several deals he made as mayor of Zagreb, including the July 2007 exchange of a lot at the intersection of Maksimirska Street and [[Gojko \u0160u\u0161ak Avenue|\u0160u\u0161ak Avenue]] for a lot in [[Sesvetski Kraljevec]]. A court-appointed expert allowed the exchange at a price of 1,300 kuna per square meter (\u20ac185) for the Sesvete lot (located in the suburbs, outside the [[Zagreb bypass]]) and 2,300 kuna (\u20ac321) for the Maksimirska lot (located in the [[Maksimir]] district, several hundred meters from downtown). New experts considered the lot on Maksimirska Street to be more valuable than the lot in Sesvetski Kraljevec. Thus, a USKOK source testified that Bandi\u0107 made a deal damaging to the city budget. The two companies with whom Bandi\u0107 dealt were headed by inexperienced students, furthering the appearance of impropriety.<ref name=bandic_index_uskok>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=86401\n |title       = Bandi\u0107 Under Investigation For Corruption\n |accessdate  = 2008-09-28\n |date        = 2007-10-03\n |work        = Javno.hr\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071004041519/http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=86401\n |archivedate = 2007-10-04\n}}</ref><ref name=uskok>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak.aspx?id=360440\n| title = Bandi\u0107 o istrazi USKOK-a: Neka institucije rade svoj posao\n| accessdate = 2008-02-16\n| date = 2007-10-03\n| work = Vijesti.net\n| language = Croatian\n}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 June 2008 the Main Committee of SDP received a letter entitled ''Za \u0161to se, uop\u0107e, danas zala\u017ee SDP?'' (\"What, overall, does the SDP stand for today?\") by [[Dra\u017een Lali\u0107]] (a Croatian [[sociologist]]) which attacked Bandi\u0107 by pointing out his misdeeds and errors and questioning Bandi\u0107's loyalty to the SDP's principles. The letter was sparked partially by the [[assault]] and [[Battery (crime)|battery]] of anti-corruption Zagreb road-authorities director Igor Ra\u0111enovi\u0107, which had not been properly investigated. Another reason was a concert held on [[Ban Jela\u010di\u0107 Square]] by [[Marko Perkovi\u0107 Thompson]], a singer known to attract an [[Usta\u0161e|usta\u0161a]] audience. Bandi\u0107 supported the concert instead of condemning it, inaccordance with SDP anti-nationalistic principles. Although the letter attacked the SDP as a whole, Bandi\u0107 was considered a key participant in all events described. Bandi\u0107 responded to the letter indirectly by encouraging the police to do their job, while failing to appropriately defend his position.<ref name=lalic_letter>{{cite journal\n| last = Cigoj\n| first = Mark\n|author2=Galovi\u0107, Alen\n| title = Pismo koje potresa SDP\n| journal = [[Globus (weekly)|Globus]]\n| issue = 918\n| pages =18\u201322\n| url = http://www.globus.com.hr\n| date = 2008-07-11\n| accessdate = 2008-07-12\n}}</ref><ref name=\"lali\u0107_ve\u010dernji\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.vecernji.hr/newsroom/news/croatia/3123249/index.do \n |title=Javne osobe pisale Milanovi\u0107u da zaustavi Bandi\u0107a \n |last=Popovi\u0107 \n |first=Jasmina \n |date=2008-07-09 \n |accessdate=2008-08-02 \n |work=[[Ve\u010dernji list]] \n |language=Croatian \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080731053802/http://www.vecernji.hr/newsroom/news/croatia/3123249/index.do \n |archivedate=2008-07-31 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> Zoran Milanovi\u0107 responded instead, accusing Lali\u0107 of trying to buy himself a return to the Croatian political scene. Bandi\u0107 thus received the SDP's support, ensuring his candidacy in the upcoming 2009 mayoral election.<ref name=\"milanovi\u0107_fights_back\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/47300/ |title=Pismo koje je u\u010dvrstilo Bandi\u0107a |author1=Bajru\u0161i, Robert |trans-title=A letter that strengthened Bandi\u0107 |author2=Gaura, Orhidea |date=2008-07-14 |accessdate=2008-08-02 |issue=661 |journal=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |language=Croatian |archivedate=30 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68oon0FPx?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/47300/pismo-koje-je-ucvrstilo-bandica}}</ref>\n\nBandi\u0107 was involved in the ''Cvjetni prolaz'' case (a lengthy affair beginning in 2007), which centered on the controversial demolition and conversion of historical buildings in Petar Preradovi\u0107 Square into a [[shopping mall]] in Zagreb's [[Donji grad (Zagreb)|Lower Town]] area.<ref name=cg_intro_nac>{{cite web |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/30633/5/ |title=Preobra\u017eenska 6 i kino Zagreb nisu spomenici |accessdate=2008-05-16 |date=2007-01-15 |work=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |last=Cviti\u0107 |first=Plamenko |language=Croatian |trans-title=Preobra\u017eenska 6 and Cinema Zagreb are no monuments |archivedate=30 June 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68og8jEQ3?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/30633/preobrazenska-6-i-kino-zagreb-nisu-spomenici |url-status=dead}}</ref> The project was headed by developer Tomislav Horvatin\u010di\u0107, who was alleged to have used illegal means in an attempt to [[evict]] the buildings' residents. These residents included a headquarters and church operated by the Zagreb-Ljubljana [[metropolitan bishop|metropolia]] of the [[Serbian Orthodox Church]] and the home of the late poet [[Vladimir Vidri\u0107]].<ref name=orthodox /> Bandi\u0107 is known to be a strong supporter of Horvatin\u010di\u0107,<ref name=cp_gi_popov /> publicly criticizing opponents of the project.<ref name=cp_dnevnik_b_swearing /> In August 2008, Horvatin\u010di\u0107 obtained a license to demolish the old buildings. Residents of the surrounding buildings and [[environmentalists]] argued that the license was improperly issued, but the demolition is (as of 2011) still underway. However, Horvatin\u010di\u0107 is forbidden to demolish Vidri\u0107's home or build any part of the project until he obtains a building-location license, which requires him to prove he can build a walkway between Gunduli\u0107eva Street and Cvjetni Square.\n\nIn 2009. Croatian media revealed that Bandi\u0107 spent 1,55 million kuna (210 000 \u20ac) of city money to build two public toilets.<ref name=\"tportal.hr\">{{cite news|url=https://www.tportal.hr/vijesti/clanak/bandicev-kum-izgradio-najskuplji-wc-u-hrvatskoj-20090318|title=Bandi\u0107ev kum izgradio najskuplji WC u Hrvatskoj|work=tportal.hr|accessdate=2017-05-12}}</ref> The media mockingly called these \"The Golden Toilets\".<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite news|url=https://www.tportal.hr/vijesti/clanak/i-bandicevi-zlatni-wc-i-dosli-na-tapetu-uskoka-20131230|title=I Bandi\u0107evi zlatni WC-i do\u0161li na tapetu Uskoka|work=tportal.hr|accessdate=2017-05-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vecernji.hr/zagreb/davor-jelavic-pod-istragom-zbog-bandicevih-zlatnih-wc-a-912533|title=Davor Jelavi\u0107 pod istragom zbog Bandi\u0107evih 'zlatnih' WC-a|accessdate=2017-05-12|language=hr}}</ref> The media wrote that the job was given to the company [[T\u017dV Gredelj]], specialized for construction of railway veichles without any tender. Gredelj then hired another company owned by Bandi\u0107's godfather to do the actual construction.<ref name=\"tportal.hr\"/> In 2013. [[USKOK|Croatian State Prosecutor's Office for the Suppression of Organized Crime and Corruption]] announced that they are investigating the case.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n===Fourth term (2009\u20132013)===\n{{see also|2009 Zagreb local elections}}\nUntil 2009, the mayor of Zagreb was elected by the city assembly ([[city council]]). In [[2009 Zagreb local elections|elections held in the spring of 2009]], the mayor was directly elected for the first time. Bandi\u0107 was forced into a second round not by HDZ candidate ([[Jasen Mesi\u0107]]) but by outsider [[Josip Kregar]] (dean of the Faculty of Law at the [[University of Zagreb]]), who ran on an independent platform. Bandi\u0107 won the second round, with 62 percent of the vote to Kregar's 37 percent. In October 2009, Bandi\u0107 visited the site of a World War II [[Yugoslav Partisans|partisan]] massacre on the island of [[Daksa (Dubrovnik)|Daksa]] with the [[Croatian Bishops' Conference]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/Dubrovnik/tabid/75/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/75337/Default.aspx | title=Daksa kod Dubrovnika: biskupi molili za \u017ertve komunisti\u010dkog terora - do\u0161ao i Milan Bandi\u0107 | work=[[Slobodna Dalmacija]] | date=October 21, 2009 | language=Croatian | accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> On 29 October 2009 Bandi\u0107's proposed exceptional budget, with a proposal to hold a referendum on the building of a new football stadium, was rejected. Among those voting against the budget was his own party, the SDP.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hrt.hr/index.php?id=48&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=51872&tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=38&cHash=8a5414470f | title=I SDP protiv Bandi\u0107a | date=October 29, 2009 | work=hrt.hr | publisher=[[Croatian Radiotelevision]] | language=Croatian | accessdate=2009-12-26 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100302221451/http://www.hrt.hr/index.php?id=48 | archivedate=March 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Presidential campaign===\n[[File:Milan bandi\u0107 poster.JPG|thumb|240px|Pro-Bandi\u0107 billboard during second round of 2009\u20132010 presidential [[Croatian presidential election, 2009\u20132010|elections]]|alt=Pro-Bandi\u0107 billboard in parking lot, with blue and red letters on white background]]\nOn 5 November 2009 Bandi\u0107 announced his presidential candidacy in the [[Croatian presidential election, 2009\u20132010|2009\u20132010 presidential election]] after media speculation. Bandi\u0107's move resulted in his automatic expulsion from the [[Social Democratic Party of Croatia]] and the loss of his positions as party president and leader of the Zagreb branch. He was replaced as leader of the Zagreb SDP by [[Davor Bernardi\u0107]].<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.hrt.hr/index.php?id=48&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=75175&tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=34&cHash=098abf8794\n| title = HRT: Bernardi\u0107 na \u010delu zagreba\u010dkog SDP-a\n| year = 2010\n| accessdate = 2010-06-29\n}}</ref>\n\nIn the 27 December 2009 first round of the election Bandi\u0107 received 14.83 percent of the vote, placing him in second place after SDP candidate [[Ivo Josipovi\u0107]] (with 32.7 percent). On 10 January he lost the second round with 39.74 percent of the vote.\nIn Zagreb Bandi\u0107 lost both rounds of the election, receiving support in only a handful of city neighbourhoods.<ref>{{cite web | work = Zagrebancija.com | url = http://www.zagrebancija.com/hr-aktualnosti/kako-je-milan-bandic-izgubio-povjerenje-zagreba_287999 | language = Croatian | title = Detaljna analiza kraha - Kako je Milan Bandi\u0107 izgubio povjerenje Zagreba | date = December 30, 2009 | accessdate = January 16, 2010 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100120181034/http://www.zagrebancija.com/hr-aktualnosti/kako-je-milan-bandic-izgubio-povjerenje-zagreba_287999 | archivedate = January 20, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | newspaper = [[Ve\u010dernji list]] | url = http://www.vecernji.hr/vijesti/josipovic-potukao-bandica-gotovo-svim-zagrebackim-cetvrtima-clanak-77273 | language = Croatian | title = Donja Dubrava i Brezovica jedine Bandi\u0107eve \u010detvrti - Josipovi\u0107 potukao Bandi\u0107a u gotovo svim zagreba\u010dkim \u010detvrtima | date = January 10, 2010 | accessdate = January 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Parliamentary election of 2011===\nOn 8 October 2011 Bandi\u0107 announced that he will compete in [[2011 Croatian parliamentary election|Croatian parliamentary election of 2011]] with independent list named \"Stijena\" ({{lang-en|Rock}}).<ref name=VL>[http://www.vecernji.hr/vijesti/bandic-izbore-ide-neovisnom-listom-koju-je-nazvao-stijena-clanak-334146 Bandi\u0107 na izbore ide s neovisnom listom koju je nazvao Stijena]. [[Ve\u010dernji list]], 2011-10-08. Retrieved 2011-10-30 {{in lang|hr}}</ref>\n\n===Fifth term (2013\u20132017)===\n{{See also|2013 Zagreb local elections}}\nBandi\u0107 was arrested on 19 October 2014 on charges of corruption, bribery and organized crime, along with two other key members of the Zagreb city council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/uhicen-milan-bandic/778492.aspx |title=Uhi\u0107en Milan Bandi\u0107 |accessdate=19 October 2014 |language=Croatian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://ca.reuters.com/article/topNews/idCAKCN0I80Q420141019|title=Croatian police arrest Zagreb mayor on corruption charges|date=19 October 2014|agency=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Sixth term (2017\u2013present)===\n{{See also|2017 Zagreb local elections}}\n\n==Mayoral achievements==\n[[File:Milan Bandi\u0107 2009.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Bandi\u0107 at the [[Snow Queen Trophy]], January 2009|alt=Bandi\u0107 smiling and looking to his right, wearing blue-and-white skiing jersey over brown long-sleeved shirt]]\n[[File:Zagrebacka Avenija, Zagreb.JPG|thumb|right|Renovated [[Zagreba\u010dka Avenue]]|alt=Aerial view of eight-lane highway]]\nOne of Bandi\u0107's best-known projects is the renovation of [[Ljubljanska Avenue]], whose eastern stretch beginning at Svilkovi\u0107i Street (later Savska Opatovina Rotary) was later renamed to [[Zagreba\u010dka Avenue]].<ref name=komunalni_lj-zg>{{cite journal\n |url=http://193.198.60.202/komunalni/arhiva/338/str04.pdf \n |title=Zastupnici skratili Ljubljansku \n |last=Kos Bu\u010dar \n |first=Dajana \n |language=Croatian \n |date=2006-10-11 \n |accessdate=2008-07-24 \n |journal=Zagreba\u010dki komunalni vjesnik \n |issue=338 \n |format=PDF, 108 KB \n |page=4 \n |issn=1845-4968 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110529140837/http://193.198.60.202/komunalni/arhiva/338/str04.pdf \n |archivedate=2011-05-29 \n}}</ref> He is also credited with the Zagreb model apartment building ({{lang-hr|Zagreba\u010dki model stanogradnje}}), also locally known as ''Bandi\u0107evi stanovi'' (\"Bandi\u0107's apartments\").<ref name=\"\u0161pansko_zms\" /> [[Radimir \u010ca\u010di\u0107]], another investor in the Zagreb apartment market, accused Bandi\u0107 of trying to undermine the statewide POS housing projects. POS ({{lang-hr|POticana Stanogradnja}}, \"subsidized apartments\") is cheap housing instituted by Radimir \u010ca\u010di\u0107 during the coalition of SDP, Bandi\u0107's party, and several other parties (such as \u010ca\u010di\u0107's HNS, which ruled the Croatian government from 2000 to 2003).<ref name=\"\u0161pansko_zms\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.spansko.net/vijesti.php?id=662\n| title = Zagreba\u010dki model stanogradnje\n| date = 2004-05-18\n| accessdate = 2008-08-03\n| work = \u0160pansko.net\n| language = Croatian\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110629150931/http://www.spansko.net/vijesti.php?id=662\n| archive-date = 2011-06-29\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref><ref name=hrt_zms>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.hrt.hr/arhiv/2002/02/22/HRT0010.html\n |title       = Milan Bandi\u0107 najavio zagreba\u010dki model stanogradnje\n |date        = 2002-02-22\n |accessdate  = 2008-08-03\n |work        = [[Croatian Radiotelevision]]\n |language    = Croatian\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304091952/http://www.hrt.hr/arhiv/2002/02/22/HRT0010.html\n |archivedate = 2016-03-04\n}}</ref>\n\nBandi\u0107 has heavily criticized the state of [[Transport in Zagreb|Zagreb's transportation system]] which he encountered at the beginning of his mayoral career.<ref name=jeza>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.javno.com/hr/zagreb/clanak.php?id=139391\n |title       = Bandi\u0107: Hvata me jeza zbog Remetine\u010dkog rotora\n |date        = 2008-04-10\n |accessdate  = 2008-09-29\n |work        = Javno.hr\n |language    = Croatian\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080412093330/http://www.javno.com/hr/zagreb/clanak.php?id=139391\n |archivedate = 2008-04-12\n}}</ref> With the guidance of Zagreb traffic engineers Bandi\u0107 has approved ambitious transportation projects in Zagreb, such as the Ljubljanska/Zagreba\u010dka Avenue widening, [[Homeland Bridge]] construction, renovation of the [[green wave]] system in the city center with the addition of [[bicycle path]]s and multi-level underground [[parking garages]] at [[Tu\u0161kanac]], [[Kvaternik Square]] and other locations. An important project begun during Bandi\u0107's term in office is the Zagreb [[light rail|metro]], which is planned to become the main suburban transportation mode to the city.<ref name=metro>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.neuron.at/64_Kolic-Marenjak-Skendr_e_09.2006.pdf\n |format      = PDF\n |title       = Design concept and financing of the light rail Zagreb project\n |date        = 2006-09-22\n |last1       = Koli\u0107\n |first1      = Davorin\n |last2       = Marenjak\n |first2      = Sa\u0161a\n |last3       = Skendrovi\u0107\n |first3      = Vladimir\n |accessdate  = 2008-09-26\n |work        = Neuron Consulting Engineers\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070711211147/http://www.neuron.at/64_Kolic-Marenjak-Skendr_e_09.2006.pdf\n |archivedate = 2007-07-11\n}}</ref> Bandi\u0107 has arranged the construction of the [[Arena Zagreb]], a [[team handball|handball]] arena located in [[Lani\u0161te, Croatia|Lani\u0161te]], which was constructed to prepare the city for the [[2009 World Men's Handball Championship]].<ref name=arena_sanader>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak.aspx?id=344911\n| title = Bandi\u0107 i Sanader dogovorili izgradnju dvorane Arena Zagreb, Ingra i TriGr\u00e1nit dobili posao\n| date = 2007-04-24\n| accessdate = 2008-08-07\n| work = Vijesti.net\n| language = Croatian\n}}</ref><ref name=\"arena_\u0161pricer\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/34754/ |title=Bandi\u0107: \"Hladan sam k'o \u0161pricer\" |trans-title=Bandi\u0107: I'm as cool as can be |date=2007-05-25 |last=Zrinjski |first=Marijana |accessdate=2008-08-07 |journal=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |issue=602 |language=Croatian |archivedate=30 June 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68oiDfnqv?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/34754/bandic-hladan-sam-ko-spricer |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Honors==\nOn July 10, 2009, Bandi\u0107 was made an honorary citizen of [[Srebrenica]], Bosnia and Herzegovina.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bihvijesti.net/izvor108857_Povelja-opstine-Milan-Bandic-pocasni-gradjanin-Srebrenice.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110914132454/http://www.bihvijesti.net/izvor108857_Povelja-opstine-Milan-Bandic-pocasni-gradjanin-Srebrenice.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 September 2011 |title=Povelja op\u0161tine: Milan Bandi\u0107 po\u010dasni gra\u0111anin Srebrenice |author=A. B. |date=10 July 2009 |publisher=BiH Vijesti |accessdate=16 November 2011 |language=bs}}</ref>\n\nOn November 4, 2018, [[President of Russia|Russian President]] [[Vladimir Putin]] honored Bandi\u0107 with an [[Order of Friendship]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Putin odlikovao Milana Bandi\u0107a Ordenom prijateljstva |url=https://www.vecernji.hr/zagreb/putin-odlikovao-milana-bandica-ordenom-prijateljstva-1264868 |website=vecernji.hr |accessdate=29 November 2018|language=hr}}</ref>\n\n==Health problems==\n\nOn 3 July 2003 after a session of the Zagreb City Council Bandi\u0107 requested medical assistance, stating that he had begun to feel ill during the session. The media reported that he had suffered a minor [[stroke]]; the official explanation was that exhaustion and overwork had caused a [[blood vessel]] in his [[endocranium]] to [[spasm]]. He was hospitalized for a few weeks, then went to [[Krapinske Toplice]] to recover, and returned to his duties in September.<ref name=\"ostojic bandic\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.vecernji.hr/lokalni-izbori/bitka-za-zagreb-kako-je-ostojic-bandicu-spasio-zivot-491484\n| title = Bitka za Zagreb: Kako je Ostoji\u0107 Bandi\u0107u spasio \u017eivot\n| work = [[Ve\u010dernji list]]\n| date = 28 December 2012\n| language = Croatian\n| accessdate = 3 March 2015\n}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n{{Criticism section|date=October 2014}}\n\n==={{anchor|Land exchange case}}Land-exchange case===\n\nAs of October 2007 Bandi\u0107 was under investigation by the [[USKOK]] (Office for the Suppression of Corruption and Organized Crime) about several deals he made as mayor of Zagreb, including the July 2007 exchange of a lot at the intersection of Maksimirska Street and [[Gojko \u0160u\u0161ak Avenue|\u0160u\u0161ak Avenue]] for a lot in [[Sesvetski Kraljevec]]. A court-appointed expert allowed the exchange at a price of 1,300 kuna per square meter (\u20ac185) for the Sesvete lot (located in the suburbs, outside the [[Zagreb bypass]]) and 2,300 kuna (\u20ac321) for the Maksimirska lot (located in the [[Maksimir]] district, several hundred meters from downtown). New experts considered the lot on Maksimirska Street to be more valuable than the lot in Sesvetski Kraljevec. Thus, a USKOK source testified that Bandi\u0107 made a deal damaging to the city budget. The two companies with whom Bandi\u0107 dealt were headed by inexperienced students, furthering the appearance of impropriety.<ref name=bandic_index_uskok>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=86401\n |title       = Bandi\u0107 Under Investigation For Corruption\n |accessdate  = 2008-09-28\n |date        = 2007-10-03\n |work        = Javno.hr\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071004041519/http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=86401\n |archivedate = 2007-10-04\n}}</ref><ref name=uskok>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak.aspx?id=360440\n| title = Bandi\u0107 o istrazi USKOK-a: Neka institucije rade svoj posao\n| accessdate = 2008-02-16\n| date = 2007-10-03\n| work = Vijesti.net\n| language = Croatian\n}}</ref>\n\n===''Cvjetni prolaz'' case===\nBandi\u0107 was involved in the ''Cvjetni prolaz'' case (a lengthy affair beginning in 2007), which centered on the controversial demolition and conversion of historical buildings in Petar Preradovi\u0107 Square into a [[shopping mall]] in Zagreb's [[Donji grad (Zagreb)|Lower Town]] area.<ref name=cg_intro_nac>{{cite web |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/30633/5/ |title=Preobra\u017eenska 6 i kino Zagreb nisu spomenici |accessdate=2008-05-16 |date=2007-01-15 |work=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |last=Cviti\u0107 |first=Plamenko |language=Croatian |trans-title=Preobra\u017eenska 6 and Cinema Zagreb are no monuments |archivedate=30 June 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68og8jEQ3?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/30633/preobrazenska-6-i-kino-zagreb-nisu-spomenici |url-status=dead}}</ref> The project was headed by developer Tomislav Horvatin\u010di\u0107, who was alleged to have used illegal means in an attempt to [[evict]] the buildings' residents. These residents included a headquarters and church operated by the Zagreb-Ljubljana [[metropolitan bishop|metropolia]] of the [[Serbian Orthodox Church]] and the home of the late poet [[Vladimir Vidri\u0107]].<ref name=orthodox>{{cite web |url=http://www.mitropolija-zagrebacka.org/STR2LAT.htm \n |title=Eparhijski arhijerej |accessdate=2008-09-27 |work=Serbian orthodox church |language=Serbian |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080531230841/http://www.mitropolija-zagrebacka.org/STR2LAT.htm |archivedate=2008-05-31 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Bandi\u0107 is known to be a strong supporter of Horvatin\u010di\u0107,<ref name=cp_gi_popov>{{cite web |url = http://www.glasistre.hr/?5bb51035b592e5bf7ec3a43bb6bb7e44,TS,1885,,11666,15206,150393, | title = Ne vjeruj Bandi\u0107u ni kad te triput ljubi | accessdate = 2008-02-17 | date = 2007-01-13 | work = Glas Istre | last = Vesi\u0107 | first = Vanja |language = Croatian}}</ref> publicly criticizing opponents of the project.<ref name=cp_dnevnik_b_swearing>{{cite web | url = http://dnevnik.hr/vijesti/hrvatska/bandic-psovkama-protiv-protivnika-projekta.html | title = Bandi\u0107 psovkama protiv protivnika projekta | accessdate = 2008-05-15 | date = 2007-01-27 | work = Dnevnik.hr | language = Croatian}}</ref> In August 2008, Horvatin\u010di\u0107 obtained a license to demolish the old buildings. Residents of the surrounding buildings and [[environmentalists]] argued that the license was improperly issued, but the demolition is (as of 2011) still underway. However, Horvatin\u010di\u0107 is forbidden to demolish Vidri\u0107's home or build any part of the project until he obtains a building-location license, which requires him to prove he can build a walkway between Gunduli\u0107eva Street and Cvjetni Square.\n\n=== ''Golden Toilets'' case ===\nIn 2009. Croatian media revealed that Bandi\u0107 spent 1,55 million kuna (210 000 \u20ac) of city money to build two public toilets.<ref name=\"tportal.hr\" /> The media mockingly called these \"The Golden Toilets\".<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.tportal.hr/vijesti/clanak/i-bandicevi-zlatni-wc-i-dosli-na-tapetu-uskoka-20131230|title=I Bandi\u0107evi zlatni WC-i do\u0161li na tapetu Uskoka|work=tportal.hr|accessdate=2017-05-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vecernji.hr/zagreb/davor-jelavic-pod-istragom-zbog-bandicevih-zlatnih-wc-a-912533|title=Davor Jelavi\u0107 pod istragom zbog Bandi\u0107evih 'zlatnih' WC-a|accessdate=2017-05-12|language=hr}}</ref> The media wrote that the job was given to the company [[T\u017dV Gredelj]], specialized for construction of railway veichles without any tender. Gredelj then hired another company owned by Bandi\u0107's godfather to do the actual construction.<ref name=\"tportal.hr\"/> In 2013. [[USKOK|Croatian State Prosecutor's Office for the Suppression of Organized Crime and Corruption]] announced that they are investigating the case.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n===2014 arrest===\nBandi\u0107 was arrested on 19 October 2014 on charges of corruption, bribery and organized crime, along with two other key members of the Zagreb city council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/uhicen-milan-bandic/778492.aspx |title=Uhi\u0107en Milan Bandi\u0107 |accessdate=19 October 2014 |language=Croatian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://ca.reuters.com/article/topNews/idCAKCN0I80Q420141019|title=Croatian police arrest Zagreb mayor on corruption charges|date=19 October 2014|agency=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Alleged use of cocaine===\nAccording to some Croatian media, Bandi\u0107 is long time cocaine addict.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dnevno.hr/vijesti/hrvatska/nas-je-gradonacelnik-zesci-ovisnik-o-kokainu-918248/ |title=Na\u0161 je gradona\u010delnik \u017ee\u0161\u0107i ovisnik o kokainu! |accessdate=7 April 2020 |language=Croatian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://100posto.jutarnji.hr/news/cak-se-ni-i-hdz-ovci-vise-se-skrivaju-s-travom-a-europarlamentarka-tvrdi-da-nam-je-sabor-pun-kokaina-bacilo-me-na-paranoju-u-strah-i-bilo-je-to-prvi-i-zadnji-put-da-sam/ |title=Kad se zabijeli Markov trg! |accessdate=7 April 2020 |language=Croatian}}</ref>\n\n===Minor controversies===\nA controversy arose on 31 July 2005, when Bandi\u0107 was on a bus with 30 other people and saw workers waving on the street. He then allegedly cited the [[Arbeit macht frei|Auschwitz motto]]: \"Work liberates, the Nazis weren't totally dumb.\" Hrvoje Kre\u0161i\u0107, a ''[[Novi list]]'' journalist, allegedly heard Bandi\u0107 and published his statement. The following day Bandi\u0107 threatened to sue Kre\u0161i\u0107 and ''Novi list''; he claimed he said \"Marxists,\" not \"Nazis\". Bandi\u0107's statement was corroborated by several of his nearby colleagues; other journalists at the rear of the bus did not hear anything said by Bandi\u0107, due to noise inside the vehicle. Bandi\u0107 said that if awarded [[damages]], he would donate the money to the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]]. The director of the center, [[Efraim Zuroff]], refused.<ref name=zuroff_auschwitz>{{cite web | url = http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak.aspx?id=277097 | title = Zuroff: Neka Bandi\u0107 sebi i suradnicima plati put u Auschwitz | date = 2005-08-02 | accessdate = 2008-09-28 | work = Vijesti.net | language = Croatian}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2006, Bandi\u0107 publicly threatened a journalist working for ''[[Ve\u010dernji list]]''. The journalist asked Bandi\u0107 about an offer from a [[Czech Republic|Czech]] company; Bandi\u0107 replied aggressively, cursing and threatening the journalist. Afterwards, he claimed he had simply spoken to the journalist in a loud voice.<ref name=threatened_journalist>{{cite web |url = http://www.bolji-zivot.hr/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=113&Itemid=96 |title= Bandi\u0107 javno prijetio novinaru |accessdate= 2007-09-11 |date= 2006-01-17 |work= Bolji \u017eivot |language= Croatian |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070928020755/http://www.bolji-zivot.hr/index.php option=com_content&task=view&id=113&Itemid=96 |archivedate = 2007-09-28}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 May 2007 Bandi\u0107 fell asleep shortly before noon during a session of the Zagreb City Assembly; TV cameras captured the moment.<ref name=city_assembly_sleep>{{cite web | url = http://dnevnik.hr/vijesti/hrvatska/bandic-zaspao-na-sjednici-skupstine.html | title = Bandi\u0107 zaspao na sjednici Skup\u0161tine | accessdate = 2008-06-15 | date = 2007-06-01 | work = [[Dnevnik Nove TV]] | language = Croatian}}</ref> This was apparently not the first time he suffered from sleep problems; he fell asleep on 16 June 2006 at the [[Croatian National Theatre in Zagreb|Croatian National Theater]], where he presented an award to Marija Musta\u0107, secretary of the [[Croatian Association of the Blind]].\n\nIn May 2008 Bandi\u0107 left his car illegally parked at the center of [[\u0160ubi\u0107eva Street]], creating a road hazard and causing traffic problems; he held a public presentation of a camera system designed to issue [[traffic ticket|tickets]] to red-light runners, improperly-parked cars and the like. He then shopped in the [[Dolac Market|Dolac]] open-air market while his driver waited in the car, obstructing traffic. When questioned about this incident, Bandi\u0107 blamed it on his driver.<ref name=subiceva_road_obstruction>{{cite web |url=http://www.vecernji.hr/newsroom/regions/zagreb/3082790/index.do |title=Bandi\u0107 najavio prometno redarstvo koje bi, kad bi ga bilo, ju\u010der najprije ulovilo njega |accessdate=2008-05-16 |date=2008-05-16 |work=[[Ve\u010dernji list]] |last=\u0160poljar |first=Marko |author2=Li\u0161anin, Mi\u0161o |language=Croatian |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517135056/http://www.vecernji.hr/newsroom/regions/zagreb/3082790/index.do |archivedate=2008-05-17 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]]\n* [[List of mayors of Zagreb]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|\n title=[[List of mayors of Zagreb|Mayor of Zagreb]]|\n before=[[Josip Kregar]]\n(governor appointed by Croatian government)|\n years=2000\u20132002|\n after=[[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]]\n}}\n{{succession box|\n title=[[List of mayors of Zagreb|Mayor of Zagreb]]|\n before=[[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]]|\n years=2005\u2013present |\n after=Incumbent\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bandic, Milan}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Zagreb]]\n[[Category:Faculty of Political Sciences, University of Zagreb alumni]]\n[[Category:Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic Party of Croatia politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Grude]]\n[[Category:League of Communists of Croatia politicians]]\n[[Category:Candidates for President of Croatia]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Friendship]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Mayor\n| name         = Milan Bandi\u0107\n| image        = Dan OSRH Milan Bandic 28052011 2.jpg| width        = 220px\n| caption      = Bandi\u0107 on 28 May 2011\n| order        = 50th and 52nd\n| office       = Mayor of Zagreb\n| term_start1  = 15 May 2005\n| predecessor1 = [[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]]\n| successor1   = \n| term_start2  = 5 May 2000\n| term_end2    = 21 January 2002\n| predecessor2 = [[Marina Matulovi\u0107-Dropuli\u0107]]\n| successor2   = [[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]]\n| office3           = Leader of the [[Bandi\u0107 Milan 365 - Labour and Solidarity Party|Bandi\u0107 Milan 365 -<br />Labour and Solidarity Party]] \n| term_start3    = 28 March 2015 \n| term_end3     =\n| predecessor3 = ''Position established'' \n| successor3     = \n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1955|11|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Grude]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|FPR Yugoslavia]] {{small|(now [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]])}}\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| nationality  = Croatian\n| party        = {{plainlist|\n*[[League of Communists of Croatia]] {{small|(1980s)}}\n*[[Social Democratic Party of Croatia]] {{small|(1990\u20132009)}}\n*[[Independent (politician)|Independent]] {{small|(2009\u20132015)}}\n*[[Bandi\u0107 Milan 365 - Labour and Solidarity Party]] {{small|(2015\u2013present)}}\n}}\n| other_party = \n| relations   =\n| spouse      = {{marriage|Vesna Bandi\u0107|1981|1996}}<br />{{marriage|Vesna Bandi\u0107|2003}}<ref name=spouse_children />\n| children    = 1<ref name=spouse_children />\n| residence   = [[Stara Pe\u0161\u010denica]]\n| alma_mater  = [[University of Zagreb]]\n| occupation  = [[Politician]]\n| profession  = \n| signature   =\n| website     = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n{{About|the Croatian politician|the Croatian filmmaker who legally changed his name to Milan Bandi\u0107|Dario Juri\u010dan}}\n\n'''Milan Bandi\u0107''' ({{IPA-hr|m\u01d0lan b\u00e2\u02d0ndit\u0361\u0255:|hr}} {{small|({{Audio-nohelp|Milanbandicname.ogg|listen}})}}; born 22 November 1955) is a Croatian politician currently serving his sixth term as [[List of mayors of Zagreb|mayor]] of the Croatian capital, [[Zagreb]], since 2005. Between 2000 and 2009, he was a prominent member of the [[Social Democratic Party of Croatia|Social Democratic Party]] (SDP). In 2007, he unsuccessfully ran for party president. However, he remained one of the main rivals of the former party president [[Zoran Milanovi\u0107]]. On 5 November 2009, he announced his intention to run for a president, in violation of the party's bylaws which led to his expulsion from the party.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/video--bandic-krenuo-u-utrku-milan-ce-igrati-lopte-u-svakom-selu/458485.aspx |title=Video - Bandi\u0107 krenuo u utrku: \"Milan \u0107e igrati lopte u svakom selu\" |author= |date=5 November 2009 |work= |publisher=[[Index.hr]] |accessdate=16 November 2011|language=hr}}</ref> On 10 January 2010, he lost the [[Croatian presidential election, 2009\u20132010|Croatian presidential election]] to the official SDP candidate [[Ivo Josipovi\u0107]] in the runoff elections.\n\nAlthough described in 2002 as the SDP's most popular politician for the \"famous 24 hours he devotes to the service of citizens of Zagreb\",<ref name=nin_omiljeni>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.nin.co.rs/2002-01/31/21760.html\n| title = Metropola bez gradona\u010delnika\n| date = 2002-01-31\n| last = Stanivukovi\u0107\n| first = Zoran\n| accessdate = 2008-09-19\n| work = [[\u041d\u0418\u041d]]\n| language = Serbian\n}}</ref> he has also gained notoriety for a number of actions and statements he has made as mayor.<ref name=javno_biografija/>\nBandi\u0107 is viewed as a hands-on mayor because of his ambition and the number of projects related to Zagreb that he has undertaken. He is widely credited{{fact|date=January 2020}} for the renovation of [[Ljubljanska Avenue]] (now [[Zagreba\u010dka Avenue]]), for his work on the [[Arena Zagreb]] and the [[Homeland Bridge]] (which opened during his third term).\n\nBandi\u0107 was arrested in the evening hours of 19 October 2014, along with 18 other officials, under the suspicion of malfeasance related to [[Zagreb Holding]]. In his absence, his deputy [[Sandra \u0160valjek]] took the duties of mayor from 19 October 2014 until 26 March 2015.<ref>http://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/Novosti/Hrvatska/tabid/66/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/279857/Bandi-opunomoio-Kusin-za-voenje-Zagreba.aspx</ref> Bandi\u0107 canceled the authorization that he granted to her because some disagreements between them.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/jutarnji-doznaje-uhicen-milan-bandic-/1229175/ |title=Uhi\u0107eni Milan Bandi\u0107! |last1=De\u0161kovi\u0107 |first1=Marin |date=2014-10-19 |website=Jutarnji list |publisher=Jutarnji list |accessdate=2014-10-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rtl.hr/vijesti/novosti/1367502/uhicen-milan-bandic-u-tijeku-pretraga-njegovog-stana/ |title=Uhi\u0107en Milan Bandi\u0107, u tijeku pretraga njegovog stana! |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2014-10-19 |website=RTL Televizija |publisher=RTL Televizija |accessdate=2014-10-19}}</ref> Consequently, \u0160valjek has resigned all of her duties in city. Bandi\u0107's second deputy Vesna Kusin took the duties of mayor on 26 March 2015. On 10 April 2015, Zagreb County Court ruled that Milan Bandi\u0107 has to be released from prison while pending trial. Consequently, he returned to the position of Mayor.<ref>http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/bandic-ostaje-na-slobodi-i-vraca-se-na-mjesto-gradonacelnika/812562.aspx</ref>\n\n==Private life==\nMilan Bandi\u0107 was born to Jozo and Blagica Bandi\u0107 ([[n\u00e9e]] Tomi\u0107) in the small [[Hamlet (place)|hamlet]] of Bandi\u0107a Brig, a part of Cerov Dolac in the municipality of [[Grude]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] (then [[PR Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[FPR Yugoslavia]]).<ref name=Bandic>Bandi\u0107, Milan. [http://www.milanbandiczagreb.com/Default.aspx?tabid=149 Biografija] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080424082908/http://www.milanbandiczagreb.com/Default.aspx?tabid=149 |date=2008-04-24}}. Bandi\u0107's official web site. Retrieved 2011-10-30 {{in lang|hr}}</ref> He was the middle child in the family, with an older brother Drago and a younger sister Tonka.<ref name=Barilar>{{cite news |title=Bandi\u0107: Od doseljenika s koferom do neprikosnovenog vladara Zagreba |author=Barilar, Suzana |url=http://www.jutarnji.hr/bandic--od-doseljenika-s-koferom-do-neprikosnovenog-vladara-zagreba/333515/ |newspaper=[[Jutarnji list]] |date=4 November 2009 |accessdate=20 November 2011|language=hr}}</ref> His family's main source of income was a [[tobacco plantation]]. As a child, Bandi\u0107 was altar servant in local church.<ref name=Bandic/> He attended [[Antun Branko \u0160imi\u0107]] High School in Grude and he was excellent student.<ref name=Barilar/> In 1974, he moved to Zagreb to study at the Department of Political Science at the [[University of Zagreb]]<ref name=Bandic/>, program of National defense and social self-protection (today non-existent). To pay off his [[student loan]]s he unloaded sugar and coal<ref name=Bandic/> and he was also a [[masonry|mason]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/bandicev-put-na-celo-zagreba-poceo-je-istovarom-secera-i-zbukanjem-fasada/778501.aspx | title=Bandi\u0107ev put na \u010delo Zagreba po\u010deo je istovarom \u0161e\u0107era i \u017ebukanjem fasada | date=19 October 2014 | work=[[Index.hr]] | language=Croatian | accessdate=14 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduation, Bandi\u0107 was conscripted to the [[Yugoslav People's Army]], and after that he was employed in [[Ledo (company)|Ledo]], producer of ice creams.<ref name=Bandic/>\n\nDuring his student days he met his wife Vesna.<ref name=Bandic/> He was married to her until their divorce in 1996, although they still live together in their [[Stara Pe\u0161\u010denica]] apartment. They have a daughter, Ana-Marija.<ref name=spouse_children>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak.aspx?id=248861\n | title = Bandi\u0107 se 1996. razveo zbog otkupa stana?\n | date = 2005-02-10\n | accessdate = 2008-08-01\n | work = Vijesti.net\n | language = Croatian}}</ref> Bandi\u0107 has stated that his divorce was the result of a seven-year separation.<ref name=spouse_children /> Bandi\u0107 owns two [[golden retriever]]s, Bil and Rudi, which he often walks during his work hours.<ref name=24sata_bil_operacija>{{cite web\n| url = http://damp.nsk.hr/arhiva/vol1/880/14301/www.24sata.hr/articles/view/48239/index.html\n| title = Bandi\u0107ev Bil ide na kemoterapiju?\n| date = 2007-03-22\n| last = Vukadin\n| first = Romana\n| accessdate = 2008-08-03\n| work = [[24 sata (Croatia)|24 sata]]\n| language = Croatian\n}}</ref><ref name=bil_rudi>{{cite journal |date=2008-08-04 |title=Bandi\u0107u u dom sti\u017ee retriver Rudi |trans-title=Retriever Rudi arrives in Bandi\u0107 home |journal=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |issue=664 |language=Croatian |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/47766/8/ |accessdate=2008-08-06 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68oppVAzh?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/47766/bandicu-u-dom-stize-retriver-rudi |archivedate=1 July 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBandi\u0107 is an avid distance runner, describing himself as \"addicted to running\".<ref>{{cite news | title=Ne bojim se, imam jo\u0161 mnogo kilometara za pretr\u010dati| work=[[Jutarnji list]] | date=July 28, 2009 | language=Croatian | quote=Mogu re\u0107i da sam ovisan o tr\u010danju i da je to moja droga.}}</ref> He is reported to run 10 kilometers every weekday morning,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.javno.com/en-croatia/photo--zagreb-mayor-turns-pilgrimage-into-marathon_182355 | title=PHOTO: Zagreb Mayor Turns Pilgrimage Into Marathon | work=javno.com | first=Ivan | last=Kova\u010d | date=September 15, 2008 | accessdate=2009-08-23 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090520043315/http://www.javno.com/en-croatia/photo--zagreb-mayor-turns-pilgrimage-into-marathon_182355 | archivedate=May 20, 2009}}</ref> and in March 2008 completed the 61&nbsp;km [[Zagreb]]\u2013[[\u010cazma]] [[ultramarathon]].\n\n==Political career==\n{{POV section|date=April 2020}}\n==={{anchor|Before becoming a mayor}}Before becoming mayor===\nAfter serving the army and short work in [[Ledo (company)|Ledo company]] Bandi\u0107 was employed in Municipal Committee of [[League of Communists of Croatia]] in [[Pe\u0161\u010denica \u2013 \u017ditnjak|Pe\u0161\u0107enica]] where he worked as professional political worker.<ref name=Bandic/><ref name=Barilar/>\n\nAfter collapse of [[Socialist Federative Republic of Yugoslavia|SFR Yugoslavia]] and [[League of Communists of Croatia]] Bandi\u0107 did not want to leave the party because he worked for years in Pe\u0161\u010denica and thus it was matter of pride.<ref name=Bandic/> He expressed his hopes that he and his colleagues will return to political stage as Croatian social democrats.<ref name=Bandic/>\n\nDuring the [[Croatian War of Independence]] Bandi\u0107 helped with logistics.<ref name=Bandic/>\n\nBandi\u0107 was one of the few [[Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Herzegovinian Croats]] to remain with the party after the [[1990 Croatian parliamentary election|first democratic elections in 1990]] in which the Communist Party, led by [[Ivica Ra\u010dan]], reformed and re-branded itself as the [[Social Democratic Party of Croatia]] (SDP). He demonstrated organizational ability and populist political instincts. These abilities allowed the SDP to gain in Zagreb blue-collar neighborhoods and attract votes which the [[Croatian Democratic Union]] (HDZ) and its then-president [[Franjo Tu\u0111man]] had considered theirs by default. As such, he proved to be a valuable asset for the Social Democratic Party. In 1993 he became party secretary.<ref name=Barilar/>\n\nConflict between HDZ and SDP manifested in the [[1995 Croatian parliamentary election|1995 parliamentary]] and City of [[Zagreb]] elections, leading to the [[Zagreb Crisis]]: an electoral alliance (in which the SDP was a major partner) won a majority in the Zagreb elections and chose [[Goran Grani\u0107]] as the new mayor, but Franjo Tu\u0111man used a legal loophole to stop Grani\u0107 from taking office. Several subsequent elections were held, with the SDP winning each time and Tu\u0111man promptly removing every candidate. For a time Zagreb was a city without a mayor, which led to public unrest and protests in [[Ban Jela\u010di\u0107 Square]]. With the final 1997 election of the HDZ candidate [[Marina Matulovi\u0107-Dropuli\u0107]] as the mayor of Zagreb, the crisis faded. Bandi\u0107 played a role in the crisis by becoming a city councilman in 1995 and the leader of the Zagreb SDP in 1997.<ref name=javno_biografija>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.javno.com/hr/hrvatska/clanak.php?id=49365\n |title       = Biografija: Milan Bandi\u0107\n |date        = 2007-06-02\n |accessdate  = 2008-08-01\n |work        = Javno.hr\n |language    = Croatian\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/68EJ2pyfI?url=http://dalje.com/hr-hrvatska/biografija--milan-bandic/49365\n |archivedate = 2012-06-06\n}}</ref>\n\nDuring the first campaign his [[Herzegovina|Herzegovinian]] background became an issue, as the [[Croatian Peasant Party]] (HSS) suggested that only a native citizen of Zagreb could become the city's mayor. HSS also launched a propaganda campaign against [[Herzegovinians]] in an effort to undermine Bandi\u0107's campaign. The party hoped that the majority of Zagreb voters would turn away from Bandi\u0107. Those expectations were not fulfilled and Bandi\u0107 later used his Herzegovinian background as an advantage, broadening his support among the ordinary citizens of Zagreb.\n\nThe HDZ under Bandi\u0107 eventually lost power in the Croatian capital in 2000.<ref name=Barilar/>\n\n==={{anchor|First and second term (2000\u20132002)}}First and second terms (2000\u20132002)===\n{{see also|2000 Zagreb local elections|2001 Zagreb local elections}}\n\nBandi\u0107 was elected [[mayor]] of Zagreb in 2000<ref name=izbori>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.zgizbori.hr/2000Lokalni/izbori_2000_.html\n | title = Izbori odr\u017eani 7. svibnja 2000.\n | work = Gradski zavod za automatsku obradu podataka\n | accessdate = 2008-07-27\n | language = Croatian\n | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100129103926/http://www.zgizbori.hr/2000Lokalni/izbori_2000_.html\n | archive-date = 2010-01-29\n | url-status = dead\n}}</ref> and re-elected in the city election in 2001.<ref name=izbori_2001>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.zgizbori.hr/2001Lokalni/rezultati.html\n| title = Izbori odr\u017eani 20. svibnja 2001.\n| work = City Bureau for Automatic Data Processing\n| accessdate = 2008-08-04\n| language = Croatian\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080316190322/http://www.zgizbori.hr/2001Lokalni/rezultati.html\n| archive-date = 2008-03-16\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref> His rise in influence among SDP politicians and on the Zagreb political scene created a backlash by the [[Croatian People's Party]] (HNS), the other left-of-center party led by [[Vesna Pusi\u0107]], who did not trust his nationalist populism and his occasional run-ins with the courts. The HNS campaigned against the SDP in the 2000 elections. However, the HNS entered into a coalition with the SDP in 2001. It governed Zagreb with the SDP until 2005 when it withdrew, again because of Bandi\u0107.\n\nIn 2002, Bandi\u0107 fled from the scene of a motor vehicle accident while under the influence of alcohol. He tried to bribe the officer who stopped him and threatened the officer with his alleged connections in the [[Ministry of the Interior (Croatia)|Ministry of the Interior]]. The incident was heavily covered by the media that asked for his resignation. The SDP was at first reluctant to sanction Bandi\u0107. Under public pressure, the SDP leadership compelled Bandi\u0107 to resign.<ref name=resignation>{{cite web| url = http://www.hsp1861.hr/vijesti2/020121jl.htm| title = Bandi\u0107eva ostavka - pobjeda javnosti| accessdate = 2008-07-27| last = Lovri\u0107| first = Jelena| date = 2002-01-21| work = [[Novi list]]| language = Croatian}}</ref><ref name=scandals_drunk_driving>{{cite web| url = http://www.hsp1861.hr/vijesti7/060118vm.htm| title = Esdepeovci zgro\u017eeni pona\u0161anjem Bandi\u0107a| accessdate = 2007-09-29| last = Mazzocco| first = Vojislav| date = 2006-01-18| work = [[Ve\u010dernji list]]| language = Croatian}}</ref><ref name=index_policemen>{{cite web| url = http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak.aspx?id=391401| title = Kako se rije\u0161iti policajca koji radi svoj posao| accessdate = 2008-09-21| last = Mazzocco| first = Vojislav| date = 2008-06-17| work = Vijesti.net| language = Croatian}}</ref> After his resignation there was uncertainty concerning his successor; while the Zagreb SDP had the right to nominate the mayor, it was so dominated by Bandi\u0107 that it was questionable who could replace him.<ref name=resignation /> Eventually [[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]] took over as mayor, while Bandi\u0107 retained a place in the Zagreb chain of command as deputy mayor. He was eager to become a mayor again, and blocked Pavi\u0107's development plans (advancing his own) while working toward an early election.<ref name=scandals_cursing_pavic /><ref name=\"savez_desni\u010dari\">{{cite journal\n |url         = http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/10596/\n |title       = Bandi\u0107 s desni\u010darima ru\u0161i Vlastu Pavi\u0107\n |date        = 2003-05-27\n |accessdate  = 2008-08-02\n |last        = Babi\u0107\n |first       = Jelena\n |issue       = 393\n |journal     = [[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]]\n |language    = Croatian\n |trans-title = Bandi\u0107 and right-wingers brings down Vlasta Pavi\u0107\n |archivedate = 30 June 2012\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/68oWiX4IA?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/10596/bandic-s-desnicarima-rusi-vlastu-pavic\n}}</ref><ref name=\"pavi\u0107_deal\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/10895/ |title=Vlasta Pavi\u0107 u zamjenu za primirje ustupa mjesto Bandi\u0107u |last=Jelini\u0107 |first=Berislav |language=Croatian |trans-title=Vlasta Pavi\u0107 steps down for Bandi\u0107 in exchange for a truce |work=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |date=24 February 2004 |accessdate=30 June 2012 |archivedate=30 June 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68oY6G8Cg?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/10895/vlasta-pavic-u-zamjenu-za-primirje-ustupa-mjesto-bandicu |url-status=dead}}</ref> In response [[Ivica Ra\u010dan]] (head of the SDP) tried to restrain Bandi\u0107's activities.<ref name=\"ra\u010dan_upozorenje\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/10240/ |title=Ra\u010dan poti\u010de Vlastu Pavi\u0107 da vlada bez Bandi\u0107a |date=15 May 2002 |last=Ple\u0161e |first=Mladen |accessdate=30 June 2012 |work=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |language=Croatian |trans-title=Ra\u010dan urges Vlasta Pavi\u0107 to govern without Bandi\u0107 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68oWJlgkS?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/10240/racan-potice-vlastu-pavic-da-vlada-bez-bandica |archivedate=30 June 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\nThe rules then in force would not allow Bandi\u0107 to have a second term as mayor during the current term of the assembly.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/10985/racan-ustuknuo-pred-bandicevim-divljastvom |publisher=[[Nacional (weekly)]] |title=Ra\u010dan ustuknuo pred Bandi\u0107evim divlja\u0161tvom |trans-title=Ra\u010dan taken aback by Bandi\u0107's savage remark |language=Croatian |author=Berislav Jelini\u0107 |date=4 May 2004 |accessdate=1 July 2012 |archivedate=1 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68pZwx7NY?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/10985/racan-ustuknuo-pred-bandicevim-divljastvom}}</ref> Vlasta Pavi\u0107 attempted to strike a deal ending the ongoing feud, but Bandi\u0107 eventually succeeded in undermining her. Although no early elections were held, he was re-elected mayor in [[2005 Zagreb mayoral elections|the May 15, 2005 elections]].<ref name=izbori_2005>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.zgizbori.hr/2005Lokalni/zgizbori_zg_a/rezultati/r06_021_0021_000.html\n| title = Rezultati glasovanja za izbor \u010dlanova Gradske skup\u0161tine Grada Zagreba (\"Voting results for the election of Municipal Councillors to the City of Zagreb\")\n| date = 2005-05-16\n| accessdate = 2008-08-01\n| language = Croatian\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110721102953/http://www.zgizbori.hr/2005Lokalni/zgizbori_zg_a/rezultati/r06_021_0021_000.html\n| archive-date = 2011-07-21\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref><ref name=\"pavi\u0107_deal\" />\n\nIn April 2004 then-mayor [[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]] criticized Bandi\u0107 for having spent 15 million [[kuna (currency)|kunas]] (about [[USD|US$]]3.26 million) of city money to buy a lot on [[Vjekoslav Heinzel Avenue|Heinzelova Avenue]] which was formerly owned by the [[meat packing industry|meat packing plant]] Zagrep\u010danka. The controversy was dubbed \"the Zagrep\u010danka case\" by the newspapers.<ref name=scandals_cursing_pavic /><ref name=scandals_drunk_driving /> The city government could not use the lot, because its ownership was divided among 43 individuals. When (responding to a question from a city counselor) Mayor Pavi\u0107 distanced herself from Bandi\u0107, Bandi\u0107 was accused of cursing her mother in a vulgar way during the talks.<ref name=scandals_cursing_pavic>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.index.hr/clanak.aspx?id=199287\n| title = Milan Bandi\u0107 opsovao majku zagreba\u010dkoj gradona\u010delnici\n| accessdate = 2007-09-29\n| date = 2004-04-28\n| work = Vijesti.net\n| language = Croatian\n}}</ref><ref name=scandals_drunk_driving /> He also published a newspaper advertisement on behalf of the city government, entitled ''Istina je!'' (\"It's true!\"). The advertisement was supported by all SDP members of the city council except [[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]], the mayor at that time. [[Ivica Ra\u010dan]] later condemned the advertisement as a political mistake, telling the Zagreb SDP that they would face consequences for their action.<ref name=zagrepcanka_indictment/>\n\nA court case ensued, with charges being brought against Bandi\u0107 and others involved.<ref name=zagrepcanka_indictment>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.hrt.hr/arhiv/2004/05/10/HRT0037.html\n |title       = Kaznena prijava protiv Bandi\u0107a, Buluma i nekih \u010dlanova poglavarstva zbog oglasa ''Istina je!''\n |date        = 2004-05-10\n |publisher   = [[Croatian Radio Television]]\n |language    = Croatian\n |accessdate  = 2008-04-30\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20160303170804/http://www.hrt.hr/arhiv/2004/05/10/HRT0037.html\n |archivedate = 2016-03-03\n}}</ref> Three years later, Bandi\u0107 was acquitted and the City of Zagreb was awarded ownership of the Zagrep\u010danka lot in a [[judgment (law)|court judgment]]. Bandi\u0107 promised a new [[business district]] in the Zagrep\u010danka location.<ref name=city_centar_zagrepcanka>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=49358\n |title       = Zagreb To Get A City Centre\n |date        = 2007-06-02\n |accessdate  = 2008-09-28\n |work        = Javno.hr\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070612235956/http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=49358\n |archivedate = 2007-06-12\n}}</ref>\n\nNot all legal troubles have been solved, however, as the city still has to deal with unsolved cases and complaints entered against the lot.<ref name=plomba>{{cite web\n |url        = http://www.javno.com/hr/zagreb/clanak.php?id=186305\n |archive-url = https://archive.is/20130126200636/http://www.javno.com/hr/zagreb/clanak.php?id=186305\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 2013-01-26\n |title      = Bandi\u0107 isplatio ovrhu za Zagrep\u010danku - 3 mil kuna\n |date       = 2008-09-26\n |accessdate = 2008-09-28\n |work       = Javno.hr\n |language   = Croatian\n}}</ref> In 2008 the sale of the Zagrep\u010danka lot to [[Institut IGH]] was announced, but the deal fell through in 2009; this has potential to incur a cost of \u20ac4.5&nbsp;million to the Zagreb [[holding company]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.poslovni.hr/133686.aspx | title = Ivo \u010covi\u0107 ipak potpisao \u0161tetan ugovor s Radi\u0107em? | language = Croatian | work = [[Poslovni dnevnik]] | date = December 4, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Third term (2005\u20132009)===\n{{see also|2005 Zagreb local elections}}\n\nFollowing the illness and death of Ra\u010dan Bandi\u0107 announced his candidacy for SDP leadership,<ref name=nacional_kandidatura>{{cite journal\n |url         = http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/34638/\n |title       = Obra\u010dun Bandi\u0107a i Milanovi\u0107a odlu\u010duje o \u0161efu SDP-a\n |trans-title = Conflict of Bandi\u0107 and Milanovi\u0107 to decide leader of the SDP\n |date        = 2007-05-21\n |last        = Bajru\u0161i\n |first       = Robert\n |accessdate  = 2008-08-04\n |issue       = 601\n |journal     = [[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]]\n |language    = Croatian\n |archivedate = 30 June 2012\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/68ohfBem2?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/34638/obracun-bandica-i-milanovica-odlucuje-o-sefu-sdp-a\n |url-status  = dead\n}}</ref> planning to resign as mayor afterwards. He competed against [[\u017deljka Antunovi\u0107]], [[Zoran Milanovi\u0107]] and [[Tonino Picula]]. [[Zoran Milanovi\u0107]] was elected on 2 June 2007 as the new SDP leader, while Bandi\u0107 remained mayor of Zagreb.<ref name=milanovic>{{cite journal\n |url         = http://www.nacional.hr/en/articles/view/35122/\n |title       = Milanovi\u0107 widens his base\n |accessdate  = 2007-09-30\n |last        = Bajru\u0161i\n |first       = Robert\n |date        = 2007-06-06\n |archivedate = 25 July 2012\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/69QLPJQhh?url=http://www.nacional.hr/en/clanak/35122/milanovic-widens-his-base\n |issue       = 603\n |journal     = [[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]]\n}}</ref> He did not give up the fight, however, organizing opposition within the party and campaigning to defeat Milanovi\u0107 in the next party election.<ref name=\"revolt_milanovi\u0107\">{{cite journal\n |url         = http://www.nacional.hr/en/articles/view/40824/\n |title       = Revolt against Milanovi\u0107\n |accessdate  = 2008-07-28\n |archivedate = 25 July 2012\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/69QLV04ei?url=http://www.nacional.hr/en/clanak/40824/revolt-against-milanovic\n |last        = Bajru\u0161i\n |first       = Robert\n |date        = 2007-12-12\n |issue       = 630\n |journal     = [[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]]\n}}</ref><ref name=\"milanovi\u0107_obra\u010dun\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/Hrvatska/tabid/66/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/11033/Default.aspx\n| title = Milanovi\u0107 krenuo u obra\u010dun s Bandi\u0107em\n| accessdate = 2008-07-28\n| last = Karlovi\u0107-Saboti\u0107\n| first = Marina\n| date = 2008-06-12\n| work = [[Slobodna Dalmacija]]\n| language = Croatian\n}}</ref>\n\nA controversy arose on 31 July 2005, when Bandi\u0107 was on a bus with 30 other people and saw workers waving on the street. He then allegedly cited the [[Arbeit macht frei|Auschwitz motto]]: \"Work liberates, the Nazis weren't totally dumb.\" Hrvoje Kre\u0161i\u0107, a ''[[Novi list]]'' journalist, allegedly heard Bandi\u0107 and published his statement. The following day Bandi\u0107 threatened to sue Kre\u0161i\u0107 and ''Novi list''; he claimed he said \"Marxists,\" not \"Nazis\". Bandi\u0107's statement was corroborated by several of his nearby colleagues; other journalists at the rear of the bus did not hear anything said by Bandi\u0107, due to noise inside the vehicle. Bandi\u0107 said that if awarded [[damages]], he would donate the money to the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]]. The director of the center, [[Efraim Zuroff]], refused.<ref name=zuroff_auschwitz />\n\nIn January 2006, Bandi\u0107 publicly threatened a journalist working for ''[[Ve\u010dernji list]]''. The journalist asked Bandi\u0107 about an offer from a [[Czech Republic|Czech]] company; Bandi\u0107 replied aggressively, cursing and threatening the journalist. Afterwards, he claimed he had simply spoken to the journalist in a loud voice.<ref name=threatened_journalist />\n\nAs of October 2007 Bandi\u0107 was under investigation by the [[USKOK]] (Office for the Suppression of Corruption and Organized Crime) about several deals he made as mayor of Zagreb, including the July 2007 exchange of a lot at the intersection of Maksimirska Street and [[Gojko \u0160u\u0161ak Avenue|\u0160u\u0161ak Avenue]] for a lot in [[Sesvetski Kraljevec]]. A court-appointed expert allowed the exchange at a price of 1,300 kuna per square meter (\u20ac185) for the Sesvete lot (located in the suburbs, outside the [[Zagreb bypass]]) and 2,300 kuna (\u20ac321) for the Maksimirska lot (located in the [[Maksimir]] district, several hundred meters from downtown). New experts considered the lot on Maksimirska Street to be more valuable than the lot in Sesvetski Kraljevec. Thus, a USKOK source testified that Bandi\u0107 made a deal damaging to the city budget. The two companies with whom Bandi\u0107 dealt were headed by inexperienced students, furthering the appearance of impropriety.<ref name=bandic_index_uskok>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=86401\n |title       = Bandi\u0107 Under Investigation For Corruption\n |accessdate  = 2008-09-28\n |date        = 2007-10-03\n |work        = Javno.hr\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071004041519/http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=86401\n |archivedate = 2007-10-04\n}}</ref><ref name=uskok>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak.aspx?id=360440\n| title = Bandi\u0107 o istrazi USKOK-a: Neka institucije rade svoj posao\n| accessdate = 2008-02-16\n| date = 2007-10-03\n| work = Vijesti.net\n| language = Croatian\n}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 June 2008 the Main Committee of SDP received a letter entitled ''Za \u0161to se, uop\u0107e, danas zala\u017ee SDP?'' (\"What, overall, does the SDP stand for today?\") by [[Dra\u017een Lali\u0107]] (a Croatian [[sociologist]]) which attacked Bandi\u0107 by pointing out his misdeeds and errors and questioning Bandi\u0107's loyalty to the SDP's principles. The letter was sparked partially by the [[assault]] and [[Battery (crime)|battery]] of anti-corruption Zagreb road-authorities director Igor Ra\u0111enovi\u0107, which had not been properly investigated. Another reason was a concert held on [[Ban Jela\u010di\u0107 Square]] by [[Marko Perkovi\u0107 Thompson]], a singer known to attract an [[Usta\u0161e|usta\u0161a]] audience. Bandi\u0107 supported the concert instead of condemning it, inaccordance with SDP anti-nationalistic principles. Although the letter attacked the SDP as a whole, Bandi\u0107 was considered a key participant in all events described. Bandi\u0107 responded to the letter indirectly by encouraging the police to do their job, while failing to appropriately defend his position.<ref name=lalic_letter>{{cite journal\n| last = Cigoj\n| first = Mark\n|author2=Galovi\u0107, Alen\n| title = Pismo koje potresa SDP\n| journal = [[Globus (weekly)|Globus]]\n| issue = 918\n| pages =18\u201322\n| url = http://www.globus.com.hr\n| date = 2008-07-11\n| accessdate = 2008-07-12\n}}</ref><ref name=\"lali\u0107_ve\u010dernji\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.vecernji.hr/newsroom/news/croatia/3123249/index.do \n |title=Javne osobe pisale Milanovi\u0107u da zaustavi Bandi\u0107a \n |last=Popovi\u0107 \n |first=Jasmina \n |date=2008-07-09 \n |accessdate=2008-08-02 \n |work=[[Ve\u010dernji list]] \n |language=Croatian \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080731053802/http://www.vecernji.hr/newsroom/news/croatia/3123249/index.do \n |archivedate=2008-07-31 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> Zoran Milanovi\u0107 responded instead, accusing Lali\u0107 of trying to buy himself a return to the Croatian political scene. Bandi\u0107 thus received the SDP's support, ensuring his candidacy in the upcoming 2009 mayoral election.<ref name=\"milanovi\u0107_fights_back\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/47300/ |title=Pismo koje je u\u010dvrstilo Bandi\u0107a |author1=Bajru\u0161i, Robert |trans-title=A letter that strengthened Bandi\u0107 |author2=Gaura, Orhidea |date=2008-07-14 |accessdate=2008-08-02 |issue=661 |journal=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |language=Croatian |archivedate=30 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68oon0FPx?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/47300/pismo-koje-je-ucvrstilo-bandica}}</ref>\n\nBandi\u0107 was involved in the ''Cvjetni prolaz'' case (a lengthy affair beginning in 2007), which centered on the controversial demolition and conversion of historical buildings in Petar Preradovi\u0107 Square into a [[shopping mall]] in Zagreb's [[Donji grad (Zagreb)|Lower Town]] area.<ref name=cg_intro_nac>{{cite web |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/30633/5/ |title=Preobra\u017eenska 6 i kino Zagreb nisu spomenici |accessdate=2008-05-16 |date=2007-01-15 |work=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |last=Cviti\u0107 |first=Plamenko |language=Croatian |trans-title=Preobra\u017eenska 6 and Cinema Zagreb are no monuments |archivedate=30 June 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68og8jEQ3?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/30633/preobrazenska-6-i-kino-zagreb-nisu-spomenici |url-status=dead}}</ref> The project was headed by developer Tomislav Horvatin\u010di\u0107, who was alleged to have used illegal means in an attempt to [[evict]] the buildings' residents. These residents included a headquarters and church operated by the Zagreb-Ljubljana [[metropolitan bishop|metropolia]] of the [[Serbian Orthodox Church]] and the home of the late poet [[Vladimir Vidri\u0107]].<ref name=orthodox /> Bandi\u0107 is known to be a strong supporter of Horvatin\u010di\u0107,<ref name=cp_gi_popov /> publicly criticizing opponents of the project.<ref name=cp_dnevnik_b_swearing /> In August 2008, Horvatin\u010di\u0107 obtained a license to demolish the old buildings. Residents of the surrounding buildings and [[environmentalists]] argued that the license was improperly issued, but the demolition is (as of 2011) still underway. However, Horvatin\u010di\u0107 is forbidden to demolish Vidri\u0107's home or build any part of the project until he obtains a building-location license, which requires him to prove he can build a walkway between Gunduli\u0107eva Street and Cvjetni Square.\n\nIn 2009. Croatian media revealed that Bandi\u0107 spent 1,55 million kuna (210 000 \u20ac) of city money to build two public toilets.<ref name=\"tportal.hr\">{{cite news|url=https://www.tportal.hr/vijesti/clanak/bandicev-kum-izgradio-najskuplji-wc-u-hrvatskoj-20090318|title=Bandi\u0107ev kum izgradio najskuplji WC u Hrvatskoj|work=tportal.hr|access-date=2017-05-12}}</ref> The media mockingly called these \"The Golden Toilets\".<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite news|url=https://www.tportal.hr/vijesti/clanak/i-bandicevi-zlatni-wc-i-dosli-na-tapetu-uskoka-20131230|title=I Bandi\u0107evi zlatni WC-i do\u0161li na tapetu Uskoka|work=tportal.hr|access-date=2017-05-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vecernji.hr/zagreb/davor-jelavic-pod-istragom-zbog-bandicevih-zlatnih-wc-a-912533|title=Davor Jelavi\u0107 pod istragom zbog Bandi\u0107evih 'zlatnih' WC-a|access-date=2017-05-12|language=hr}}</ref> The media wrote that the job was given to the company [[T\u017dV Gredelj]], specialized for construction of railway veichles without any tender. Gredelj then hired another company owned by Bandi\u0107's godfather to do the actual construction.<ref name=\"tportal.hr\"/> In 2013. [[USKOK|Croatian State Prosecutor's Office for the Suppression of Organized Crime and Corruption]] announced that they are investigating the case.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n===Fourth term (2009\u20132013)===\n{{see also|2009 Zagreb local elections}}\nUntil 2009, the mayor of Zagreb was elected by the city assembly ([[city council]]). In [[2009 Zagreb local elections|elections held in the spring of 2009]], the mayor was directly elected for the first time. Bandi\u0107 was forced into a second round not by HDZ candidate ([[Jasen Mesi\u0107]]) but by outsider [[Josip Kregar]] (dean of the Faculty of Law at the [[University of Zagreb]]), who ran on an independent platform. Bandi\u0107 won the second round, with 62 percent of the vote to Kregar's 37 percent. In October 2009, Bandi\u0107 visited the site of a World War II [[Yugoslav Partisans|partisan]] massacre on the island of [[Daksa (Dubrovnik)|Daksa]] with the [[Croatian Bishops' Conference]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.slobodnadalmacija.hr/Dubrovnik/tabid/75/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/75337/Default.aspx | title=Daksa kod Dubrovnika: biskupi molili za \u017ertve komunisti\u010dkog terora - do\u0161ao i Milan Bandi\u0107 | work=[[Slobodna Dalmacija]] | date=October 21, 2009 | language=Croatian | accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> On 29 October 2009 Bandi\u0107's proposed exceptional budget, with a proposal to hold a referendum on the building of a new football stadium, was rejected. Among those voting against the budget was his own party, the SDP.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hrt.hr/index.php?id=48&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=51872&tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=38&cHash=8a5414470f | title=I SDP protiv Bandi\u0107a | date=October 29, 2009 | work=hrt.hr | publisher=[[Croatian Radiotelevision]] | language=Croatian | accessdate=2009-12-26 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100302221451/http://www.hrt.hr/index.php?id=48 | archivedate=March 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Presidential campaign===\n[[File:Milan bandi\u0107 poster.JPG|thumb|240px|Pro-Bandi\u0107 billboard during second round of 2009\u20132010 presidential [[Croatian presidential election, 2009\u20132010|elections]]|alt=Pro-Bandi\u0107 billboard in parking lot, with blue and red letters on white background]]\nOn 5 November 2009 Bandi\u0107 announced his presidential candidacy in the [[Croatian presidential election, 2009\u20132010|2009\u20132010 presidential election]] after media speculation. Bandi\u0107's move resulted in his automatic expulsion from the [[Social Democratic Party of Croatia]] and the loss of his positions as party president and leader of the Zagreb branch. He was replaced as leader of the Zagreb SDP by [[Davor Bernardi\u0107]].<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.hrt.hr/index.php?id=48&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=75175&tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=34&cHash=098abf8794\n| title = HRT: Bernardi\u0107 na \u010delu zagreba\u010dkog SDP-a\n| year = 2010\n| accessdate = 2010-06-29\n}}</ref>\n\nIn the 27 December 2009 first round of the election Bandi\u0107 received 14.83 percent of the vote, placing him in second place after SDP candidate [[Ivo Josipovi\u0107]] (with 32.7 percent). On 10 January he lost the second round with 39.74 percent of the vote.\nIn Zagreb Bandi\u0107 lost both rounds of the election, receiving support in only a handful of city neighbourhoods.<ref>{{cite web | work = Zagrebancija.com | url = http://www.zagrebancija.com/hr-aktualnosti/kako-je-milan-bandic-izgubio-povjerenje-zagreba_287999 | language = Croatian | title = Detaljna analiza kraha - Kako je Milan Bandi\u0107 izgubio povjerenje Zagreba | date = December 30, 2009 | accessdate = January 16, 2010 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100120181034/http://www.zagrebancija.com/hr-aktualnosti/kako-je-milan-bandic-izgubio-povjerenje-zagreba_287999 | archivedate = January 20, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | newspaper = [[Ve\u010dernji list]] | url = http://www.vecernji.hr/vijesti/josipovic-potukao-bandica-gotovo-svim-zagrebackim-cetvrtima-clanak-77273 | language = Croatian | title = Donja Dubrava i Brezovica jedine Bandi\u0107eve \u010detvrti - Josipovi\u0107 potukao Bandi\u0107a u gotovo svim zagreba\u010dkim \u010detvrtima | date = January 10, 2010 | accessdate = January 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Parliamentary election of 2011===\nOn 8 October 2011 Bandi\u0107 announced that he will compete in [[2011 Croatian parliamentary election|Croatian parliamentary election of 2011]] with independent list named \"Stijena\" ({{lang-en|Rock}}).<ref name=VL>[http://www.vecernji.hr/vijesti/bandic-izbore-ide-neovisnom-listom-koju-je-nazvao-stijena-clanak-334146 Bandi\u0107 na izbore ide s neovisnom listom koju je nazvao Stijena]. [[Ve\u010dernji list]], 2011-10-08. Retrieved 2011-10-30 {{in lang|hr}}</ref>\n\n===Fifth term (2013\u20132017)===\n{{See also|2013 Zagreb local elections}}\nBandi\u0107 was arrested on 19 October 2014 on charges of corruption, bribery and organized crime, along with two other key members of the Zagreb city council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/uhicen-milan-bandic/778492.aspx |title=Uhi\u0107en Milan Bandi\u0107 |accessdate=19 October 2014 |language=Croatian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://ca.reuters.com/article/topNews/idCAKCN0I80Q420141019|title=Croatian police arrest Zagreb mayor on corruption charges|date=19 October 2014|agency=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Sixth term (2017\u2013present)===\n{{See also|2017 Zagreb local elections}}\n\n==Mayoral achievements==\n[[File:Milan Bandi\u0107 2009.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Bandi\u0107 at the [[Snow Queen Trophy]], January 2009|alt=Bandi\u0107 smiling and looking to his right, wearing blue-and-white skiing jersey over brown long-sleeved shirt]]\n[[File:Zagrebacka Avenija, Zagreb.JPG|thumb|right|Renovated [[Zagreba\u010dka Avenue]]|alt=Aerial view of eight-lane highway]]\nOne of Bandi\u0107's best-known projects is the renovation of [[Ljubljanska Avenue]], whose eastern stretch beginning at Svilkovi\u0107i Street (later Savska Opatovina Rotary) was later renamed to [[Zagreba\u010dka Avenue]].<ref name=komunalni_lj-zg>{{cite journal\n |url=http://193.198.60.202/komunalni/arhiva/338/str04.pdf \n |title=Zastupnici skratili Ljubljansku \n |last=Kos Bu\u010dar \n |first=Dajana \n |language=Croatian \n |date=2006-10-11 \n |accessdate=2008-07-24 \n |journal=Zagreba\u010dki komunalni vjesnik \n |issue=338 \n |format=PDF, 108 KB \n |page=4 \n |issn=1845-4968 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110529140837/http://193.198.60.202/komunalni/arhiva/338/str04.pdf \n |archivedate=2011-05-29 \n}}</ref> He is also credited with the Zagreb model apartment building ({{lang-hr|Zagreba\u010dki model stanogradnje}}), also locally known as ''Bandi\u0107evi stanovi'' (\"Bandi\u0107's apartments\").<ref name=\"\u0161pansko_zms\" /> [[Radimir \u010ca\u010di\u0107]], another investor in the Zagreb apartment market, accused Bandi\u0107 of trying to undermine the statewide POS housing projects. POS ({{lang-hr|POticana Stanogradnja}}, \"subsidized apartments\") is cheap housing instituted by Radimir \u010ca\u010di\u0107 during the coalition of SDP, Bandi\u0107's party, and several other parties (such as \u010ca\u010di\u0107's HNS, which ruled the Croatian government from 2000 to 2003).<ref name=\"\u0161pansko_zms\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.spansko.net/vijesti.php?id=662\n| title = Zagreba\u010dki model stanogradnje\n| date = 2004-05-18\n| accessdate = 2008-08-03\n| work = \u0160pansko.net\n| language = Croatian\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110629150931/http://www.spansko.net/vijesti.php?id=662\n| archive-date = 2011-06-29\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref><ref name=hrt_zms>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.hrt.hr/arhiv/2002/02/22/HRT0010.html\n |title       = Milan Bandi\u0107 najavio zagreba\u010dki model stanogradnje\n |date        = 2002-02-22\n |accessdate  = 2008-08-03\n |work        = [[Croatian Radiotelevision]]\n |language    = Croatian\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304091952/http://www.hrt.hr/arhiv/2002/02/22/HRT0010.html\n |archivedate = 2016-03-04\n}}</ref>\n\nBandi\u0107 has heavily criticized the state of [[Transport in Zagreb|Zagreb's transportation system]] which he encountered at the beginning of his mayoral career.<ref name=jeza>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.javno.com/hr/zagreb/clanak.php?id=139391\n |title       = Bandi\u0107: Hvata me jeza zbog Remetine\u010dkog rotora\n |date        = 2008-04-10\n |accessdate  = 2008-09-29\n |work        = Javno.hr\n |language    = Croatian\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080412093330/http://www.javno.com/hr/zagreb/clanak.php?id=139391\n |archivedate = 2008-04-12\n}}</ref> With the guidance of Zagreb traffic engineers Bandi\u0107 has approved ambitious transportation projects in Zagreb, such as the Ljubljanska/Zagreba\u010dka Avenue widening, [[Homeland Bridge]] construction, renovation of the [[green wave]] system in the city center with the addition of [[bicycle path]]s and multi-level underground [[parking garages]] at [[Tu\u0161kanac]], [[Kvaternik Square]] and other locations. An important project begun during Bandi\u0107's term in office is the Zagreb [[light rail|metro]], which is planned to become the main suburban transportation mode to the city.<ref name=metro>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.neuron.at/64_Kolic-Marenjak-Skendr_e_09.2006.pdf\n |format      = PDF\n |title       = Design concept and financing of the light rail Zagreb project\n |date        = 2006-09-22\n |last1       = Koli\u0107\n |first1      = Davorin\n |last2       = Marenjak\n |first2      = Sa\u0161a\n |last3       = Skendrovi\u0107\n |first3      = Vladimir\n |accessdate  = 2008-09-26\n |work        = Neuron Consulting Engineers\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070711211147/http://www.neuron.at/64_Kolic-Marenjak-Skendr_e_09.2006.pdf\n |archivedate = 2007-07-11\n}}</ref> Bandi\u0107 has arranged the construction of the [[Arena Zagreb]], a [[team handball|handball]] arena located in [[Lani\u0161te, Croatia|Lani\u0161te]], which was constructed to prepare the city for the [[2009 World Men's Handball Championship]].<ref name=arena_sanader>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak.aspx?id=344911\n| title = Bandi\u0107 i Sanader dogovorili izgradnju dvorane Arena Zagreb, Ingra i TriGr\u00e1nit dobili posao\n| date = 2007-04-24\n| accessdate = 2008-08-07\n| work = Vijesti.net\n| language = Croatian\n}}</ref><ref name=\"arena_\u0161pricer\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/34754/ |title=Bandi\u0107: \"Hladan sam k'o \u0161pricer\" |trans-title=Bandi\u0107: I'm as cool as can be |date=2007-05-25 |last=Zrinjski |first=Marijana |accessdate=2008-08-07 |journal=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |issue=602 |language=Croatian |archivedate=30 June 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68oiDfnqv?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/34754/bandic-hladan-sam-ko-spricer |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Honors==\nOn July 10, 2009, Bandi\u0107 was made an honorary citizen of [[Srebrenica]], Bosnia and Herzegovina.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bihvijesti.net/izvor108857_Povelja-opstine-Milan-Bandic-pocasni-gradjanin-Srebrenice.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110914132454/http://www.bihvijesti.net/izvor108857_Povelja-opstine-Milan-Bandic-pocasni-gradjanin-Srebrenice.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 September 2011 |title=Povelja op\u0161tine: Milan Bandi\u0107 po\u010dasni gra\u0111anin Srebrenice |author=A. B. |date=10 July 2009 |publisher=BiH Vijesti |accessdate=16 November 2011 |language=bs}}</ref>\n\nOn November 4, 2018, [[President of Russia|Russian President]] [[Vladimir Putin]] honored Bandi\u0107 with an [[Order of Friendship]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Putin odlikovao Milana Bandi\u0107a Ordenom prijateljstva |url=https://www.vecernji.hr/zagreb/putin-odlikovao-milana-bandica-ordenom-prijateljstva-1264868 |website=vecernji.hr |accessdate=29 November 2018|language=hr}}</ref>\n\n==Health problems==\n\nOn 3 July 2003 after a session of the Zagreb City Council Bandi\u0107 requested medical assistance, stating that he had begun to feel ill during the session. The media reported that he had suffered a minor [[stroke]]; the official explanation was that exhaustion and overwork had caused a [[blood vessel]] in his [[endocranium]] to [[spasm]]. He was hospitalized for a few weeks, then went to [[Krapinske Toplice]] to recover, and returned to his duties in September.<ref name=\"ostojic bandic\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.vecernji.hr/lokalni-izbori/bitka-za-zagreb-kako-je-ostojic-bandicu-spasio-zivot-491484\n| title = Bitka za Zagreb: Kako je Ostoji\u0107 Bandi\u0107u spasio \u017eivot\n| work = [[Ve\u010dernji list]]\n| date = 28 December 2012\n| language = Croatian\n| accessdate = 3 March 2015\n}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n{{Criticism section|date=October 2014}}\n\n==={{anchor|Land exchange case}}Land-exchange case===\n\nAs of October 2007 Bandi\u0107 was under investigation by the [[USKOK]] (Office for the Suppression of Corruption and Organized Crime) about several deals he made as mayor of Zagreb, including the July 2007 exchange of a lot at the intersection of Maksimirska Street and [[Gojko \u0160u\u0161ak Avenue|\u0160u\u0161ak Avenue]] for a lot in [[Sesvetski Kraljevec]]. A court-appointed expert allowed the exchange at a price of 1,300 kuna per square meter (\u20ac185) for the Sesvete lot (located in the suburbs, outside the [[Zagreb bypass]]) and 2,300 kuna (\u20ac321) for the Maksimirska lot (located in the [[Maksimir]] district, several hundred meters from downtown). New experts considered the lot on Maksimirska Street to be more valuable than the lot in Sesvetski Kraljevec. Thus, a USKOK source testified that Bandi\u0107 made a deal damaging to the city budget. The two companies with whom Bandi\u0107 dealt were headed by inexperienced students, furthering the appearance of impropriety.<ref name=bandic_index_uskok>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=86401\n |title       = Bandi\u0107 Under Investigation For Corruption\n |accessdate  = 2008-09-28\n |date        = 2007-10-03\n |work        = Javno.hr\n |url-status  = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071004041519/http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=86401\n |archivedate = 2007-10-04\n}}</ref><ref name=uskok>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak.aspx?id=360440\n| title = Bandi\u0107 o istrazi USKOK-a: Neka institucije rade svoj posao\n| accessdate = 2008-02-16\n| date = 2007-10-03\n| work = Vijesti.net\n| language = Croatian\n}}</ref>\n\n===''Cvjetni prolaz'' case===\nBandi\u0107 was involved in the ''Cvjetni prolaz'' case (a lengthy affair beginning in 2007), which centered on the controversial demolition and conversion of historical buildings in Petar Preradovi\u0107 Square into a [[shopping mall]] in Zagreb's [[Donji grad (Zagreb)|Lower Town]] area.<ref name=cg_intro_nac>{{cite web |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/30633/5/ |title=Preobra\u017eenska 6 i kino Zagreb nisu spomenici |accessdate=2008-05-16 |date=2007-01-15 |work=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |last=Cviti\u0107 |first=Plamenko |language=Croatian |trans-title=Preobra\u017eenska 6 and Cinema Zagreb are no monuments |archivedate=30 June 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68og8jEQ3?url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/30633/preobrazenska-6-i-kino-zagreb-nisu-spomenici |url-status=dead}}</ref> The project was headed by developer Tomislav Horvatin\u010di\u0107, who was alleged to have used illegal means in an attempt to [[evict]] the buildings' residents. These residents included a headquarters and church operated by the Zagreb-Ljubljana [[metropolitan bishop|metropolia]] of the [[Serbian Orthodox Church]] and the home of the late poet [[Vladimir Vidri\u0107]].<ref name=orthodox>{{cite web |url=http://www.mitropolija-zagrebacka.org/STR2LAT.htm \n |title=Eparhijski arhijerej |accessdate=2008-09-27 |work=Serbian orthodox church |language=Serbian |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080531230841/http://www.mitropolija-zagrebacka.org/STR2LAT.htm |archivedate=2008-05-31 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Bandi\u0107 is known to be a strong supporter of Horvatin\u010di\u0107,<ref name=cp_gi_popov>{{cite web |url = http://www.glasistre.hr/?5bb51035b592e5bf7ec3a43bb6bb7e44,TS,1885,,11666,15206,150393, | title = Ne vjeruj Bandi\u0107u ni kad te triput ljubi | accessdate = 2008-02-17 | date = 2007-01-13 | work = Glas Istre | last = Vesi\u0107 | first = Vanja |language = Croatian}}</ref> publicly criticizing opponents of the project.<ref name=cp_dnevnik_b_swearing>{{cite web | url = http://dnevnik.hr/vijesti/hrvatska/bandic-psovkama-protiv-protivnika-projekta.html | title = Bandi\u0107 psovkama protiv protivnika projekta | accessdate = 2008-05-15 | date = 2007-01-27 | work = Dnevnik.hr | language = Croatian}}</ref> In August 2008, Horvatin\u010di\u0107 obtained a license to demolish the old buildings. Residents of the surrounding buildings and [[environmentalists]] argued that the license was improperly issued, but the demolition is (as of 2011) still underway. However, Horvatin\u010di\u0107 is forbidden to demolish Vidri\u0107's home or build any part of the project until he obtains a building-location license, which requires him to prove he can build a walkway between Gunduli\u0107eva Street and Cvjetni Square.\n\n=== ''Golden Toilets'' case ===\nIn 2009. Croatian media revealed that Bandi\u0107 spent 1,55 million kuna (210 000 \u20ac) of city money to build two public toilets.<ref name=\"tportal.hr\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.tportal.hr/vijesti/clanak/bandicev-kum-izgradio-najskuplji-wc-u-hrvatskoj-20090318|title=Bandi\u0107ev kum izgradio najskuplji WC u Hrvatskoj|work=tportal.hr|access-date=2017-05-12}}</ref> The media mockingly called these \"The Golden Toilets\".<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.tportal.hr/vijesti/clanak/i-bandicevi-zlatni-wc-i-dosli-na-tapetu-uskoka-20131230|title=I Bandi\u0107evi zlatni WC-i do\u0161li na tapetu Uskoka|work=tportal.hr|access-date=2017-05-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vecernji.hr/zagreb/davor-jelavic-pod-istragom-zbog-bandicevih-zlatnih-wc-a-912533|title=Davor Jelavi\u0107 pod istragom zbog Bandi\u0107evih 'zlatnih' WC-a|access-date=2017-05-12|language=hr}}</ref> The media wrote that the job was given to the company [[T\u017dV Gredelj]], specialized for construction of railway veichles without any tender. Gredelj then hired another company owned by Bandi\u0107's godfather to do the actual construction.<ref name=\"tportal.hr\"/> In 2013. [[USKOK|Croatian State Prosecutor's Office for the Suppression of Organized Crime and Corruption]] announced that they are investigating the case.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n===2014 arrest===\nBandi\u0107 was arrested on 19 October 2014 on charges of corruption, bribery and organized crime, along with two other key members of the Zagreb city council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak/uhicen-milan-bandic/778492.aspx |title=Uhi\u0107en Milan Bandi\u0107 |accessdate=19 October 2014 |language=Croatian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://ca.reuters.com/article/topNews/idCAKCN0I80Q420141019|title=Croatian police arrest Zagreb mayor on corruption charges|date=19 October 2014|agency=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Alleged use of cocaine===\nAccording to some Croatian media, Bandi\u0107 is long time cocaine addict.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dnevno.hr/vijesti/hrvatska/nas-je-gradonacelnik-zesci-ovisnik-o-kokainu-918248/ |title=Na\u0161 je gradona\u010delnik \u017ee\u0161\u0107i ovisnik o kokainu! |accessdate=7 April 2020 |language=Croatian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://100posto.jutarnji.hr/news/cak-se-ni-i-hdz-ovci-vise-se-skrivaju-s-travom-a-europarlamentarka-tvrdi-da-nam-je-sabor-pun-kokaina-bacilo-me-na-paranoju-u-strah-i-bilo-je-to-prvi-i-zadnji-put-da-sam/ |title=Kad se zabijeli Markov trg! |accessdate=7 April 2020 |language=Croatian}}</ref>\n\n===Minor controversies===\nA controversy arose on 31 July 2005, when Bandi\u0107 was on a bus with 30 other people and saw workers waving on the street. He then allegedly cited the [[Arbeit macht frei|Auschwitz motto]]: \"Work liberates, the Nazis weren't totally dumb.\" Hrvoje Kre\u0161i\u0107, a ''[[Novi list]]'' journalist, allegedly heard Bandi\u0107 and published his statement. The following day Bandi\u0107 threatened to sue Kre\u0161i\u0107 and ''Novi list''; he claimed he said \"Marxists,\" not \"Nazis\". Bandi\u0107's statement was corroborated by several of his nearby colleagues; other journalists at the rear of the bus did not hear anything said by Bandi\u0107, due to noise inside the vehicle. Bandi\u0107 said that if awarded [[damages]], he would donate the money to the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]]. The director of the center, [[Efraim Zuroff]], refused.<ref name=zuroff_auschwitz>{{cite web | url = http://www.index.hr/vijesti/clanak.aspx?id=277097 | title = Zuroff: Neka Bandi\u0107 sebi i suradnicima plati put u Auschwitz | date = 2005-08-02 | accessdate = 2008-09-28 | work = Vijesti.net | language = Croatian}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2006, Bandi\u0107 publicly threatened a journalist working for ''[[Ve\u010dernji list]]''. The journalist asked Bandi\u0107 about an offer from a [[Czech Republic|Czech]] company; Bandi\u0107 replied aggressively, cursing and threatening the journalist. Afterwards, he claimed he had simply spoken to the journalist in a loud voice.<ref name=threatened_journalist>{{cite web |url = http://www.bolji-zivot.hr/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=113&Itemid=96 |title= Bandi\u0107 javno prijetio novinaru |accessdate= 2007-09-11 |date= 2006-01-17 |work= Bolji \u017eivot |language= Croatian |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070928020755/http://www.bolji-zivot.hr/index.php option=com_content&task=view&id=113&Itemid=96 |archivedate = 2007-09-28}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 May 2007 Bandi\u0107 fell asleep shortly before noon during a session of the Zagreb City Assembly; TV cameras captured the moment.<ref name=city_assembly_sleep>{{cite web | url = http://dnevnik.hr/vijesti/hrvatska/bandic-zaspao-na-sjednici-skupstine.html | title = Bandi\u0107 zaspao na sjednici Skup\u0161tine | accessdate = 2008-06-15 | date = 2007-06-01 | work = [[Dnevnik Nove TV]] | language = Croatian}}</ref> This was apparently not the first time he suffered from sleep problems; he fell asleep on 16 June 2006 at the [[Croatian National Theatre in Zagreb|Croatian National Theater]], where he presented an award to Marija Musta\u0107, secretary of the [[Croatian Association of the Blind]].\n\nIn May 2008 Bandi\u0107 left his car illegally parked at the center of [[\u0160ubi\u0107eva Street]], creating a road hazard and causing traffic problems; he held a public presentation of a camera system designed to issue [[traffic ticket|tickets]] to red-light runners, improperly-parked cars and the like. He then shopped in the [[Dolac Market|Dolac]] open-air market while his driver waited in the car, obstructing traffic. When questioned about this incident, Bandi\u0107 blamed it on his driver.<ref name=subiceva_road_obstruction>{{cite web |url=http://www.vecernji.hr/newsroom/regions/zagreb/3082790/index.do |title=Bandi\u0107 najavio prometno redarstvo koje bi, kad bi ga bilo, ju\u010der najprije ulovilo njega |accessdate=2008-05-16 |date=2008-05-16 |work=[[Ve\u010dernji list]] |last=\u0160poljar |first=Marko |author2=Li\u0161anin, Mi\u0161o |language=Croatian |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517135056/http://www.vecernji.hr/newsroom/regions/zagreb/3082790/index.do |archivedate=2008-05-17 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]]\n* [[List of mayors of Zagreb]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|\n title=[[List of mayors of Zagreb|Mayor of Zagreb]]|\n before=[[Josip Kregar]]\n(governor appointed by Croatian government)|\n years=2000\u20132002|\n after=[[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]]\n}}\n{{succession box|\n title=[[List of mayors of Zagreb|Mayor of Zagreb]]|\n before=[[Vlasta Pavi\u0107]]|\n years=2005\u2013present |\n after=Incumbent\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bandic, Milan}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Zagreb]]\n[[Category:Faculty of Political Sciences, University of Zagreb alumni]]\n[[Category:Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic Party of Croatia politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Grude]]\n[[Category:League of Communists of Croatia politicians]]\n[[Category:Candidates for President of Croatia]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Friendship]]\n", "name_user": "Quebec99", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix duplicate ref names \u2013You can help!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Milan_Bandi%C4%87"}
{"title_page": "Boris Berezovsky (pianist)", "text_new": "{{for|businessman|Boris Berezovsky (businessman)}}\n{{BLP sources|date=June 2009}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n\n| native_name      =  \u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0301\u0441 \u0412\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0301\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0411\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0437\u043e\u0301\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439\n| native_name_lang = rus\n| image               = BorisBerezovsky.jpg\n| alt                   = a man in a black suit stands on stage\n| caption            = Boris Berezovsky during his concert in Tbilisi, Georgia, March 5, 2010\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = Boris Vadimovich Berezovsky \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1969|1|4}}\n| birth_place       = [[Moscow]]\n| genre               = [[Classical music]]\n| occupation        = Musician\n| instrument        = Piano\n| years_active     = 1988\u2013present\n| label                 = [[Teldec]], Apex, [[Erato Records|Erato]], [[Simax]], Koch, [[Warner Classics]], [[Mirare]]\n}}\n\n'''Boris Vadimovich Berezovsky''' ({{lang-ru|\u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0301\u0441 \u0412\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0301\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0411\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0437\u043e\u0301\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439}}) is a Russian pianist.\n\n== Biography ==\nBerezovsky studied at the [[Moscow Conservatory]] with [[Eliso Virsaladze]] and privately with [[Alexander Satz]]. Following his [[London]] d\u00e9but at the [[Wigmore Hall]] in 1988, ''[[The Times]]'' described him as \"an artist of exceptional promise, a player of dazzling virtuosity and formidable power.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.warnerclassics.com/artist,BorisBerezovsky_5.htm |title=Boris Berezovsky: Biography |publisher=Warner Classics |accessdate=9 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315000038/http://www.warnerclassics.com/artist%2CBorisBerezovsky_5.htm |archivedate=15 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2005 he had his first solo recital<ref>[[Jean-Pierre Thiollet]], ''88 notes pour piano solo'', \"Solo nec plus ultra\", Neva Editions, 2015, p.51. {{ISBN|978 2 3505 5192 0}}.</ref> in [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre des Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es]] in [[Paris]] and played in the same venue in January 2006 with the [[Orchestre National de France]]. In January 2007 he played seven recitals \"Carte Blanche\" in the [[Louvre]].\nIn May 2009, he premiered [[Karol Beffa]]'s \"Piano concerto\" in Toulouse, with [[Orchestre national du Capitole de Toulouse|Orchestre National du Capitole de Toulouse]] and [[Tugan Sokhiev]] as conductor.\n\n== Career ==\n\nHe has initiated and organized the ''International [[Medtner]] Festival'' that took place 2006 and 2007 in [[Moscow]], [[Yekaterinburg]] and [[Vladimir, Russia|Vladimir]], as he has championed the composer since the early 1990s and has been one of the foremost recent interpreters of Medtner's music.\n\n==Recordings==\n[[File:Gia Kancheli & Boris Berezovski.jpg|thumb|left|300px|Georgian composer [[Giya Kancheli]] and Boris Berezovsky in Tbilisi, after a concert at the [[Tbilisi State Conservatory]]]]\nBerezovsky's recordings of the complete [[Ludwig van Beethoven|Beethoven]] Piano concertos with the [[Swedish Chamber Orchestra]] with [[Thomas Dausgaard]] have been greeted with high critical acclaim.{{Citation needed|date=January 2011}}  He has made a considerable number of records for [[Teldec]], including solo discs of works by [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Chopin|Chopin]], [[Robert Schumann|Schumann]], [[Sergei Rachmaninoff|Rachmaninoff]], [[Modest Mussorgsky|Mussorgsky]], [[Mily Balakirev|Balakirev]], [[Nikolai Medtner|Medtner]], [[Maurice Ravel|Ravel]] and the complete [[Franz Liszt|Liszt]] ''[[Transcendental Etudes]]''.\n\nWith the [[Mirare]] Label, he has recorded the Rachmaninoff ''Pr\u00e9ludes'' (May 2005) as well as that composer's complete ''Piano Concertos'' with the [[Ural Philharmonic Orchestra]] conducted by [[Dmitry Liss|Dmitri Liss]] (August 2005). His album Tchaikovsky ''Piano Concerto No. 1'' and [[Aram Khachaturian|Khachaturian]] ''Piano \u0421oncerto'' ([[Ural Philharmonic Orchestra]]/[[Dmitry Liss]]) was released on April 2006 in the [[UK]].\n\nThe most recent recordings are Medtner ''Tales & Poems'' with Yana Ivanilova (soprano), Vassily Savenko (baritone) (Mirare 2008), Medtner ''Two pieces for two pianos'', Op. 58, with [[Hamish Milne]] (piano) in: Medtner ''Complete Piano Sonatas; Piano Works \u2014 Vol. 7'' (Brilliant Classics 2008), Rachmaninoff ''Suite No. 1 for two pianos'', Op. 5 & ''Suite No. 2 for two pianos'', Op. 17, with [[Brigitte Engerer]] (piano) (Mirare 2008). In 2010 Berezovsky released a record of his Liszt recital (Mirare 2008). His recording of selected works by [[Johannes Brahms|Brahms]] ([[Piano Concerto No. 2 (Brahms)|Piano Concerto No. 2]], [[Variations on a Theme of Paganini (Brahms)|Variations on a Theme of Paganini]], and [[Hungarian Dances (Brahms)|Hungarian Dances]] Nos. 1, 2 & 4) was released in January  2011 (Mirare). More recently, Berezovsky released a recording of the Piano Concerto no. 2 by Tchaikovsky and other selected works (also with Mirare).\n\n==CDs==\n* A trio consisting of Boris Berezovsky, Dmitri Makhtin, Alexander Kniazev recorded a [[DVD]] of [[Tchaikovsky]] ''pieces for'' ''[[piano]]'', ''[[violin]]'' ''and'' ''[[cello]]'' and [[Sergei Rachmaninoff|Rachmaninoff's]] ''Trio \u00e9l\u00e9giaque'' \u201c''A la m\u00e9moire d\u2019un grand artiste''\u201d presented on [[Arte TV|ARTE TV]] Channel and NHK in [[Japan]]. They received for this DVD the 4 stars [[Diapason d'Or]].\n* For Warner Classics International Boris Berezovsky recorded with the same trio the [[Shostakovitch]] [[Piano Trio No. 2 (Shostakovich)|''Trio No. 2'']] and [[Rachmaninoff]] [[Trio \u00e9l\u00e9giaque No. 2 (Rachmaninoff)|''Trio \u00e9l\u00e9giaque No. 2'']] which were awarded Choc de la Musique in France, [[Gramophone Company|Gramophone]] in England, [[Echo Klassik|ECHO Klassik]]<ref name=\"ECHO\">[http://www.echoklassik.de/kategorie/kat918.htm ECHO Klassik]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, 2005.</ref> and Deutsche Schallplattenkritik<ref name=\"DS\">[http://www.schallplattenkritik.de/li/2005-2.html Preis der Deutschen Schallplattenkritik] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081008105336/http://www.schallplattenkritik.de/li/2005-2.html |date=October 8, 2008 }}, 2005.</ref> in Germany.\n* His solo live recording [[Chopin]]/[[Leopold Godowsky|Godowsky]] ''Etudes'' was released in January 2006 and got several awards such as the [[Diapason d'Or]], RTL d'Or and [[BBC Music Magazine]].<ref name=\"BBC\">[http://www.bbcmusicmagazine.com/instrumentalwinner.asp BBC Music Magazine Awards] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304224119/http://www.bbcmusicmagazine.com/instrumentalwinner.asp |date=March 4, 2009 }}, 2006.</ref>\n* His album of [[Paul Hindemith]] ''Ludus Tonalis'' and ''Suite 1922'' (Warner Classics) was awarded ECHO Klassik<ref name=\"ECHO-2007\">[http://www.echoklassik.de/kategorie/kat1019.htm ECHO Klassik] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080325230459/http://www.echoklassik.de/kategorie/kat1019.htm |date=March 25, 2008 }}, 2007.</ref> as the best solo recording of \"Music of the 20th \u2014 21st Century\".\n\n==DVDs==\n* Boris Berezovsky \u2014 \"Les Pianos de la Nuit\". Liszt ''[[Transcendental Etudes]]'', S. 139. Director: Andy Sommer. Filming: 4 August 2002 (Na\u00efve 2003)\n* Boris Berezovsky / Dmitri Makhtin / Alexander Kniazev \u2014 \"Les Pianos De La Nuit\". Tschaikovsky ''Seasons'' (No. 6); ''Nocturne'' in D minor, Op. 19, No. 4; ''Trio'' in A minor \"''A la m\u00e9moire d\u2019un grand artiste''\", Op. 50; ''Serenade melancholique''. Director: Andy Sommer. Filming: 10 August 2004 (Na\u00efve 2006)\n* Boris Berezovsky \u2014 \"Change of Plans\": Interview & Performance. Beethoven ''33 Variationen'' C-Dur ''on Theme Antonio Diabelli'', Op. 120; Medtner ''Tales'', Op. 14, 20, 26, 34, 35, 48, 51; [[Dafydd Llywelyn|Llywelyn]] ''Improvisation on \"Change of Plans\"''; Godovsky ''Altes Wien''; Lyadov ''Preludes'' d-moll, Op. 40, No. 3 and G-Dur, Op. 46, No. 3, Bagatel As-Dur, Op. 53, No. 3. In: \"Legato \u2014 The World Of Piano\", Vol. 1. Director: Jan Schmidt-Garre. Filming: 14 July 2006 (Naxos 2007)\n\n==Awards==\nBerezovsky won the Gold Medal at the 1990 [[Tchaikovsky Competition|International Tchaikovsky Competition]] in Moscow.\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071217051947/http://www.warnerclassicsandjazz.com/artistbiography.php?artist=5 Biography from Warner Classics]\n* [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/soft-pedaller-1248873.html Michael Church about Boris Berezovsky for ''The Independent'' (1997)]\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/classicalmusic/3651696/Playing-for-the-highest-stakes.html Peter Culshaw about Boris Berezovsky for ''Telegraph'' (2006)]\n* [http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/fm20070615a1.html Mariko Kato about Boris Berezovsky for ''The Japan Times'' (2007)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120217022716/http://www.productions-sarfati.com/pages/biographies.php?niveau=0&cat=11&lang=2&page=45 Productions Internationales Albert Sarfati: Boris Berezovsky]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berezovsky, Boris}}\n[[Category:Russian classical pianists]]\n[[Category:Russian expatriates in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Russian expatriates in Belgium]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Moscow]]\n[[Category:Moscow Conservatory alumni]]\n[[Category:Prize-winners of the Leeds International Pianoforte Competition]]\n[[Category:Prize-winners of the International Tchaikovsky Competition]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|businessman|Boris Berezovsky (businessman)}}\n{{BLP sources|date=June 2009}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n\n| native_name      =  \u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0301\u0441 \u0412\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0301\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0411\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0437\u043e\u0301\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439\n| native_name_lang = rus\n| image               = BorisBerezovsky.jpg\n| alt                   = a man in a black suit stands on stage\n| caption            = Boris Berezovsky during his concert in Tbilisi, Georgia, March 5, 2010\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = Boris Vadimovich Berezovsky \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1969|1|4}}\n| birth_place       = [[Moscow]]\n| genre               = [[Classical music]]\n| occupation        = Musician\n| instrument        = Piano\n| years_active     = 1988\u2013present\n| label                 = [[Teldec]], Apex, [[Erato Records|Erato]], [[Simax]], Koch, [[Warner Classics]], [[Mirare]]\n}}\n\n'''Boris Vadimovich Berezovsky''' ({{lang-ru|\u0411\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0301\u0441 \u0412\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0301\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0411\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0437\u043e\u0301\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439}}) is a Russian pianist.\n\n== Biography ==\nBerezovsky studied at the [[Moscow Conservatory]] with [[Eliso Virsaladze]] and privately with [[Alexander Satz]]. Following his [[London]] d\u00e9but at the [[Wigmore Hall]] in 1988, ''[[The Times]]'' described him as \"an artist of exceptional promise, a player of dazzling virtuosity and formidable power.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.warnerclassics.com/artist,BorisBerezovsky_5.htm |title=Boris Berezovsky: Biography |publisher=Warner Classics |accessdate=9 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315000038/http://www.warnerclassics.com/artist%2CBorisBerezovsky_5.htm |archivedate=15 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2005 he had his first solo recital<ref>[[Jean-Pierre Thiollet]], ''88 notes pour piano solo'', \"Solo nec plus ultra\", Neva Editions, 2015, p.51. {{ISBN|978 2 3505 5192 0}}.</ref> in [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre des Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es]] in [[Paris]] and played in the same venue in January 2006 with the [[Orchestre National de France]]. In January 2007 he played seven recitals \"Carte Blanche\" in the [[Louvre]].\nIn May 2009, he premiered [[Karol Beffa]]'s \"Piano concerto\" in Toulouse, with [[Orchestre national du Capitole de Toulouse|Orchestre National du Capitole de Toulouse]] and [[Tugan Sokhiev]] as conductor.\n\n== Career ==\n\nHe has initiated and organized the ''International [[Medtner]] Festival'' that took place 2006 and 2007 in [[Moscow]], [[Yekaterinburg]] and [[Vladimir, Russia|Vladimir]], as he has championed the composer since the early 1990s and has been one of the foremost recent interpreters of Medtner's music.\n\n==Recordings==\n[[File:Gia Kancheli & Boris Berezovski.jpg|thumb|left|300px|Georgian composer [[Giya Kancheli]] and Boris Berezovsky in Tbilisi, after a concert at the [[Tbilisi State Conservatory]]]]\nBerezovsky's recordings of the complete [[Ludwig van Beethoven|Beethoven]] Piano concertos with the [[Swedish Chamber Orchestra]] with [[Thomas Dausgaard]] have been greeted with high critical acclaim.{{Citation needed|date=January 2011}}  He has made a considerable number of records for [[Teldec]], including solo discs of works by [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Chopin|Chopin]], [[Robert Schumann|Schumann]], [[Sergei Rachmaninoff|Rachmaninoff]], [[Modest Mussorgsky|Mussorgsky]], [[Mily Balakirev|Balakirev]], [[Nikolai Medtner|Medtner]], [[Maurice Ravel|Ravel]] and the complete [[Franz Liszt|Liszt]] ''[[Transcendental Etudes]]''.\n\nWith the [[Mirare]] Label, he has recorded the Rachmaninoff ''Pr\u00e9ludes'' (May 2005) as well as that composer's complete ''Piano Concertos'' with the [[Ural Philharmonic Orchestra]] conducted by [[Dmitry Liss|Dmitri Liss]] (August 2005). His album Tchaikovsky ''Piano Concerto No. 1'' and [[Aram Khachaturian|Khachaturian]] ''Piano \u0421oncerto'' ([[Ural Philharmonic Orchestra]]/[[Dmitry Liss]]) was released on April 2006 in the [[UK]].\n\nThe most recent recordings are Medtner ''Tales & Poems'' with Yana Ivanilova (soprano), Vassily Savenko (baritone) (Mirare 2008), Medtner ''Two pieces for two pianos'', Op. 58, with [[Hamish Milne]] (piano) in: Medtner ''Complete Piano Sonatas; Piano Works \u2014 Vol. 7'' (Brilliant Classics 2008), Rachmaninoff ''Suite No. 1 for two pianos'', Op. 5 & ''Suite No. 2 for two pianos'', Op. 17, with [[Brigitte Engerer]] (piano) (Mirare 2008). In 2010 Berezovsky released a record of his Liszt recital (Mirare 2008). His recording of selected works by [[Johannes Brahms|Brahms]] ([[Piano Concerto No. 2 (Brahms)|Piano Concerto No. 2]], [[Variations on a Theme of Paganini (Brahms)|Variations on a Theme of Paganini]], and [[Hungarian Dances (Brahms)|Hungarian Dances]] Nos. 1, 2 & 4) was released in January  2011 (Mirare). More recently, Berezovsky released a recording of the Piano Concerto no. 2 by Tchaikovsky and other selected works (also with Mirare).\n\n==CDs==\n* A trio consisting of Boris Berezovsky, Dmitri Makhtin, Alexander Kniazev recorded a [[DVD]] of [[Tchaikovsky]] ''pieces for'' ''[[piano]]'', ''[[violin]]'' ''and'' ''[[cello]]'' and [[Sergei Rachmaninoff|Rachmaninoff's]] ''Trio \u00e9l\u00e9giaque'' \u201c''A la m\u00e9moire d\u2019un grand artiste''\u201d presented on [[Arte TV|ARTE TV]] Channel and NHK in [[Japan]]. They received for this DVD the 4 stars [[Diapason d'Or]].\n* For Warner Classics International Boris Berezovsky recorded with the same trio the [[Shostakovitch]] [[Piano Trio No. 2 (Shostakovich)|''Trio No. 2'']] and [[Rachmaninoff]] [[Trio \u00e9l\u00e9giaque No. 2 (Rachmaninoff)|''Trio \u00e9l\u00e9giaque No. 2'']] which were awarded Choc de la Musique in France, [[Gramophone Company|Gramophone]] in England, [[Echo Klassik|ECHO Klassik]]<ref name=\"ECHO\">[http://www.echoklassik.de/kategorie/kat918.htm ECHO Klassik]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, 2005.</ref> and Deutsche Schallplattenkritik<ref name=\"DS\">[http://www.schallplattenkritik.de/li/2005-2.html Preis der Deutschen Schallplattenkritik] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081008105336/http://www.schallplattenkritik.de/li/2005-2.html |date=October 8, 2008 }}, 2005.</ref> in Germany.\n* His solo live recording [[Chopin]]/[[Leopold Godowsky|Godowsky]] ''Etudes'' was released in January 2006 and got several awards such as the [[Diapason d'Or]], RTL d'Or and [[BBC Music Magazine]].<ref name=\"BBC\">[http://www.bbcmusicmagazine.com/instrumentalwinner.asp BBC Music Magazine Awards] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304224119/http://www.bbcmusicmagazine.com/instrumentalwinner.asp |date=March 4, 2009 }}, 2006.</ref>\n* His album of [[Paul Hindemith]] ''Ludus Tonalis'' and ''Suite 1922'' (Warner Classics) was awarded ECHO Klassik<ref name=\"ECHO-2007\">[http://www.echoklassik.de/kategorie/kat1019.htm ECHO Klassik] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080325230459/http://www.echoklassik.de/kategorie/kat1019.htm |date=March 25, 2008 }}, 2007.</ref> as the best solo recording of \"Music of the 20th \u2014 21st Century\".\n\n==DVDs==\n* Boris Berezovsky \u2014 \"Les Pianos de la Nuit\". Liszt ''[[Transcendental Etudes]]'', S. 139. Director: Andy Sommer. Filming: 4 August 2002 (Na\u00efve 2003)\n* Boris Berezovsky / Dmitri Makhtin / Alexander Kniazev \u2014 \"Les Pianos De La Nuit\". Tschaikovsky ''Seasons'' (No. 6); ''Nocturne'' in D minor, Op. 19, \u2116 4; ''Trio'' in A minor \"''A la m\u00e9moire d\u2019un grand artiste''\", Op. 50; ''Serenade melancholique''. Director: Andy Sommer. Filming: 10 August 2004 (Na\u00efve 2006)\n* Boris Berezovsky \u2014 \"Change of Plans\": Interview & Performance. Beethoven ''33 Variationen'' C-Dur ''on Theme Antonio Diabelli'', Op. 120; Medtner ''Tales'', Op. 14, 20, 26, 34, 35, 48, 51; [[Dafydd Llywelyn|Llywelyn]] ''Improvisation on \"Change of Plans\"''; Godovsky ''Altes Wien''; Lyadov ''Preludes'' d-moll, Op. 40, No. 3 and G-Dur, Op. 46, No. 3, Bagatel As-Dur, Op. 53, No. 3. In: \"Legato \u2014 The World Of Piano\", Vol. 1. Director: Jan Schmidt-Garre. Filming: 14 July 2006 (Naxos 2007)\n\n==Awards==\nBerezovsky won the Gold Medal at the 1990 [[Tchaikovsky Competition|International Tchaikovsky Competition]] in Moscow.\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071217051947/http://www.warnerclassicsandjazz.com/artistbiography.php?artist=5 Biography from Warner Classics]\n* [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/soft-pedaller-1248873.html Michael Church about Boris Berezovsky for ''The Independent'' (1997)]\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/classicalmusic/3651696/Playing-for-the-highest-stakes.html Peter Culshaw about Boris Berezovsky for ''Telegraph'' (2006)]\n* [http://search.japantimes.co.jp/cgi-bin/fm20070615a1.html Mariko Kato about Boris Berezovsky for ''The Japan Times'' (2007)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120217022716/http://www.productions-sarfati.com/pages/biographies.php?niveau=0&cat=11&lang=2&page=45 Productions Internationales Albert Sarfati: Boris Berezovsky]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berezovsky, Boris}}\n[[Category:Russian classical pianists]]\n[[Category:Russian expatriates in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Russian expatriates in Belgium]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Moscow]]\n[[Category:Moscow Conservatory alumni]]\n[[Category:Prize-winners of the Leeds International Pianoforte Competition]]\n[[Category:Prize-winners of the International Tchaikovsky Competition]]\n", "name_user": "Amkgp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDVDs:clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2116 \u2192 No.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boris_Berezovsky_(pianist)"}
{"title_page": "La Macorina", "text_new": "{{short description|Cuban high-class prostitute}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = \n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Mar\u00eda Constancia Caraza Vald\u00e9s\n| birth_date    = {{Birth year|1892}}\n| birth_place   = [[Guanajay]], Cuba\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1977|06|15|1892||}} \n| death_place   = [[Havana]], Cuba\n| nationality   = [[Cubans|Cuban]]\n| other_names   = Mar\u00eda Calvo Nodarse\n| occupation    = [[Prostitute]]\n| years_active  = 1917-1934\n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Mar\u00eda Calvo Nodarse''' ([[Guanajay]], 1892 - [[Havana]], 15 June 1977), better known as '''La Macorina''', was a [[Cubans|Cuban]] high-class [[prostitute]] who was a friend of ex-president [[Jos\u00e9 Miguel G\u00f3mez]], who she supported during the [[History of Cuba#Cuba in the early 20th century|Chambelona War]]. She was the first female to a hold a [[driving license]] in the [[Americas]].\n\n==Biography==\nLa Macorina was born ''Mar\u00eda Constancia Caraza Vald\u00e9s''{{sfn|Alfonso|2016}} in 1892{{sfn|del Castillo Pichardo|2017}} in Guanajay, Cuba, then in [[Pinar del R\u00edo Province]]. She was reputed to be of [[Afro-Asians|Afro-Chinese]] heritage, but her driving license appears to show a white woman.{{sfn|Alfonso|2016}} Little is known of her childhood, but at 15 she left home and moved to Havana with her boyfriend. Although her parents tried to get her to return she stayed in Havana. The couple were faced economic hardship until a woman told her how they could live luxuriously and La Macorina turned to [[prostitution]].{{sfn|Alfonso|2016}} She assumed the name ''Mar\u00eda Calvo Nodarse'' and moved to Galiano Street, near the [[Malec\u00f3n, Havana|Malec\u00f3n]],{{sfn|Ortega|2008}} a popular location in Havana at the time, including for prostitution.{{sfn|Cooke|2014}}\n\nPersonality and beauty helped La Macorina become one of the most elegant and famous prostitutes, entering the most select circles of Cuban society at the time. She was selective of her [[Client (prostitution)|clients]] and in an interview by Guillermo Villarronda<ref>{{cite web |title=Macorina |url=http://www.enricophil.it/tales/Central_America/Scripts/macorina.htm |website=www.enricophil.it |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> for Bohemia magazine in 1958, she said \"more than a dozen men were at my feet, full of money, and begging for love.\u201d{{sfn|Alfonso|2016}} She wore her hair short in the Garz\u00f3n style, which was considered scandalous at the time, and smoked cigars.<ref name=\"Hello Foros\">{{cite web |title=Personajes Celebres La Macorina |url=https://www.helloforos.com/t/personajes-celebres-la-macorina/271057 |website=Hello Foros - La Comunidad en Espa\u00f1ol m\u00e1s Popular de los Latinos |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=es |date=3 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nBy the time she retired in 1934 she had amassed a fortune. She owned mansions in Havana, Calzada, Linea and San Miguel,<ref name=\"Hello Foros\" /> race horses, expensive furs, a large collection of valuable jewellery and 9 cars.{{sfn|Alfonso|2016}}\n\n===Chambelona War===\nGeneral, later president, Jos\u00e9 Miguel G\u00f3mez was one of her protectors. La Macorina supported him during the Chambelona War. When G\u00f3mez was imprisoned in the [[Castillo del Pr\u00edncipe (Havana)|Castillo del Pr\u00edncipe]], La Macorina retained her loyalty.{{sfn|Ross|2017}} She  visited him and campaigned for his release and ferried his supporters around in her cars. La Macorina herself was imprisoned for 25 days in Havana prison during the period for her opposition to President [[Mario Garc\u00eda Menocal]]. Although Menocal had ordered her to be treated harshly in prison, warden Andr\u00e9s Hern\u00e1ndez arranged for her to have separate quarters and, in her words, \"treated me like a queen\".<ref name=\"TodoCuba\" />\n\n===Decline and death===\nLa Macorina retired in 1934 when the country's economics took a downturn and, at 42, her looks had started to fade. Although she had amassed a fortune, she was reputed to be spending two thousand pesos a month and soon had to start selling her assets. Her previous friends distanced themselves from her and she eventually ended up living in poverty in a rented room in Havana. La Macorina died in Havana on 15 June 1977.{{sfn|Alfonso|2016}}{{sfn|Iglesias|2008}}\n\n==In popular culture==\n{{Quote box |width=300px |align=right |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 | salign=right\n|title = Macorina\n |quote  =<poem>\nPut your hand here, Macorina,\nput your hand here.\nYour feet left the mat\nand your saya ran away\nlooking for the guard\nthat when your size was so fine,\nthe sugarcanes\nwere thrown down the road\nso that you could grind them\nas if you were a mill.\nYour breasts, flesh of anon,\nyour mouth a blessing\nof ripe soursop,\nand your thin waist was\nthe same as that\nhot danzon of that danzon.\nThen the dawn\nthat carries you from my arms,\nand I without knowing what to do\nwith that smell of woman,\nmango and new cane\nwith which you filled me to the\nwarm sound of that danz\u00f3n.<ref name=\"www.futurodecuba.org\">{{cite web |title=La Macorina\u00a0\u00a0 Maria Calvo Nodarse |url=http://www.futurodecuba.org/la_macorina___maria_calvo_nodars.htm |website=www.futurodecuba.org |accessdate=15 April 2020 |language=es}}</ref>{{sfn|del Castillo Pichardo|2017}}\n</poem>\n|source =\u2014Poem by [[Alfonso Cam\u00edn]]<br>-Recorded as a song by [[Chavela Vargas]]}}\nThe [[Asturias|Asturian]] [[Alfonso Cam\u00edn]] wrote a poem about her, \"''Macorina''\",  which was later recorded as a song by [[Chavela Vargas]],{{sfn|Ramos-Kittrell|2019|p=50}}  one of the best-known songs of her career. The chorus is a suggestive \"''Put Your Hand Here Macorina ..''\". Vargas met La Macorina in Havana \"getting out of a white car\" and was struck by her \"her slanted eyes and fierce hair.\" She later said of La Macorina \u201cShe was a beautiful woman. Black mixed from China. I saw her and I was speechless.\u201d{{sfn|Bono|2013}} The song became the \"lesbian hymn\"{{sfn|Ramos-Kittrell|2019|p=50}} and was banned in Spain during [[Francoist Spain|Francoism]].<ref name=\"Hello Foros\" />\n\nLa Macorina frequently drove around Havana in a red convertible Hispano-Suiza.{{sfn|del Castillo Pichardo|2017}} Artist [[Cundo Berm\u00fadez]] portrayed her in that setting in a painting from memory{{sfn|Alfonso|2016}} in 1978, the year after her death.<ref name=\"www.futurodecuba.org\" /> The red car also featured in the modified lyrics of the 1950s recording of \"''Macorina''\" by [[Abelardo Barroso]].{{sfn|del Castillo Pichardo|2017}}<ref name=\"www.futurodecuba.org\" />\n\nPoet [[Otilio Vigil D\u00edaz|Vigil D\u00edaz]] wrote enthusiastically about La Macorina in his \"Fatamorgana\" column for the Dominican newspaper [[List\u00edn Diario]].{{sfn|del Castillo Pichardo|2017}}\n\nIn his novel ''Las Impuras'', Miguel de Carrion based the main character ''La Aviadora'' on La Macorina.<ref name=\"Hello Foros\" />\n\nIn the brass bands parade during the [[Bejucal|Charangas de Bejucal]] annual festival, La Macorina was honoured as one of the parade's characters by a doll with a mask of her face.<ref name=\"www.futurodecuba.org\" /> The doll has been preserved.{{sfn|Ortega|2008}} La Macorina is still one of the characters of the Charangas, usually being present on the floats of \"''La Espina de Oro''\" and the \"''La Ceiba de Plata''\".<ref name=\"www.angerona.cult.cu\">{{cite web |title=La Habana, Cuba...La Macorina: Personaje de Bejucal |url=http://www.angerona.cult.cu/bejucal/lamacorina.htm |website=www.angerona.cult.cu |accessdate=16 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070807185621/http://www.angerona.cult.cu/bejucal/lamacorina.htm |archivedate=7 August 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Origin of \"La Macorina\"==\nThe nickname La Macorina is reputed to have come from a drunken young man. Whilst walking past the Acera del Louvre{{sfn|Nodal|2019}} (the terrace of the Louvre cafe where Cuba's literati and baseball players met),{{sfn|Echevarria|2001|p=85}} the young man on seeing her beauty said \"there goes La Macorina!\". He had meant to say \"La Fornarina\", mistaking her for the famous Spanish cupletista, ''Consuelo Bello'', who was commonly called La Fornarina after the famous painting of the [[La Fornarina|same name]] by Italian master [[Raphael]] of his lover [[Margarita Luti]].{{sfn|Nodal|2019}}\n\n==Cars and driving==\nLa Macorina's first car, a [[Ford]],<ref>{{cite web |title=La Macorina - Curiosidades |url=http://www.tvavila.icrt.cu/noticia.php?id=631&clas=Curiosidades |website=www.tvavila.icrt.cu |accessdate=16 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081230021402/http://www.tvavila.icrt.cu/noticia.php?id=631&clas=Curiosidades |archivedate=30 December 2008 |language=es |date=23 September 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> was presented to her as compensation by an an influential politician who had run her over in his car.<ref name=\"TodoCuba\">{{cite web |title=Conoce la historia de la primera mujer cubana que condujo un autom\u00f3vil|trans-title=Learn about the story of the first Cuban woman to drive a car |url=https://www.todocuba.org/conoce-la-historia-la-primera-mujer-cubana-condujo-automovil/ |website=TodoCuba |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=es |date=6 February 2018}}</ref> Having the car, she applied and was issued with a Havana driving licence in 1917 under the name of Mar\u00eda Calvo Nodarse,{{sfn|Schweid|2009|p=60}} the first woman in the Americas to be issued with a licence.<ref name=\"www.thecubanhistory.com\">{{cite web |title=MARIA Calvo Nodarse \"La Macorina Cubana\", First Women Chofer of America. VIDEO. {{!}} The History, Culture and Legacy of the People of Cuba |url=https://www.thecubanhistory.com/2019/11/maria-calvo-nodarse-la-macorina-cubana-first-women-chofer-of-america-maria-calvo-nodarse-la-macorina-cubana-primer-mujer-chofer-de-america-video/ |website=www.thecubanhistory.com |accessdate=16 April 2020 |date=1 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the time, licences could be denied if the applicant was of an \"immoral character\". It has been speculated that sexual favours were given by La Macorina to obtain her licence. There are anecdotal reports that La Macorina had problems with the police soon after she obtained her licence due to her poor driving.{{sfn|Schweid|2009|p=62}}\n\nBy the time of her retirement in 1934 she owned 9 cars, mostly European brands,{{sfn|Alfonso|2016}}{{sfn|del Castillo Pichardo|2017}} including a red [[Mercedes-Benz|Mercedes]]<ref name=\"TodoCuba\" /> and two from [[Hispano-Suiza]], one white and one a red convertible. She was often seen driving around Havana in one of the Hispano-Suizas with popular music of the time playing loudly.{{sfn|Alfonso|2016}}{{sfn|del Castillo Pichardo|2017}} The current owners of her cars sometimes bring them together as the \"La Macorina Club\"{{sfn|Schweid|2009|p=211}} for exhibitions in Havana.{{sfn|Valenzuela|2004}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Prostitution in Cuba]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite web |title=The True History of La Macorina |url=http://www.radiometropolitana.icrt.cu/2016/04/12/the-true-history-of-la-macorina/ |website=www.radiometropolitana.icrt.cu|first=Vanessa |last=Alfonso |accessdate=15 April 2020 |language=es-ES|ref=harv |date=12 April 2016}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Bono |first1=Ferran |title=Chavela Vargas y la deslumbrante belleza de Macorina |trans-title=Chavela Vargas and the dazzling beauty of Macorina |url=https://elpais.com/ccaa/2013/10/08/valencia/1381241250_827114.html |newspaper=El Pa\u00eds |accessdate=15 April 2020 |language=es|ref=harv |date=8 October 2013}}\n* {{cite web |last1=del Castillo Pichardo |first1=Jos\u00e9 |title=Ponme la mano aqu\u00ed Macorina |trans-title=Put your hand here Macorina |url=https://www.diariolibre.com/opinion/lecturas/ponme-la-mano-aqui-macorina-YX8606331 |website=www.diariolibre.com |accessdate=15 April 2020 |language=es-ES|ref=harv |date=18 November 2017}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Cooke |first1=Julia |title=The Other Side of Paradise: Life in the New Cuba |date=2014 |publisher=Basic Books |isbn=978-1-58005-532-1 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=pTRKDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT39&lpg=PT39&dq=havana+malecon+prostitution+1920s#v=onepage |ref=harv|language=en}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Echevarria |first1=Roberto Gonzalez |title=The Pride of Havana: A History of Cuban Baseball |date=2001 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-534917-7 |page= |url=https://books.google.com/?id=vSXRd4C3ihEC&pg=PA85&lpg=PA85&dq=the+Louvre+havana#v=onepage |ref=harv|language=en}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Iglesias |first1=Gema Rull |title=La primera mujer que condujo un auto y que obtuvo una licencia de conducci\u00f3n.|trans-title=The first woman to drive a car and obtain a license from driving |url=http://www.sld.cu/galerias/pdf/sitios/histologia/la_primera_mujer_que_condujo_un_auto.pdf |website=www.sld.cu |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=es |ref=harv|date=24 April 2008}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Nodal |first1=Leonel |title=Macorina, el nombre de una leyenda|trans-title=Macorina, the name of a legend |url=https://www.excelenciasdelmotor.com/otras-secciones/habana-500/macorina-el-nombre-de-una-leyenda |website=Excelencias del Motor |accessdate=15 April 2020 |language=es|ref=harv |date=24 February 2019}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Ortega |first1=Josefina |title=La Macorina |url=http://www.lajiribilla.cubaweb.cu/2009/n418_05/memoria.html |website=La Jiribilla |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=es|ref=harv |date=2008}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Ramos-Kittrell |first1=Jes\u00fas A. |title=Decentering the Nation: Music, Mexicanidad, and Globalization |date=2019 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1-4985-7318-4 |page= |url=https://books.google.com/?id=WWbBDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA50&dq=Mar%C3%ADa+Calvo+Nodarse#v=onepage|ref=harv |language=en}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Ross |first1=Ciro Bianchi |title=Cuba: A different Story |date=2017 |publisher=RUTH |isbn=978-959-211-427-2 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Mqi1DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT64&lpg=PT64&dq=Mar%C3%ADa+Calvo+Nodarse#v=onepage|ref=harv |language=en}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Schweid |first1=Richard |title=Che's Chevrolet, Fidel's Oldsmobile: On the Road in Cuba |date=2009 |publisher=Univ of North Carolina Press |isbn=978-0-8078-8862-9 |page= |url=https://books.google.com/?id=RlnqCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA60&lpg=PA60&dq=Mar%C3%ADa+Calvo+Nodarse#v=onepage|ref=harv |language=en}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Valenzuela |first1=L\u00eddice |title=Los almendrones: museo rodante de La Habana|trans-title=Los almendrones: rolling museum of Havana |url=http://www.cmbfradio.cu/cmbf/ciudad/articulos/almendrones.htm |website=www.cmbfradio.cu |accessdate=16 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090531074406/http://www.cmbfradio.cu/cmbf/ciudad/articulos/almendrones.htm |archivedate=31 May 2009|ref=harv |date=2004}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macorina, La}}\n\n[[Category:1892 births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n[[Category:Cuban prostitutes]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Cuban high-class prostitute}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = \n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Mar\u00eda Constancia Caraza Vald\u00e9s\n| birth_date    = {{Birth year|1892}}\n| birth_place   = [[Guanajay]], Cuba\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1977|06|15|1892||}} \n| death_place   = [[Havana]], Cuba\n| nationality   = [[Cubans|Cuban]]\n| other_names   = Mar\u00eda Calvo Nodarse\n| occupation    = [[Prostitute]]\n| years_active  = 1917-1934\n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Mar\u00eda Calvo Nodarse''' ([[Guanajay]], 1892 - [[Havana]], 15 June 1977), better known as '''La Macorina''', was a [[Cubans|Cuban]] high-class [[prostitute]] who was a friend of ex-president [[Jos\u00e9 Miguel G\u00f3mez]], who she supported during the [[History of Cuba#Cuba in the early 20th century|Chambelona War]]. She was the first female to a hold a [[driving license]] in the [[Americas]].\n\n==Biography==\nLa Macorina was born ''Mar\u00eda Constancia Caraza Vald\u00e9s''{{sfn|Alfonso|2016}} in 1892{{sfn|del Castillo Pichardo|2017}} in Guanajay, Cuba, then in [[Pinar del R\u00edo Province]]. She was reputed to be of [[Afro-Asians|Afro-Chinese]] heritage, but her driving license appears to show a white woman.{{sfn|Alfonso|2016}} Little is known of her childhood, but at 15 she left home and moved to Havana with her boyfriend. Although her parents tried to get her to return she stayed in Havana. The couple were faced economic hardship until a woman told her how they could live luxuriously and La Macorina turned to [[prostitution]].{{sfn|Alfonso|2016}} She assumed the name ''Mar\u00eda Calvo Nodarse'' and moved to Galiano Street, near the [[Malec\u00f3n, Havana|Malec\u00f3n]],{{sfn|Ortega|2008}} a popular location in Havana at the the time, including for prostitution.{{sfn|Cooke|2014}}\n\nPersonality and beauty helped La Macorina become one of the most elegant and famous prostitutes, entering the most select circles of Cuban society at the time. She was selective of her [[Client (prostitution)|clients]] and in an interview by Guillermo Villarronda<ref>{{cite web |title=Macorina |url=http://www.enricophil.it/tales/Central_America/Scripts/macorina.htm |website=www.enricophil.it |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> for Bohemia magazine in 1958, she said \"more than a dozen men were at my feet, full of money, and begging for love.\u201d{{sfn|Alfonso|2016}} She wore her hair short in the Garz\u00f3n style, which was considered scandalous at the time, and smoked cigars.<ref name=\"Hello Foros\">{{cite web |title=Personajes Celebres La Macorina |url=https://www.helloforos.com/t/personajes-celebres-la-macorina/271057 |website=Hello Foros - La Comunidad en Espa\u00f1ol m\u00e1s Popular de los Latinos |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=es |date=3 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nBy the time she retired in 1934 she had amassed a fortune. She owned mansions in Havana, Calzada, Linea and San Miguel,<ref name=\"Hello Foros\" /> race horses, expensive furs, a large collection of valuable jewellery and 9 cars.{{sfn|Alfonso|2016}}\n\n===Chambelona War===\nGeneral, later president, Jos\u00e9 Miguel G\u00f3mez was one of her protectors. La Macorina supported him during the Chambelona War. When G\u00f3mez was imprisoned in the [[Castillo del Pr\u00edncipe (Havana)|Castillo del Pr\u00edncipe]], La Macorina retained her loyalty.{{sfn|Ross|2017}} She  visited him and campaigned for his release and ferried his supporters around in her cars. La Macorina herself was imprisoned for 25 days in Havana prison during the period for her opposition to President [[Mario Garc\u00eda Menocal]]. Although Menocal had ordered her to be treated harshly in prison, warden Andr\u00e9s Hern\u00e1ndez arranged for her to have separate quarters and, in her words, \"treated me like a queen\".<ref name=\"TodoCuba\" />\n\n===Decline and death===\nLa Macorina retired in 1934 when the country's economics took a downturn and, at 42, her looks had started to fade. Although she had amassed a fortune, she was reputed to be spending two thousand pesos a month and soon had to start selling her assets. Her previous friends distanced themselves from her and she eventually ended up living in poverty in a rented room in Havana. La Macorina died in Havana on 15 June 1977.{{sfn|Alfonso|2016}}{{sfn|Iglesias|2008}}\n\n==In popular culture==\n{{Quote box |width=300px |align=right |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 | salign=right\n|title = Macorina\n |quote  =<poem>\nPut your hand here, Macorina,\nput your hand here.\nYour feet left the mat\nand your saya ran away\nlooking for the guard\nthat when your size was so fine,\nthe sugarcanes\nwere thrown down the road\nso that you could grind them\nas if you were a mill.\nYour breasts, flesh of anon,\nyour mouth a blessing\nof ripe soursop,\nand your thin waist was\nthe same as that\nhot danzon of that danzon.\nThen the dawn\nthat carries you from my arms,\nand I without knowing what to do\nwith that smell of woman,\nmango and new cane\nwith which you filled me to the\nwarm sound of that danz\u00f3n.<ref name=\"www.futurodecuba.org\">{{cite web |title=La Macorina\u00a0\u00a0 Maria Calvo Nodarse |url=http://www.futurodecuba.org/la_macorina___maria_calvo_nodars.htm |website=www.futurodecuba.org |accessdate=15 April 2020 |language=es}}</ref>{{sfn|del Castillo Pichardo|2017}}\n</poem>\n|source =\u2014Poem by [[Alfonso Cam\u00edn]]<br>-Recorded as a song by [[Chavela Vargas]]}}\nThe [[Asturias|Asturian]] [[Alfonso Cam\u00edn]] wrote a poem about her, \"''Macorina''\",  which was later recorded as a song by [[Chavela Vargas]],{{sfn|Ramos-Kittrell|2019|p=50}}  one of the best-known songs of her career. The chorus is a suggestive \"''Put Your Hand Here Macorina ..''\". Vargas met La Macorina in Havana \"getting out of a white car\" and was struck by her \"her slanted eyes and fierce hair.\" She later said of La Macorina \u201cShe was a beautiful woman. Black mixed from China. I saw her and I was speechless.\u201d{{sfn|Bono|2013}} The song became the \"lesbian hymn\"{{sfn|Ramos-Kittrell|2019|p=50}} and was banned in Spain during [[Francoist Spain|Francoism]].<ref name=\"Hello Foros\" />\n\nLa Macorina frequently drove around Havana in a red convertible Hispano-Suiza.{{sfn|del Castillo Pichardo|2017}} Artist [[Cundo Berm\u00fadez]] portrayed her in that setting in a painting from memory{{sfn|Alfonso|2016}} in 1978, the year after her death.<ref name=\"www.futurodecuba.org\" /> The red car also featured in the modified lyrics of the 1950s recording of \"''Macorina''\" by [[Abelardo Barroso]].{{sfn|del Castillo Pichardo|2017}}<ref name=\"www.futurodecuba.org\" />\n\nPoet [[Otilio Vigil D\u00edaz|Vigil D\u00edaz]] wrote enthusiastically about La Macorina in his \"Fatamorgana\" column for the Dominican newspaper [[List\u00edn Diario]].{{sfn|del Castillo Pichardo|2017}}\n\nIn his novel ''Las Impuras'', Miguel de Carrion based the main character ''La Aviadora'' on La Macorina.<ref name=\"Hello Foros\" />\n\nIn the brass bands parade during the [[Bejucal|Charangas de Bejucal]] annual festival, La Macorina was honoured as one of the parade's characters by a doll with a mask of her face.<ref name=\"www.futurodecuba.org\" /> The doll has been preserved.{{sfn|Ortega|2008}} La Macorina is still one of the characters of the Charangas, usually being present on the floats of \"''La Espina de Oro''\" and the \"''La Ceiba de Plata''\".<ref name=\"www.angerona.cult.cu\">{{cite web |title=La Habana, Cuba...La Macorina: Personaje de Bejucal |url=http://www.angerona.cult.cu/bejucal/lamacorina.htm |website=www.angerona.cult.cu |accessdate=16 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070807185621/http://www.angerona.cult.cu/bejucal/lamacorina.htm |archivedate=7 August 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Origin of \"La Macorina\"==\nThe nickname La Macorina is reputed to have come from a drunken young man. Whilst walking past the Acera del Louvre{{sfn|Nodal|2019}} (the terrace of the Louvre cafe where Cuba's literati and baseball players met),{{sfn|Echevarria|2001|p=85}} the young man on seeing her beauty said \"there goes La Macorina!\". He had meant to say \"La Fornarina\", mistaking her for the famous Spanish cupletista, ''Consuelo Bello'', who was commonly called La Fornarina after the famous painting of the [[La Fornarina|same name]] by Italian master [[Raphael]] of his lover [[Margarita Luti]].{{sfn|Nodal|2019}}\n\n==Cars and driving==\nLa Macorina's first car, a [[Ford]],<ref>{{cite web |title=La Macorina - Curiosidades |url=http://www.tvavila.icrt.cu/noticia.php?id=631&clas=Curiosidades |website=www.tvavila.icrt.cu |accessdate=16 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081230021402/http://www.tvavila.icrt.cu/noticia.php?id=631&clas=Curiosidades |archivedate=30 December 2008 |language=es |date=23 September 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> was presented to her as compensation by an an influential politician who had run her over in his car.<ref name=\"TodoCuba\">{{cite web |title=Conoce la historia de la primera mujer cubana que condujo un autom\u00f3vil|trans-title=Learn about the story of the first Cuban woman to drive a car |url=https://www.todocuba.org/conoce-la-historia-la-primera-mujer-cubana-condujo-automovil/ |website=TodoCuba |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=es |date=6 February 2018}}</ref> Having the car, she applied and was issued with a Havana driving licence in 1917 under the name of Mar\u00eda Calvo Nodarse,{{sfn|Schweid|2009|p=60}} the first woman in the Americas to be issued with a licence.<ref name=\"www.thecubanhistory.com\">{{cite web |title=MARIA Calvo Nodarse \"La Macorina Cubana\", First Women Chofer of America. VIDEO. {{!}} The History, Culture and Legacy of the People of Cuba |url=https://www.thecubanhistory.com/2019/11/maria-calvo-nodarse-la-macorina-cubana-first-women-chofer-of-america-maria-calvo-nodarse-la-macorina-cubana-primer-mujer-chofer-de-america-video/ |website=www.thecubanhistory.com |accessdate=16 April 2020 |date=1 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the time, licences could be denied if the applicant was of an \"immoral character\". It has been speculated that sexual favours were given by La Macorina to obtain her licence. There are anecdotal reports that La Macorina had problems with the police soon after she obtained her licence due to her poor driving.{{sfn|Schweid|2009|p=62}}\n\nBy the time of her retirement in 1934 she owned 9 cars, mostly European brands,{{sfn|Alfonso|2016}}{{sfn|del Castillo Pichardo|2017}} including a red [[Mercedes-Benz|Mercedes]]<ref name=\"TodoCuba\" /> and two from [[Hispano-Suiza]], one white and one a red convertible. She was often seen driving around Havana in one of the Hispano-Suizas with popular music of the time playing loudly.{{sfn|Alfonso|2016}}{{sfn|del Castillo Pichardo|2017}} The current owners of her cars sometimes bring them together as the \"La Macorina Club\"{{sfn|Schweid|2009|p=211}} for exhibitions in Havana.{{sfn|Valenzuela|2004}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Prostitution in Cuba]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite web |title=The True History of La Macorina |url=http://www.radiometropolitana.icrt.cu/2016/04/12/the-true-history-of-la-macorina/ |website=www.radiometropolitana.icrt.cu|first=Vanessa |last=Alfonso |accessdate=15 April 2020 |language=es-ES|ref=harv |date=12 April 2016}}\n* {{cite news |last1=Bono |first1=Ferran |title=Chavela Vargas y la deslumbrante belleza de Macorina |trans-title=Chavela Vargas and the dazzling beauty of Macorina |url=https://elpais.com/ccaa/2013/10/08/valencia/1381241250_827114.html |newspaper=El Pa\u00eds |accessdate=15 April 2020 |language=es|ref=harv |date=8 October 2013}}\n* {{cite web |last1=del Castillo Pichardo |first1=Jos\u00e9 |title=Ponme la mano aqu\u00ed Macorina |trans-title=Put your hand here Macorina |url=https://www.diariolibre.com/opinion/lecturas/ponme-la-mano-aqui-macorina-YX8606331 |website=www.diariolibre.com |accessdate=15 April 2020 |language=es-ES|ref=harv |date=18 November 2017}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Cooke |first1=Julia |title=The Other Side of Paradise: Life in the New Cuba |date=2014 |publisher=Basic Books |isbn=978-1-58005-532-1 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=pTRKDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT39&lpg=PT39&dq=havana+malecon+prostitution+1920s#v=onepage |ref=harv|language=en}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Echevarria |first1=Roberto Gonzalez |title=The Pride of Havana: A History of Cuban Baseball |date=2001 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-534917-7 |page= |url=https://books.google.com/?id=vSXRd4C3ihEC&pg=PA85&lpg=PA85&dq=the+Louvre+havana#v=onepage |ref=harv|language=en}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Iglesias |first1=Gema Rull |title=La primera mujer que condujo un auto y que obtuvo una licencia de conducci\u00f3n.|trans-title=The first woman to drive a car and obtain a license from driving |url=http://www.sld.cu/galerias/pdf/sitios/histologia/la_primera_mujer_que_condujo_un_auto.pdf |website=www.sld.cu |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=es |ref=harv|date=24 April 2008}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Nodal |first1=Leonel |title=Macorina, el nombre de una leyenda|trans-title=Macorina, the name of a legend |url=https://www.excelenciasdelmotor.com/otras-secciones/habana-500/macorina-el-nombre-de-una-leyenda |website=Excelencias del Motor |accessdate=15 April 2020 |language=es|ref=harv |date=24 February 2019}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Ortega |first1=Josefina |title=La Macorina |url=http://www.lajiribilla.cubaweb.cu/2009/n418_05/memoria.html |website=La Jiribilla |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=es|ref=harv |date=2008}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Ramos-Kittrell |first1=Jes\u00fas A. |title=Decentering the Nation: Music, Mexicanidad, and Globalization |date=2019 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1-4985-7318-4 |page= |url=https://books.google.com/?id=WWbBDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA50&dq=Mar%C3%ADa+Calvo+Nodarse#v=onepage|ref=harv |language=en}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Ross |first1=Ciro Bianchi |title=Cuba: A different Story |date=2017 |publisher=RUTH |isbn=978-959-211-427-2 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Mqi1DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT64&lpg=PT64&dq=Mar%C3%ADa+Calvo+Nodarse#v=onepage|ref=harv |language=en}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Schweid |first1=Richard |title=Che's Chevrolet, Fidel's Oldsmobile: On the Road in Cuba |date=2009 |publisher=Univ of North Carolina Press |isbn=978-0-8078-8862-9 |page= |url=https://books.google.com/?id=RlnqCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA60&lpg=PA60&dq=Mar%C3%ADa+Calvo+Nodarse#v=onepage|ref=harv |language=en}}\n* {{cite web |last1=Valenzuela |first1=L\u00eddice |title=Los almendrones: museo rodante de La Habana|trans-title=Los almendrones: rolling museum of Havana |url=http://www.cmbfradio.cu/cmbf/ciudad/articulos/almendrones.htm |website=www.cmbfradio.cu |accessdate=16 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090531074406/http://www.cmbfradio.cu/cmbf/ciudad/articulos/almendrones.htm |archivedate=31 May 2009|ref=harv |date=2004}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macorina, La}}\n\n[[Category:1892 births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n[[Category:Cuban prostitutes]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/La_Macorina"}
{"title_page": "Station to Station (song)", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Station to Station\n| cover      = David Bowie - Station to Station song cover art.jpg\n| alt        = \n| caption    = Label of the French promotional single\n| type       = Song\n| artist     = [[David Bowie]]\n| album      = [[Station to Station]]\n| B-side     = \n| released   = 23 January 1976\n| format     = \n| recorded   = September\u2013November 1975\n| studio     = [[Cherokee Studios|Cherokee]], Los Angeles\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Art rock]]|[[Progressive rock|prog]]-[[disco]]}}\n| length     = 10:14 (album)<br>3:40 (French single)\n| label      = [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n| writer     = David Bowie\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n* David Bowie\n* [[Harry Maslin]]\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Station to Station'''\" is a song by English singer-songwriter [[David Bowie]]. It was released in January 1976 as the title track and opener of his tenth studio album ''[[Station to Station]]'', as well as on a promotional [[Gramophone record|7-inch single]] in France the same month. Co-produced by Bowie and [[Harry Maslin]], it was written and recorded at [[Cherokee Studios]] in Los Angeles between September and November 1975. At over 10&nbsp;minutes in length, it is Bowie's longest studio recording. Opening with a train-like noise, the song's first half is a slow march, built around an atonal guitar riff, while the second half takes the form of a [[Progressive rock|prog]]-[[disco]] suite in a different key and tempo than the first. It contains elements of [[art rock]] and is influenced by the German electronic bands [[Kraftwerk]] and [[Tangerine Dream]].\n\nLyrically, the song introduces Bowie's sinister persona [[the Thin White Duke]], who became the mouthpiece for ''Station to Station'' and, throughout 1976, often the embodiment of Bowie himself. During the recording, Bowie was heavily dependent on drugs such as [[cocaine]], which is referenced directly throughout. \"Station to Station\" also makes references to the [[Kabbalah]], [[occultism]], [[gnosticism]], [[paranoia]] and other fixations that affected Bowie's mind at the time. The opening sound effect is a [[red herring]] meant to represent the [[Stations of the Cross]], along with a juncture connecting two different stages of his career; it combined the [[funk]] and [[Soul music|soul]] of his previous album ''[[Young Americans]]'' with the experimental sound he would explore on his [[Berlin Trilogy]].\n\n\"Station to Station\" has received acclaim from music critics, who have praised the performance of the band and Bowie himself. Retrospectively, it has been named one of Bowie's greatest songs and, like its parent album, is seen as the indicator of where his career was heading at the time. He performed the track throughout the [[Isolar \u2013 1976 Tour|1976 Isolar Tour]], often in character as the Thin White Duke, and continued to perform it on different tours throughout his career. It was remastered, along with its parent album, as part of the box set ''[[Who Can I Be Now? (1974\u20131976)]]'' in 2016.\n\n==Composition==\n\"Station to Station\" was recorded at [[Cherokee Studios]] in Los Angeles between September and November 1975.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=285}} According to Emily Barker of ''[[NME]]'', Bowie \"starved his body of all nutrients (besides [[milk]], red peppers, and [[cocaine]])\" during the song's recording.<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web |last1=Barker |first1=Emily |title=David Bowie's 40 greatest songs \u2013 as decided by ''NME'' and friends |url=https://www.nme.com/photos/david-bowie-s-40-greatest-songs-as-decided-by-nme-and-friends-1418012 |website=[[NME]] |accessdate=16 February 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191103063248/https://www.nme.com/photos/david-bowie-s-40-greatest-songs-as-decided-by-nme-and-friends-1418012 |archivedate=3 November 2019 |date=8 January 2018}}</ref> Bowie would recall later that he could not remember recording the album at all, saying \"I have only flashes of making it.\"{{sfn|Buckley|2005|p=234}} Author David Buckley states that Bowie's only memory of the sessions was \"standing with [lead guitarist] [[Earl Slick]] in the studio and asking him to play a [[Chuck Berry]] riff in the same key throughout the opening of 'Station to Station'.\"{{sfn|Buckley|2005|p=234}} At over 10 minutes in length, it is Bowie's longest studio recording.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=467}} Structurally, the song builds from a droning, guitar-driven introductory portion that mimics a train building up speed.{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|pp=78\u201380}} Following the train noise, the band begins to enter, with percussion and keyboards playing chords in and out of key.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=287}} What follows is, according to [[Peter Doggett]], a \"slow, hypnotic instrumental march\", led by an atonal guitar riff played by Bowie and Slick with syncopated accents across three bars in {{music|time|4|4}} and one in {{music|time|2|4}}.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=287}}<ref name=\"Light RS\" /> The march lasts for more than three minutes before Bowie begins his vocals.<ref name=\"Light RS\" /> After several verses, at the five-minute mark, a thud of drums signals a change of tempo and key and the band erupts into what Alan Light of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' calls a prog-disco \"celebratory groove\", which lasts for the rest of the track.<ref name=\"Light RS\" /><ref name=\"Needham Guardian\">{{cite web |last1=Needham |first1=Alex |title=My favorite album: ''Station to Station'' by David Bowie |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2011/sep/16/station-station-david-bowie |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=14 March 2020 |date=16 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406095256/https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2011/sep/16/station-station-david-bowie |archive-date=6 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=288}} Doggett likens the section to a [[progressive rock]] suite by the 1970s bands [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]] and [[Jethro Tull (band)|Jethro Tull]].{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=287}} Like the album, the entire song contains elements of [[art rock]].<ref name=\"AllMusic album\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/station-to-station-mw0000098920|title=''Station to Station'' \u2013 David Bowie {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|website=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=1 August 2019|quote=At its heart, ''Station to Station'' is an avant-garde art-rock album, most explicitly on 'TVC 15' and the epic sprawl of the title track|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190424115507/https://www.allmusic.com/album/station-to-station-mw0000098920|archive-date=24 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe train sound effect was created by Slick using [[Flanging|flangers]] and delay effects.{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|pp=78\u201380}}{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=287}} The noise pans from right to left across the stereo channels before fading out using [[feedback]], which Doggett likens to \"disappearing into a tunnel\".{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=287}} According to [[Nicholas Pegg]], the effect \"acknowledges\" the influence of the 1974 album ''[[Autobahn (album)|Autobahn]]'' by the German [[Electronic music|electronic]] band [[Kraftwerk]], which begins with a car starting up and driving across the stereo speakers.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=468}} Pegg believes another influence is from [[Edgar Froese]] of the German electronic band [[Tangerine Dream]], whom Bowie befriended during his \"Berlin\" years (1977\u20131979); Froese's 1975 album ''[[Epsilon in Malaysian Pale]]'' also begins with a train sound effect.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=468}} However, he notes that the train is a [[red herring]] in that it expresses what Bowie later called \"the album's 'wayward spiritual search'\".{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=468}} More specifically, it reinstates the \"travelling metaphor\" of earlier compositions: \"the stations recall the 'new surroundings' of \"[[Rock 'n' Roll with Me]]\" [from ''[[Diamond Dogs]]''], and the \"mountains on mountains\" reprise the questing motifs of \"[[Wild Eyed Boy from Freecloud]]\" [from ''[[David Bowie (1969 album)|David Bowie]]'' (1969)] and ''[[The Man Who Sold the World]]''.\"{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=468}} Bowie would later state, \"the 'Station to Station' track itself is very much concerned with the [[Stations of the Cross]]\",<ref name=Q97X /> the series of 14 images depicting [[Jesus|Christ]]'s path to [[Crucifixion of Jesus|his crucifixion]], each symbolising a stopping-point for [[prayer]].{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=468}} Stuart Berman of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' supports this, saying: \"the title track's momentous prog-disco suite&nbsp;[...] charts a course from spiritual void toward ecstatic religious reawakening.\"<ref name=\"Berman Pitchfork\">{{cite web|last=Berman|first=Stuart|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/14687-station-to-station-deluxe-edition/|title=David Bowie: ''Station to Station'' (Deluxe Edition)|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=29 September 2010|accessdate=22 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101021073153/http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/14687-station-to-station-deluxe-edition/|archive-date=21 October 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> Another possible influence is guitarist [[Jimmy Page]] of the English rock band [[Led Zeppelin]]. Page was a session musician on Bowie's earliest recordings and had been an occasional acquaintance ever since.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=469}} During the same time Bowie became dependent on cocaine, Page had become dependent on [[heroin]], which Pegg considered \"even more fearful\" than Bowie's addiction.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=469}} Led Zeppelin's ''[[Physical Graffiti]]'' was released in March 1975,<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Physical Graffiti|others=[[Led Zeppelin]]|year=1975|publisher=[[Swan Song Records]]|location=UK|type=liner notes|id=SSK 894007}}</ref> months ahead of the ''Station to Station'' sessions.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=469}} Pegg writes: \"It's possible to discern in [\"Station to Station\"] a distinct flavour of the groove, tempo and sense of building tension created by the famous rising riff of ''Physical Graffiti''<nowiki/>'s standout track '[[Kashmir (song)|Kashmir]]'\", an epic track that evokes a \"troubled spiritual journey\" through its music and lyrics.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=469}}\n\n==Lyrics==\n[[File:The Thin White Duke 76.jpg|thumb|160px|left|alt=David Bowie performing in 1976 and in character as the Thin White Duke|Bowie in character as the Thin White Duke performing on the [[Isolar \u2013 1976 Tour|1976 Isolar Tour]].]]\n\"Station to Station\" introduces Bowie's persona [[the Thin White Duke]], a sinister figure who became the mouthpiece for ''Station to Station'' and, often throughout 1976, for Bowie himself.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=467}}{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|pp=78\u201380}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Light |first=Alan |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/how-david-bowie-brought-thin-white-duke-to-life-on-station-to-station-125797/ |title=How David Bowie Brought Thin White Duke to Life on 'Station to Station' |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=26 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227040904/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/how-david-bowie-brought-thin-white-duke-to-life-on-station-to-station-125797/ |archive-date=27 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The persona was noticeably darker than Bowie's previous characters, being described as \"a mad aristocrat\",{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|pp=78\u201380}} an \"amoral zombie\",{{sfn|Buckley|2000|p=258}} and \"an emotionless ''[[Aryan race|Aryan]]'' superman\".{{sfn|Pegg|2004|pp=297\u2013300}} For Bowie himself, the Duke was \"a nasty character indeed\".{{sfn|Wilcken|2005|p=24}} The lyrics themselves contain very cryptic messages and direct references, including to the 13th century Jewish mystical system known as the [[Kabbalah]] and [[gnosticism]].<ref name=\"Q97X\">{{cite book| last=Cavanagh | first=David | title=ChangesFiftyBowie | journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q magazine]] |date=February 1997 | pages=52\u201359}}</ref> Bowie would later claim in 1997: \"All the references within [\"Station to Station\"] have to do with the Kabbalah.\"{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=286}} Doggett believes the main themes of the track are magic, the arts of legendary musicians, both real and fictitious, the Kabbalah's mythical account of progress from [[Keter|Kether]] to [[Malkuth]], love and cocaine.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=286}} Doggett further argues: \"just as [the ''[[Hunky Dory]]'' track] \"[[Quicksand (David Bowie song)|Quicksand]]\" offered a catalogue of avenues open to the inquisitive imagination of David Bowie circa 1971, so \"Station to Station\" present a more confused medley of the themes that were haunting his nightmares in the final weeks of 1975.\"{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=286}}\n\nThe Duke introduces himself by saying \"the return of the Thin White Duke/throwing darts in lovers' eyes.\"<ref name=\"Needham Guardian\" /> Darts, or arrows, are interpreted to be a symbol of direction revealing the dynamic of the True Will.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=286}} Doggett argues that other than the Thin White Duke, another duke was at the heart of the action: [[Prospero]], the Duke of [[Milan]] and protagonist of [[William Shakespeare]]'s play ''[[The Tempest]]''.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=285}} He writes that Prospero, like the Thin White Duke, is a \"master of magic\", who can control elements while \"lost in my [magic] circle\", as well as cast spells over \"lovers' eyes\" (mirroring throwing darts), as Prospero does with his daughter [[Miranda (The Tempest)|Miranda]] and her lover [[Ferdinand (The Tempest)|Ferdinand]] over the course of the play.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|pp=285\u2013286}} Fixation with the English [[occultist]] [[Aleister Crowley]] is evident in such phrases as \"[[White Stains|white stains]]\", the name of a book of poetry by Crowley,{{sfn|Wilcken|2005|p=7}} who was previously mentioned by Bowie on \"Quicksand\".{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=469}} Once the song changes into the prog-disco section, the lyrics become brighter. Punctuated by the refrain \"It's too late\",{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|pp=78\u201380}} Bowie enters a landscape of \"mountains and sunbirds\".{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=288}} Themes in this section include drug use, as presented in the lyrics \"It's not the side effects of the cocaine/I'm thinking that it must be love\",{{sfn|Wilcken|2005|p=9}} which he sings in a joyous tone.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=288}} Light writes that other themes present on the track are \"[[paranoia]] and odd fixations\" that were present in Bowie's mind at the time.<ref name=\"Light RS\" /> At different points Bowie declares \"the European canon is here\", which Doggett believes is a \"pretentious way\" of summarising Bowie's interest in Kraftwerk and [[Brechtian]] theatre; he also notes the word 'canon' could be interpreted \"at a stretch\" as the word 'cannon'.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=286}}\n\n==Release and reception==\n\"Station to Station\" was released as the opening title track to Bowie's tenth studio album [[Station to Station|of the same name]] on 23&nbsp;January 1976.<ref name=\"AllMusic album\" /><ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Station to Station|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=1976|publisher=[[RCA Records|RCA Victor]]|location=UK|type=liner notes|id=APL1 1327}}</ref> The song was also released as a [[promotional single]] (as 42549 A) in January 1976 in France by [[RCA Records]], with a shortened duration of&nbsp;3:40 and \"[[TVC 15]]\" as the B-side.<ref name=\"single liner notes\" /> The single version begins at the central section of the song with the drums just prior to the \"once there were mountains...\" lyric.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=470}} The single edit appears on the 2010 Deluxe Edition of ''Station to Station'' and on ''Re:Call&nbsp;2'', as part of the 2016 box set ''[[Who Can I Be Now? (1974\u20131976)]]''.<ref name=\"deluxe edition\">{{cite AV media notes|title=Station to Station|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=2010|publisher=[[EMI]]|location=USA & Europe|type=Deluxe edition liner notes|id=5099964760124}}</ref><ref name=\"who can I be now\">{{cite AV media notes|title=Who Can I Be Now? (1974\u20131976)|others=David Bowie|year=2016|publisher=[[Parlophone]]|location=UK, Europe & US|type=Box set booklet|id=0190295989842}}</ref> The full track was remastered, along with its parent album, and released on the same box set in 2016.<ref name=\"who can I be now\" />\n\nThe song has received acclaim from music critics, who have praised the performance of the band and Bowie himself. Nicholas Pegg praised the track, writing \"Scintillatingly performed and gorgeously produced, it represents one of the high watermarks in his studio work.\"{{sfn|Pegg|2016|pp=467\u2013468}} He further praises Bowie's vocal performance and Earl Slick's \"fine\" guitar contributions.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|pp=467\u2013468}} Dave Thompson of [[AllMusic]] calls the guitar work \"fabulous\" and makes the argument that the track could be the most \"evocative\" song Bowie ever wrote.<ref name=\"Thompson AllMusic\">{{cite web |last1=Thompson |first1=Dave |title=\"Station to Station\" |url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/station-to-station-mt0054050614 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=13 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607123337/https://www.allmusic.com/song/station-to-station-mt0054050614 |archive-date=7 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Doggett writes that what saves the track from \"utter obscurity\" and his audience from \"alienation\" was the music itself.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=287}} Alex Needham of ''[[The Guardian]]'', in a review declaring ''Station to Station'' his favorite album, calls the track \"monumental\", writing, \"[with the track] Bowie blasts away his immediate Philly soul past and speeds into a more experimental future over 10 totally exhilarating minutes.\"<ref name=\"Needham Guardian\" /> Needham also found it impressive that the song did not \"overshadow\" the rest of the album which he believes shows \"how much Bowie was on fire.\"<ref name=\"Needham Guardian\" /> In a review of the live album ''[[Glastonbury 2000]]'' in 2018, Sean T. Collins of ''Pitchfork'' calls the track a \"teutonic-occult behemoth\" and a highlight of the album. He felt the main section's \"off-kilter groove\" and the \"barreling ''braukeller'' climax\" were made for performing live.<ref name=\"Collins Pitchfork\" /> He continued, \"hearing Bowie croon Kabbalistic jargon like 'one magical movement from Kether to Malkuth' to [a] massive crowd serves as a helpful reminder that he remained, even then, one of the weirdest people ever to achieve festival-headlining success.\"<ref name=\"Collins Pitchfork\" /> In 2018, the writers of ''[[NME]]'' listed \"Station to Station\" as Bowie's 24th&nbsp;greatest song.<ref name=\"NME\" /> In a list of Bowie's 50 greatest songs, [[Alexis Petridis]] of ''The Guardian'' ranked the song third, calling the shift into its second section as \"possibly the single most thrilling moment in his entire catalogue.\"<ref name=\"Petridis Guardian\">{{cite web |last1=Petridis |first1=Alexis |authorlink=Alexis Petridis|title=David Bowie's 50 greatest songs \u2013 ranked! |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/mar/19/david-bowie-50-greatest-songs-ranked |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=23 March 2020 |date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322224635/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/mar/19/david-bowie-50-greatest-songs-ranked |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\"Station to Station\" has been described as heralding \"a new era of experimentalism\" for Bowie.{{sfn|Buckley|2000|pp=275\u2013277}} Along with the rest of the album, the song presented the new direction Bowie was taking in his career, from the [[funk]] and [[Soul music|soul]] of ''[[Young Americans]]'' to the experimental sound of his [[Berlin Trilogy]].{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|pp=78\u201380}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=470}} In 2001, Bowie said, \"As far as the music goes, ''[[Low (David Bowie album)|Low]]'' and its siblings were a direct follow-on from the title track [of ''Station to Station'']. It's often struck me that there will usually be one track on any given album of mine, which will be a fair indicator of the intent of the following album.\"{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=467}} \nNeedham from ''The Guardian'' similarly writes that with the lyrics \"the European cannon is here\", Bowie fully announces what was to come.<ref name=\"Needham Guardian\" /> Doggett writes: \"Here was Bowie's first nod of recognition to the so-called ''[[motorik]]'' sound of [[Krautrock]], as the ominous, [[Wagnerian]] strains of the early segments of the song were succeeded by the propulsive dance rhythms of the finale. Only a churl would have worried that the theme of this cathartic moment was that it was too \u2013 suggesting that the spiritual journey might be only just beginning.\"{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=288}}\n\n==Live versions==\n\"Station to Station\" was the opening number throughout the [[Isolar \u2013 1976 Tour|1976 Isolar Tour]].{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=470}} A performance from this tour was included on the 2017 [[live album]] ''[[Live Nassau Coliseum '76]]'',<ref>{{cite web |last1= |first1= |title=''Live Nassau Coliseum '76'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/live-nassau-coliseum-76-mw0003015315 |publisher=AllMusic |accessdate=3 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191117143208/https://www.allmusic.com/album/live-nassau-coliseum-76-mw0003015315 |archive-date=17 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> which was released as part of the 2010 Deluxe Edition of ''Station to Station'' and on the 2016 box set ''Who Can I Be Now? (1974\u20131976)''.<ref name=\"deluxe edition\" /><ref name=\"who can I be now\" /> It was subsequently performed on the [[Isolar II \u2013 The 1978 World Tour|Stage]] (1978), [[Serious Moonlight Tour|Serious Moonlight]] (1984), [[Sound+Vision Tour|Sound+Vision]] (1990), [[Mini Tour (David Bowie)|Summer 2000]] and [[A Reality Tour|A Reality]] (2003\u20132004) tours.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=470}} Performances from the Stage tour have been released on ''[[Stage (David Bowie album)|Stage]]'' (1978) and ''[[Welcome to the Blackout (Live London '78)|Welcome to the Blackout]]'' (2018).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=''Welcome to the Blackout (Live London '78)'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/welcome-to-the-blackout-live-london-78-mw0003173016 |publisher=AllMusic |accessdate=12 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191117143206/https://www.allmusic.com/album/welcome-to-the-blackout-live-london-78-mw0003173016 |archive-date=17 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=''Stage'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/stage-mw0000193055 |publisher=AllMusic |accessdate=12 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190805090901/https://www.allmusic.com/album/stage-mw0000193055 |archive-date=5 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The ''Stage'' version was also featured in the [[Uli Edel]] film ''[[Christiane F. (film)|Christiane&nbsp;F.]]'' (1981), where Bowie, miming recording, made an appearance as himself performing the song at a concert.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=470}} An edit of this version was released on the film's [[Christiane F. (album)|soundtrack]]. A performance from the Serious Moonlight Tour was included on the live album ''Serious Moonlight (Live '83)'', which was part of the 2018 box set ''[[Loving the Alien (1983\u20131988)]]''.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Loving the Alien (1983\u20131988)|others=David Bowie|year=2018|publisher=Parlophone|location=UK, Europe & US|type=Box set booklet|id=0190295693534}}</ref> and released as its own album in 2019.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Serious Moonlight (Live '83)|others=David Bowie|year=2019|publisher=Parlophone|location=Europe|type=CD liner notes|id=0190295511180}}</ref> Bowie's performance of the song at the Glastonbury Festival in June 2000 was released in 2018 on ''[[Glastonbury 2000]]''.<ref name=\"Collins Pitchfork\">{{cite web |last1=Collins |first1=Sean T. |title=David Bowie: ''Glastonbury 2000'' Album Review |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/david-bowie-glastonbury-2000/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=14 March 2020 |date=5 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711093411/https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/david-bowie-glastonbury-2000/ |archive-date=11 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs written by David Bowie.<ref name=\"single liner notes\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=''\"Station to Station\"''|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=1976|publisher=[[RCA Records|RCA]]|location=France|type=Single liner notes|id=42549}}</ref>\n;7\" French promotional single\n# \"Station to Station\" \u2013 3:40\n# \"[[TVC 15]]\" \u2013 4:40\n\n==Personnel==\nPersonnel per ''Rolling Stone'' and David Buckley.{{sfn|Buckley|2005|p=234}}<ref name=\"Light RS\">{{cite web |last1=Light |first1=Alan |title=How David Bowie Brought Thin White Duke to Life on 'Station to Station' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/how-david-bowie-brought-thin-white-duke-to-life-on-station-to-station-125797/ |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=14 March 2020 |date=23 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227040904/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/how-david-bowie-brought-thin-white-duke-to-life-on-station-to-station-125797/ |archive-date=27 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*[[David Bowie]] \u2013 lead vocals, acoustic guitar, production\n*[[Earl Slick]] \u2013 lead guitar\n*[[Carlos Alomar]] \u2013 rhythm guitar\n*[[George Murray (musician)|George Murray]] \u2013 bass\n*[[Roy Bittan]] \u2013 piano, [[electronic organ|organ]]\n*[[Dennis Davis]] \u2013 drums\n*[[Warren Peace]] \u2013 [[percussion]], backing vocals\n*[[Harry Maslin]] \u2013 [[melodica]], production\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n;Sources\n*{{cite book |last=Buckley |first=David |year=2000 |origyear=1999 |title=Strange Fascination \u2013 David Bowie: The Definitive Story |location=London |publisher=[[Virgin Group|Virgin]] |isbn=0-7535-0457-X |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Buckley |first=David |year=2005 |origyear=1999 |title=Strange Fascination \u2013 David Bowie: The Definitive Story |location=London |publisher=Virgin |isbn=978-0-75351-002-5 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Carr |first1=Roy|authorlink1=Roy Carr |last2=Murray |first2=Charles Shaar| authorlink2=Charles Shaar Murray |year=1981 |title=Bowie: An Illustrated Record |publisher=[[Eel Pie Publishing]] |isbn=978-0-38077-966-6|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Doggett |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Doggett |year=2012 |title=The Man Who Sold the World: David Bowie and the 1970s |publisher=[[HarperCollins|HarperCollins Publishers]] |isbn=978-0-06-202466-4 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Pegg |first=Nicholas |authorlink=Nicholas Pegg |year=2004 |origyear=2000 |title=The Complete David Bowie |location=London |publisher=Reynolds & Hearn |isbn=1-903111-73-0|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pegg |first=Nicholas |title=The Complete David Bowie |publisher=[[Titan Books]] |edition=7th |location=London |year=2016 |isbn=978-1-78565-365-0 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Wilcken |first=Hugo |year=2005 |title=Low |location=New York, London |publisher=[[Continuum International Publishing Group|Continuum]] |isbn=0-8264-1684-5|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|david-bowie|station-to-station}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{David Bowie singles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Station To Station (Song)}}\n[[Category:British disco songs]]\n[[Category:British progressive rock songs]]\n[[Category:David Bowie songs]]\n[[Category:1976 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by David Bowie]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by David Bowie]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Station to Station\n| cover      = David Bowie - Station to Station song cover art.jpg\n| alt        = \n| caption    = Label of the French promotional single\n| type       = Song\n| artist     = [[David Bowie]]\n| album      = [[Station to Station]]\n| B-side     = \n| released   = 23 January 1976\n| format     = \n| recorded   = September\u2013November 1975\n| studio     = [[Cherokee Studios|Cherokee]], Los Angeles\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Art rock]]|[[Progressive rock|prog]]-[[disco]]}}\n| length     = 10:14 (album)<br>3:40 (French single)\n| label      = [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n| writer     = David Bowie\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n* David Bowie\n* [[Harry Maslin]]\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Station to Station'''\" is a song by English singer-songwriter [[David Bowie]]. It was released in January 1976 as the title track and opener of his tenth studio album ''[[Station to Station]]'', as well as on a promotional [[Gramophone record|7-inch single]] in France the same month. Co-produced by Bowie and [[Harry Maslin]], it was written and recorded at [[Cherokee Studios]] in Los Angeles between September and November 1975. At over 10&nbsp;minutes in length, it is Bowie's longest studio recording. Opening with a train-like noise, the song's first half is a slow march, built around an atonal guitar riff, while the second half takes the form of a [[Progressive rock|prog]]-[[disco]] suite in a different key and tempo than the first. It contains elements of [[art rock]] and is influenced by the German electronic bands [[Kraftwerk]] and [[Tangerine Dream]].\n\nLyrically, the song introduces Bowie's sinister persona [[the Thin White Duke]], who became the mouthpiece for ''Station to Station'' and, throughout 1976, often the embodiment of Bowie himself. During the recording, Bowie was heavily dependent on drugs such as [[cocaine]], which is referenced directly throughout. \"Station to Station\" also makes references to the [[Kabbalah]], [[occultism]], [[gnosticism]], [[paranoia]] and other fixations that affected Bowie's mind at the time. The opening sound effect is a [[red herring]] meant to represent the [[Stations of the Cross]], along with a juncture connecting two different stages of his career; it combined the [[funk]] and [[Soul music|soul]] of his previous album ''[[Young Americans]]'' with the experimental sound he would explore on his [[Berlin Trilogy]].\n\n\"Station to Station\" has received acclaim from music critics, who have praised the performance of the band and Bowie himself. Retrospectively, it has been named one of Bowie's greatest songs and, like its parent album, is seen as the indicator of where his career was heading at the time. He performed the track throughout the [[Isolar \u2013 1976 Tour|1976 Isolar Tour]], often in character as the Thin White Duke, and continued to perform it on different tours throughout his career. It was remastered, along with its parent album, as part of the box set ''[[Who Can I Be Now? (1974\u20131976)]]'' in 2016.\n\n==Composition==\n\"Station to Station\" was recorded at [[Cherokee Studios]] in Los Angeles between September and November 1975.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=285}} According to Emily Barker of ''[[NME]]'', Bowie \"starved his body of all nutrients (besides [[milk]], red peppers, and [[cocaine]])\" during the song's recording.<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web |last1=Barker |first1=Emily |title=David Bowie's 40 greatest songs \u2013 as decided by ''NME'' and friends |url=https://www.nme.com/photos/david-bowie-s-40-greatest-songs-as-decided-by-nme-and-friends-1418012 |website=[[NME]] |accessdate=16 February 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191103063248/https://www.nme.com/photos/david-bowie-s-40-greatest-songs-as-decided-by-nme-and-friends-1418012 |archivedate=3 November 2019 |date=8 January 2018}}</ref> Bowie would recall later that he could not remember recording the album at all, saying \"I have only flashes of making it.\"{{sfn|Buckley|2005|p=234}} Author David Buckley states that Bowie's only memory of the sessions was \"standing with [lead guitarist] [[Earl Slick]] in the studio and asking him to play a [[Chuck Berry]] riff in the same key throughout the opening of 'Station to Station'.\"{{sfn|Buckley|2005|p=234}} At over 10 minutes in length, it is Bowie's longest studio recording.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=467}} Structurally, the song builds from a droning, guitar-driven introductory portion that mimics a train building up speed.{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|pp=78\u201380}} Following the train noise, the band begins to enter, with percussion and keyboards playing chords in and out of key.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=287}} What follows is, according to [[Peter Doggett]], a \"slow, hypnotic instrumental march\", led by an atonal guitar riff played by Bowie and Slick with syncopated accents across three bars in {{music|time|4|4}} and one in {{music|time|2|4}}.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=287}}<ref name=\"Light RS\" /> The march lasts for more than three minutes before Bowie begins his vocals.<ref name=\"Light RS\" /> After several verses, at the five-minute mark, a thud of drums signals a change of tempo and key and the band erupts into what Alan Light of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' calls a prog-disco \"celebratory groove\", which lasts for the rest of the track.<ref name=\"Light RS\" /><ref name=\"Needham Guardian\">{{cite web |last1=Needham |first1=Alex |title=My favorite album: ''Station to Station'' by David Bowie |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2011/sep/16/station-station-david-bowie |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=14 March 2020 |date=16 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406095256/https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2011/sep/16/station-station-david-bowie |archive-date=6 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=288}} Doggett likens the section to a [[progressive rock]] suite by the 1970s bands [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]] and [[Jethro Tull (band)|Jethro Tull]].{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=287}} Like the album, the entire song contains elements of [[art rock]].<ref name=\"AllMusic album\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/station-to-station-mw0000098920|title=''Station to Station'' \u2013 David Bowie {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|website=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=1 August 2019|quote=At its heart, ''Station to Station'' is an avant-garde art-rock album, most explicitly on 'TVC 15' and the epic sprawl of the title track|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190424115507/https://www.allmusic.com/album/station-to-station-mw0000098920|archive-date=24 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe train sound effect was created by Slick using [[Flanging|flangers]] and delay effects.{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|pp=78\u201380}}{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=287}} The noise pans from right to left across the stereo channels before fading out using [[feedback]], which Doggett likens to \"disappearing into a tunnel\".{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=287}} According to [[Nicholas Pegg]], the effect \"acknowledges\" the influence of the 1974 album ''[[Autobahn (album)|Autobahn]]'' by the German [[Electronic music|electronic]] band [[Kraftwerk]], which begins with a car starting up and driving across the stereo speakers.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=468}} Pegg believes another influence is from [[Edgar Froese]] of the German electronic band [[Tangerine Dream]], whom Bowie befriended during his \"Berlin\" years (1977\u20131979); Froese's 1975 album ''[[Epsilon in Malaysian Pale]]'' also begins with a train sound effect.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=468}} However, he notes that the train is a [[red herring]] in that it expresses what Bowie later called \"the album's 'wayward spiritual search'\".{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=468}} More specifically, it reinstates the \"travelling metaphor\" of earlier compositions: \"the stations recall the 'new surroundings' of \"[[Rock 'n' Roll with Me]]\" [from ''[[Diamond Dogs]]''], and the \"mountains on mountains\" reprise the questing motifs of \"[[Wild Eyed Boy from Freecloud]]\" [from ''[[David Bowie (1969 album)|David Bowie]]'' (1969)] and ''[[The Man Who Sold the World]]''.\"{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=468}} Bowie would later state, \"the 'Station to Station' track itself is very much concerned with the [[Stations of the Cross]]\",<ref name=Q97X /> the series of 14 images depicting [[Jesus|Christ]]'s path to [[Crucifixion of Jesus|his crucifixion]], each symbolising a stopping-point for [[prayer]].{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=468}} Stuart Berman of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' supports this, saying: \"the title track's momentous prog-disco suite&nbsp;[...] charts a course from spiritual void toward ecstatic religious reawakening.\"<ref name=\"Berman Pitchfork\">{{cite web|last=Berman|first=Stuart|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/14687-station-to-station-deluxe-edition/|title=David Bowie: ''Station to Station'' (Deluxe Edition)|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=29 September 2010|accessdate=22 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101021073153/http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/14687-station-to-station-deluxe-edition/|archive-date=21 October 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> Another possible influence is guitarist [[Jimmy Page]] of the English rock band [[Led Zeppelin]]. Page was a session musician on Bowie's earliest recordings and had been an occasional acquaintance ever since.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=469}} During the same time Bowie became dependent on cocaine, Page had become dependent on [[heroin]], which Pegg considered \"even more fearful\" than Bowie's addiction.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=469}} Led Zeppelin's ''[[Physical Graffiti]]'' was released in March 1975,<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Physical Graffiti|others=[[Led Zeppelin]]|year=1975|publisher=[[Swan Song Records]]|location=UK|type=liner notes|id=SSK 894007}}</ref> months ahead of the ''Station to Station'' sessions.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=469}} Pegg writes: \"It's possible to discern in [\"Station to Station\"] a distinct flavour of the groove, tempo and sense of building tension created by the famous rising riff of ''Physical Graffiti''<nowiki/>'s standout track '[[Kashmir (song)|Kashmir]]'\", an epic track that evokes a \"troubled spiritual journey\" through its music and lyrics.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=469}}\n\n==Lyrics==\n[[File:The Thin White Duke 76.jpg|thumb|160px|left|alt=David Bowie performing in 1976 and in character as the Thin White Duke|Bowie in character as the Thin White Duke performing on the [[Isolar \u2013 1976 Tour|1976 Isolar Tour]].]]\n\"Station to Station\" introduces Bowie's persona [[the Thin White Duke]], a sinister figure who became the mouthpiece for ''Station to Station'' and, often throughout 1976, for Bowie himself.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=467}}{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|pp=78\u201380}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Light |first=Alan |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/how-david-bowie-brought-thin-white-duke-to-life-on-station-to-station-125797/ |title=How David Bowie Brought Thin White Duke to Life on 'Station to Station' |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=26 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227040904/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/how-david-bowie-brought-thin-white-duke-to-life-on-station-to-station-125797/ |archive-date=27 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The persona was noticeably darker than Bowie's previous characters, being described as \"a mad aristocrat\",{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|pp=78\u201380}} an \"amoral zombie\",{{sfn|Buckley|2000|p=258}} and \"an emotionless ''[[Aryan race|Aryan]]'' superman\".{{sfn|Pegg|2004|pp=297\u2013300}} For Bowie himself, the Duke was \"a nasty character indeed\".{{sfn|Wilcken|2005|p=24}} The lyrics themselves contain very cryptic messages and direct references, including to the 13th century Jewish mystical system known as the [[Kabbalah]] and [[gnosticism]].<ref name=\"Q97X\">{{cite book| last=Cavanagh | first=David | title=ChangesFiftyBowie | journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q magazine]] |date=February 1997 | pages=52\u201359}}</ref> Bowie would later claim in 1997: \"All the references within [\"Station to Station\"] have to do with the Kabbalah.\"{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=286}} Author [[Peter Doggett]] believes the main themes of the track are magic, the arts of legendary musicians, both real and fictitious, the Kabbalah's mythical account of progress from [[Keter|Kether]] to [[Malkuth]], love and cocaine.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=286}} Doggett further argues: \"just as [the ''[[Hunky Dory]]'' track] \"[[Quicksand (David Bowie song)|Quicksand]]\" offered a catalogue of avenues open to the inquisitive imagination of David Bowie circa 1971, so \"Station to Station\" present a more confused medley of the themes that were haunting his nightmares in the final weeks of 1975.\"{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=286}}\n\nThe Duke introduces himself by saying \"the return of the Thin White Duke/throwing darts in lovers' eyes.\"<ref name=\"Needham Guardian\" /> Darts, or arrows, are interpreted to be a symbol of direction revealing the dynamic of the True Will.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=286}} Doggett argues that other than the Thin White Duke, another duke was at the heart of the action: [[Prospero]], the Duke of [[Milan]] and protagonist of [[William Shakespeare]]'s play ''[[The Tempest]]''.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=285}} He writes that Prospero, like the Thin White Duke, is a \"master of magic\", who can control elements while \"lost in my [magic] circle\", as well as cast spells over \"lovers' eyes\" (mirroring throwing darts), as Prospero does with his daughter [[Miranda (The Tempest)|Miranda]] and her lover [[Ferdinand (The Tempest)|Ferdinand]] over the course of the play.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|pp=285\u2013286}} Fixation with the English [[occultist]] [[Aleister Crowley]] is evident in such phrases as \"[[White Stains|white stains]]\", the name of a book of poetry by Crowley,{{sfn|Wilcken|2005|p=7}} who was previously mentioned by Bowie on \"Quicksand\".{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=469}} Once the song changes into the prog-disco section, the lyrics become brighter. Punctuated by the refrain \"It's too late\",{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|pp=78\u201380}} Bowie enters a landscape of \"mountains and sunbirds\".{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=288}} Themes in this section include drug use, as presented in the lyrics \"It's not the side effects of the cocaine/I'm thinking that it must be love\",{{sfn|Wilcken|2005|p=9}} which he sings in a joyous tone.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=288}} Light writes that other themes present on the track are \"[[paranoia]] and odd fixations\" that were present in Bowie's mind at the time.<ref name=\"Light RS\" /> At different points Bowie declares \"the European canon is here\", which Doggett believes is a \"pretentious way\" of summarising Bowie's interest in Kraftwerk and [[Brechtian]] theatre; he also notes the word 'canon' could be interpreted \"at a stretch\" as the word 'cannon'.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=286}}\n\n==Release and reception==\n\"Station to Station\" was released as the opening title track to Bowie's tenth studio album [[Station to Station|of the same name]] on 23&nbsp;January 1976.<ref name=\"AllMusic album\" /><ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Station to Station|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=1976|publisher=[[RCA Records|RCA Victor]]|location=UK|type=liner notes|id=APL1 1327}}</ref> The song was also released as a [[promotional single]] (as 42549 A) in January 1976 in France by [[RCA Records]], with a shortened duration of&nbsp;3:40 and \"[[TVC 15]]\" as the B-side.<ref name=\"single liner notes\" /> The single version begins at the central section of the song with the drums just prior to the \"once there were mountains...\" lyric.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=470}} The single edit appears on the 2010 Deluxe Edition of ''Station to Station'' and on ''Re:Call&nbsp;2'', as part of the 2016 box set ''[[Who Can I Be Now? (1974\u20131976)]]''.<ref name=\"deluxe edition\">{{cite AV media notes|title=Station to Station|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=2010|publisher=[[EMI]]|location=USA & Europe|type=Deluxe edition liner notes|id=5099964760124}}</ref><ref name=\"who can I be now\">{{cite AV media notes|title=Who Can I Be Now? (1974\u20131976)|others=David Bowie|year=2016|publisher=[[Parlophone]]|location=UK, Europe & US|type=Box set booklet|id=0190295989842}}</ref> The full track was remastered, along with its parent album, and released on the same box set in 2016.<ref name=\"who can I be now\" />\n\nThe song has received acclaim from music critics, who have praised the performance of the band and Bowie himself. Nicholas Pegg praised the track, writing \"Scintillatingly performed and gorgeously produced, it represents one of the high watermarks in his studio work.\"{{sfn|Pegg|2016|pp=467\u2013468}} He further praises Bowie's vocal performance and Earl Slick's \"fine\" guitar contributions.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|pp=467\u2013468}} Dave Thompson of [[AllMusic]] calls the guitar work \"fabulous\" and makes the argument that the track could be the most \"evocative\" song Bowie ever wrote.<ref name=\"Thompson AllMusic\">{{cite web |last1=Thompson |first1=Dave |title=\"Station to Station\" |url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/station-to-station-mt0054050614 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=13 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607123337/https://www.allmusic.com/song/station-to-station-mt0054050614 |archive-date=7 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Doggett writes that what saves the track from \"utter obscurity\" and his audience from \"alienation\" was the music itself.{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=287}} Alex Needham of ''[[The Guardian]]'', in a review declaring ''Station to Station'' his favorite album, calls the track \"monumental\", writing, \"[with the track] Bowie blasts away his immediate Philly soul past and speeds into a more experimental future over 10 totally exhilarating minutes.\"<ref name=\"Needham Guardian\" /> Needham also found it impressive that the song did not \"overshadow\" the rest of the album which he believes shows \"how much Bowie was on fire.\"<ref name=\"Needham Guardian\" /> In a review of the live album ''[[Glastonbury 2000]]'' in 2018, Sean T. Collins of ''Pitchfork'' calls the track a \"teutonic-occult behemoth\" and a highlight of the album. He felt the main section's \"off-kilter groove\" and the \"barreling ''braukeller'' climax\" were made for performing live.<ref name=\"Collins Pitchfork\" /> He continued, \"hearing Bowie croon Kabbalistic jargon like 'one magical movement from Kether to Malkuth' to [a] massive crowd serves as a helpful reminder that he remained, even then, one of the weirdest people ever to achieve festival-headlining success.\"<ref name=\"Collins Pitchfork\" /> In 2018, the writers of ''[[NME]]'' listed \"Station to Station\" as Bowie's 24th&nbsp;greatest song.<ref name=\"NME\" /> In a list of Bowie's 50 greatest songs, [[Alexis Petridis]] of ''The Guardian'' ranked the song third, calling the shift into its second section as \"possibly the single most thrilling moment in his entire catalogue.\"<ref name=\"Petridis Guardian\">{{cite web |last1=Petridis |first1=Alexis |authorlink=Alexis Petridis|title=David Bowie's 50 greatest songs \u2013 ranked! |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/mar/19/david-bowie-50-greatest-songs-ranked |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=23 March 2020 |date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322224635/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/mar/19/david-bowie-50-greatest-songs-ranked |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\"Station to Station\" has been described as heralding \"a new era of experimentalism\" for Bowie.{{sfn|Buckley|2000|pp=275\u2013277}} Along with the rest of the album, the song presented the new direction Bowie was taking in his career, from the [[funk]] and [[Soul music|soul]] of ''[[Young Americans]]'' to the experimental sound of his [[Berlin Trilogy]].{{sfn|Carr|Murray|1981|pp=78\u201380}}{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=470}} In 2001, Bowie said, \"As far as the music goes, ''[[Low (David Bowie album)|Low]]'' and its siblings were a direct follow-on from the title track [of ''Station to Station'']. It's often struck me that there will usually be one track on any given album of mine, which will be a fair indicator of the intent of the following album.\"{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=467}} \nNeedham from ''The Guardian'' similarly writes that with the lyrics \"the European cannon is here\", Bowie fully announces what was to come.<ref name=\"Needham Guardian\" /> Doggett writes: \"Here was Bowie's first nod of recognition to the so-called ''[[motorik]]'' sound of [[Krautrock]], as the ominous, [[Wagnerian]] strains of the early segments of the song were succeeded by the propulsive dance rhythms of the finale. Only a churl would have worried that the theme of this cathartic moment was that it was too \u2013 suggesting that the spiritual journey might be only just beginning.\"{{sfn|Doggett|2012|p=288}}\n\n==Live versions==\n\"Station to Station\" was the opening number throughout the [[Isolar \u2013 1976 Tour|1976 Isolar Tour]].{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=470}} A performance from this tour was included on the 2017 [[live album]] ''[[Live Nassau Coliseum '76]]'',<ref>{{cite web |last1= |first1= |title=''Live Nassau Coliseum '76'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/live-nassau-coliseum-76-mw0003015315 |publisher=AllMusic |accessdate=3 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191117143208/https://www.allmusic.com/album/live-nassau-coliseum-76-mw0003015315 |archive-date=17 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> which was released as part of the 2010 Deluxe Edition of ''Station to Station'' and on the 2016 box set ''Who Can I Be Now? (1974\u20131976)''.<ref name=\"deluxe edition\" /><ref name=\"who can I be now\" /> It was subsequently performed on the [[Isolar II \u2013 The 1978 World Tour|Stage]] (1978), [[Serious Moonlight Tour|Serious Moonlight]] (1984), [[Sound+Vision Tour|Sound+Vision]] (1990), [[Mini Tour (David Bowie)|Summer 2000]] and [[A Reality Tour|A Reality]] (2003\u20132004) tours.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=470}} Performances from the Stage tour have been released on ''[[Stage (David Bowie album)|Stage]]'' (1978) and ''[[Welcome to the Blackout (Live London '78)|Welcome to the Blackout]]'' (2018).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=''Welcome to the Blackout (Live London '78)'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/welcome-to-the-blackout-live-london-78-mw0003173016 |publisher=AllMusic |accessdate=12 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191117143206/https://www.allmusic.com/album/welcome-to-the-blackout-live-london-78-mw0003173016 |archive-date=17 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=''Stage'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/stage-mw0000193055 |publisher=AllMusic |accessdate=12 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190805090901/https://www.allmusic.com/album/stage-mw0000193055 |archive-date=5 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The ''Stage'' version was also featured in the [[Uli Edel]] film ''[[Christiane F. (film)|Christiane&nbsp;F.]]'' (1981), where Bowie, miming recording, made an appearance as himself performing the song at a concert.{{sfn|Pegg|2016|p=470}} An edit of this version was released on the film's [[Christiane F. (album)|soundtrack]]. A performance from the Serious Moonlight Tour was included on the live album ''Serious Moonlight (Live '83)'', which was part of the 2018 box set ''[[Loving the Alien (1983\u20131988)]]''.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Loving the Alien (1983\u20131988)|others=David Bowie|year=2018|publisher=Parlophone|location=UK, Europe & US|type=Box set booklet|id=0190295693534}}</ref> and released as its own album in 2019.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=Serious Moonlight (Live '83)|others=David Bowie|year=2019|publisher=Parlophone|location=Europe|type=CD liner notes|id=0190295511180}}</ref> Bowie's performance of the song at the Glastonbury Festival in June 2000 was released in 2018 on ''[[Glastonbury 2000]]''.<ref name=\"Collins Pitchfork\">{{cite web |last1=Collins |first1=Sean T. |title=David Bowie: ''Glastonbury 2000'' Album Review |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/david-bowie-glastonbury-2000/ |website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=14 March 2020 |date=5 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711093411/https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/david-bowie-glastonbury-2000/ |archive-date=11 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs written by David Bowie.<ref name=\"single liner notes\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=''\"Station to Station\"''|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=1976|publisher=[[RCA Records|RCA]]|location=France|type=Single liner notes|id=42549}}</ref>\n;7\" French promotional single\n# \"Station to Station\" \u2013 3:40\n# \"[[TVC 15]]\" \u2013 4:40\n\n==Personnel==\nPersonnel per ''Rolling Stone'' and David Buckley.{{sfn|Buckley|2005|p=234}}<ref name=\"Light RS\">{{cite web |last1=Light |first1=Alan |title=How David Bowie Brought Thin White Duke to Life on 'Station to Station' |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/how-david-bowie-brought-thin-white-duke-to-life-on-station-to-station-125797/ |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=14 March 2020 |date=23 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181227040904/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/how-david-bowie-brought-thin-white-duke-to-life-on-station-to-station-125797/ |archive-date=27 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*[[David Bowie]] \u2013 lead vocals, acoustic guitar, production\n*[[Earl Slick]] \u2013 lead guitar\n*[[Carlos Alomar]] \u2013 rhythm guitar\n*[[George Murray (musician)|George Murray]] \u2013 bass\n*[[Roy Bittan]] \u2013 piano, [[electronic organ|organ]]\n*[[Dennis Davis]] \u2013 drums\n*[[Warren Peace]] \u2013 [[percussion]], backing vocals\n*[[Harry Maslin]] \u2013 [[melodica]], production\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n;Sources\n*{{cite book |last=Buckley |first=David |year=2000 |origyear=1999 |title=Strange Fascination \u2013 David Bowie: The Definitive Story |location=London |publisher=[[Virgin Group|Virgin]] |isbn=0-7535-0457-X |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Buckley |first=David |year=2005 |origyear=1999 |title=Strange Fascination \u2013 David Bowie: The Definitive Story |location=London |publisher=Virgin |isbn=978-0-75351-002-5 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Carr |first1=Roy|authorlink1=Roy Carr |last2=Murray |first2=Charles Shaar| authorlink2=Charles Shaar Murray |year=1981 |title=Bowie: An Illustrated Record |publisher=[[Eel Pie Publishing]] |isbn=978-0-38077-966-6|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Doggett |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Doggett |year=2012 |title=The Man Who Sold the World: David Bowie and the 1970s |publisher=[[HarperCollins|HarperCollins Publishers]] |isbn=978-0-06-202466-4 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Pegg |first=Nicholas |authorlink=Nicholas Pegg |year=2004 |origyear=2000 |title=The Complete David Bowie |location=London |publisher=Reynolds & Hearn |isbn=1-903111-73-0|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pegg |first=Nicholas |title=The Complete David Bowie |publisher=[[Titan Books]] |edition=7th |location=London |year=2016 |isbn=978-1-78565-365-0 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Wilcken |first=Hugo |year=2005 |title=Low |location=New York, London |publisher=[[Continuum International Publishing Group|Continuum]] |isbn=0-8264-1684-5|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|david-bowie|station-to-station}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{David Bowie singles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Station To Station (Song)}}\n[[Category:British disco songs]]\n[[Category:British progressive rock songs]]\n[[Category:David Bowie songs]]\n[[Category:1976 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by David Bowie]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by David Bowie]]\n", "name_user": "Ian Rose", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLyrics:Doggett introduced/linked earlier now -- more later", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Station_to_Station_(song)"}
{"title_page": "Structure of the Italian Army in 1989", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\nThe '''[[Order of Battle]] of the [[Italian Army]] at the end of 1989''' is given below.\n\nThe article is based on the 1984 publication of the Italian Army's order of battle by the Institute for Disarmament, Development and Peace (Istituto di ricerche per il disarmo, lo sviluppo e la pace (IRDISP) in [[Rome]] (a think thank of the [[Radical Party (Italy)|Radical Party]]). The published order of battle, down to company level, can be found at the Radical's Radio's website ([https://web.archive.org/web/20171201031533/http://www.radioradicale.it/exagora/lesercito-italiano-3-quello-che-i-russi-gia-sanno-e-gli-italiani-non-devono-sapere Link]). The structure was then adapted with information from the Italian Army's website and its units' histories listed there. Additionally the following website was used, which lists every Order of Battle for Italy's armies from 1553 to 1997, [http://xoomer.virgilio.it/ramius//Militaria/L'ESERCITO_DAL_1553_AL_1996.html Link]. Specifically the Order of Battle after the 1986 reform was used, which was then corrected and expanded with the Italian Army's website information.\n\n== Graphic of the Italian Army in 1989 ==\n\n[[File:Italy Army - 1989.png|thumb|center|1200px|Structure of the Italian Army in 1989 (click image to enlarge)]]\n\n== Army General Staff ==\nThe Army General Staff in Rome oversaw all Italian Army units. However in the event of war the three Corps' in Northern Italy would have come under command of [[NATO]]'s [[Allied Land Forces Southern Europe]] (LANDSOUTH) Command in [[Verona]].\n\n=== 3rd Army Corps ===\n[[File:Italian Army - 3rd Army Corps - 1989.png|thumb|right|560px|Structure of the 3rd Army Corps in 1989 (click image to enlarge)]]\n\n* '''[[3rd Army Corps (Italy)|3rd Army Corps]]''', in [[Milan]]:\n** 3rd Army Corps Command Unit, in Milan\n** '''Artillery Command''', in [[Vercelli]]\n*** [[File:CoA mil ITA rgt artiglieria cav.png|25px]] Horse Artillery Regiment, in Milan\n**** Command Battery, in Milan\n**** 1st Self-propelled Field Artillery Group \"[[Gioacchino Bellezza]]\", ([[M109 howitzer|M109 155mm]] [[Self-propelled artillery|self-propelled howitzers]]), in Milan\n**** 2nd Self-propelled Field Artillery Group \"[[Sergio Bresciani]]\", (M109 155mm self-propelled howitzers), in Cremona\n**** 3rd Heavy Field Artillery Group (Reserve), (M59 155/45 towed howitzers), in Cremona\n**** 3rd Battery, 30th Artillery Specialists Group \"[[Brianza]]\", in Milan\n*** [[File:CoA mil ITA rgt artiglieria 131.png|25px]] 131st Heavy Field Artillery Group \"Vercelli\", in Vercelli, ([[FH70|FH70 155mm]] towed [[howitzer]]s)\n*** [[File:CoA mil ITA grp artiglieria 205.png|25px]] 205th Heavy Field Artillery Group \"[[Lomellina]]\", in Vercelli, (FH70 155mm towed howitzers)\n*** 11th Light Anti-aircraft Artillery Group \"[[Falcon|Falco]]\" (Reserve), in Vercelli\n*** [[File:CoA mil ITA rgt art pes cam 05.png|25px]] 12th Artillery Specialists Group \"[[Biella]]\", in Vercelli\n*** 30th Artillery Specialist Group \"Brianza\" (Reserve)<ref>With one permanent operational battery attached to the Horse Artillery Regiment in Milan, see above.</ref>, in Milan\n** '''Engineer Command''', in [[Novara]]\n*** [[File:CoA mil ITA rgt genio 10.png|25px]] 3rd Pioneer Battalion \"[[Lake Como|Lario]]\", in [[Pavia]]\n*** [[File:CoA mil ITA btg genio 131.png|25px]] 131st Pioneer Battalion \"[[Ticino (river)|Ticino]]\", in [[Bellinzago Novarese]]\n** '''Signal Command''', in Milan\n*** [[File:CoA mil ITA rgt trasmissioni 01.png|25px]] 3rd Signal Battalion \"[[Spl\u00fcgen Pass|Spluga]]\", in Milan\n*** [[File:CoA mil ITA btg trasmissioni 231.png|25px]] 231st Signal Battalion \"[[Simplon Pass|Sempione]]\", in Novara\n** '''Light Aviation Command''', at [[Bresso Airport|Bresso Air Base]]\n*** 23rd Recon Helicopters Squadrons Group \"[[Eridanus (constellation)|Eridano]]\", at Bresso Air Base\n**** 423rd Recon Helicopter Squadron ([[Bell 206|AB-206]])\n**** 461st Recon Helicopter Squadron ([[Bell 206|AB-206]])\n**** 462nd Recon Helicopter Squadron ([[Bell 206|AB-206]])\n*** 53rd Multirole Helicopters Squadrons Group \"[[Cassiopeia (constellation)|Cassiopea]]\", at Bresso Air Base\n**** 531st Multirole Helicopter Squadron ([[Bell 204/205|AB-205]]) \n**** 532nd Multirole Helicopter Squadron ([[Bell 204/205|AB-205]])\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA btg logistico 33.png|25px]] 33rd Logistic Maneuver Battalion \"[[Sant'Ambrogio|Ambrosiano]]\", in Novara\n\n==== Armored Brigade \"Centauro\" ====\n* [[File:CoA mil ITA arm bde centauro.png|30px]] '''[[Armored Brigade \"Centauro\"]]''', in [[Novara]]\n** Command and Signal Unit \"[[Centaur|Centauro]]\", in Novara\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA rgt carri 031.png|25px]] 1st Tank Battalion \"[[Gold Medal of Military Valor|M.O.]] Cracco\", in [[Bellinzago Novarese]], ([[Leopard 1|Leopard 1A2]] [[main battle tank]]s)\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA rgt carri 131.png|25px]] 101st Tank Battalion \"M.O. Zappal\u00e0\", in Bellinzago Novarese, (Leopard 1A2 main battle tanks)\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA btg bersaglieri 28.png|25px]] [[28th Bersaglieri Battalion \"Oslavia\"]], in Bellinzago Novarese, ([[M113 armored personnel carrier|VCC-2]] [[armored personnel carrier]]s)\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA grp artiglieria 009.png|25px]] 9th Self-propelled Field Artillery Group \"[[Brenner Pass|Brennero]]\", in [[Vercelli]], ([[M109 howitzer|M109 155mm]] [[Self-propelled artillery|self-propelled howitzers]])\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA btg logistico centauro.png|25px]] Logistic Battalion \"Centauro\", in Bellinzago Novarese\n** Anti-tank Company \"Centauro\", in Bellinzago Novarese\n** Engineer Company \"Centauro\", in Novara\n\n==== Mechanized Brigade \"Goito\" ====\n* [[File:CoA mil ITA Bersaglieri bde Goito.png|30px]] '''[[Mechanized Brigade \"Goito\"]]''' in [[Milan]]\n** Command and Signal Unit \"[[Battle of Goito|Goito]]\", in Milan\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA btg carri 004.png|25px]] 4th Tank Battalion \"[[Gold Medal of Military Valor|M.O.]] Passalacqua\", in [[Solbiate Olona]], ([[Leopard 1|Leopard 1A2]] [[main battle tank]]s)\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA rgt bersaglieri 06.png|25px]] 6th Bersaglieri Battalion \"[[Battle of Palestro|Palestro]]\", in [[Turin]], ([[M113 armored personnel carrier|VCC-2]] [[armored personnel carrier]]s)\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA rgt bersaglieri 07.png|25px]] 10th Bersaglieri Battalion \"[[Battle of Bezzecca|Bezzecca]]\", in Solbiate Olona, (VCC-2 armored personnel carriers)\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA rgt bersaglieri 03.png|25px]] 18th Bersaglieri Battalion \"Poggio Scanno\", in Milan, (VCC-2 armored personnel carriers)\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA gr artiglieria 003.png|25px]] 3rd Self-propelled Field Artillery Group \"[[Skirmish of Pastrengo (1848)|Pastrengo]]\", in [[Vercelli]], ([[M109 howitzer|M109 155mm]] [[Self-propelled artillery|self-propelled howitzers]])\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA btg logistico goito.png|25px]] Logistic Battalion \"Goito\", in [[Monza]]\n** Anti-tank Company \"Goito\", in Turin\n** Engineer Company \"Goito\", in [[Novara]]\n\n==== Mechanized Brigade \"Legnano\" ====\n* [[File:CoA mil ITA mec bde legnano.png|30px]] '''[[Legnano Mechanized Brigade|Mechanized Brigade \"Legnano\"]]''', in [[Bergamo]]\n** Command and Signal Unit \"[[Battle of Legnano|Legnano]]\", in Bergamo\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA btg carri 020.png|25px]] 20th Tank Battalion \"[[Gold Medal of Military Valor|M.O.]] Pentimalli\", in [[Legnano]], ([[Leopard 1|Leopard 1A2]] [[main battle tank]]s)\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA rgt bersaglieri 02.png|25px]] 2nd Bersaglieri Battalion \"Governolo\", in Legnano, ([[M113 armored personnel carrier|VCC-2]] [[armored personnel carrier]]s)\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA rgt fanteria 067.png|25px]] 67th Mechanized Infantry Battalion \"Montelungo\", in [[Monza]], (M113 armored personnel carriers)\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA btg fanteria 068.png|25px]] 68th Mechanized Infantry Battalion \"[[Palermo]]\", in Bergamo, (M113 armored personnel carriers, disbanded on 30 November 1989)\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA gr artiglieria 011.png|25px]] 11th Field Artillery Group \"[[Montferrat|Monferrato]]\", in [[Cremona]], ([[M114 155 mm howitzer|M114 155mm]] towed [[howitzer]]s)\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA btg logistico legnano.png|25px]] Logistic Battalion \"Legnano\", in [[Presezzo]]\n** Anti-tank Company \"Legnano\", in Monza\n** Engineer Company \"Legnano\", in Bergamo\n\n==== Mechanized Brigade \"Trieste\" ====\n* [[File:CoA mil ITA mec bde Trieste.png|30px]] '''[[Trieste Mechanized Brigade|Mechanized Brigade \"Trieste\"]]''', in [[Bologna]]\n** Command and Signal Unit \"[[Trieste]]\", in Bologna\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA btg carri 011.png|25px]] 11th Tank Battalion \"[[Gold Medal of Military Valor|M.O.]] Calzecchi\", in [[Ozzano dell'Emilia]], ([[Leopard 1|Leopard 1A2]] [[main battle tank]]s)\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA btg fanteria 037.png|25px]] 37th Mechanized Infantry Battalion \"[[Ravenna]]\", in Bologna, ([[M113 armored personnel carrier|VCC-2]] [[armored personnel carrier]]s)\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA btg fanteria 040.png|25px]] 40th Mechanized Infantry Battalion \"Bologna\", in Bologna, (VCC-2 armored personnel carriers)\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA rgt fanteria 066.png|25px]] 66th Mechanized Infantry Battalion \"[[Valtellina]]\", in [[Forl\u00ec]], (VCC-2 armored personnel carriers)\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA rgt artiglieria 021.png|25px]] 21st Artillery Group \"[[Romagna]]\", in Bologna, ([[M114 155 mm howitzer|M114 155mm]] towed [[howitzer]]s)\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA btg logistico trieste.png|25px]] Logistic Battalion \"Trieste\", in [[Budrio]]\n** Anti-tank Company \"Trieste\", in Bologna\n** Engineer Company \"Trieste\", in Bologna\n\n==== Mechanized Brigade \"Brescia\" ====\n* [[File:CoA mil ITA mec bde Brescia.png|30px]] '''[[Mechanized Brigade \"Brescia\"]]''', in [[Brescia]]\n** [[File:CoA mil ITA rpt comando e trasmissioni Brescia.png|25px]] Command and Signal Unit \"Brescia\